// nodule: compiler.semcore
// @version: 0.1.0
// @license: MIT
// @authors: Tyler Zervas
// @since: 2026-07-06
// @updated: 2026-07-09
// @summary: Self-hosted L1 semantic-core — a PARTIAL FIRST INCREMENT (M-740 Stage 5, increment 1;
//   DN-26 SS7.3 row 5 / SS9 flag-1). The full semcore is a 9-file strongly-connected component
//   (checkty/elab/eval/mono/fuse/decision/usefulness/grade/affine, ~16.7k Rust lines) that is ONE
//   nodule by design (DN-26 SS9 flag-1). This increment lands only the TRACTABLE sub-core that
//   depends on checkty's TYPES but not its checking LOGIC or the evaluator:
//     IN this increment  — the type vocabulary (Ty/Width/DataInfo/CtorInfo, mirroring
//       crates/mycelium-l1/src/checkty.rs's declarations only, none of its ~7k lines of checking
//       logic), the Maranget usefulness/decision-tree pipeline (usefulness.rs + decision.rs, 623
//       Rust lines), the static affine use-once tracker (affine.rs, 230 Rust lines), and the
//       static guarantee-grading pass (grade.rs, 474 Rust lines).
//     INCREMENT 2 (M-1007, appended below) — checkty.rs's four PURE type-algebra leaves
//       (has_var / type_head / subst_ty / param_subst), the substitution primitives the checker /
//       elaborator / monomorphizer build on. Still NONE of checkty's checking LOGIC — these are
//       leaf `Ty`-transformers ported ahead of the entangled core (each live-oracle-differentialed).
//     M-1013 STEP 5 (appended below) — register_types/register_traits/register_instances (STEP 3)
//       and resolve_imports (STEP 4) already landed the "registration"/"resolution" halves of
//       checkty.rs's declaration pass; this step ports register_nodule_decls itself (checkty.rs
//       1340-1401) plus its two small pure prerequisites — checkty.rs::prelude (the `Bool` seed) and
//       fuse.rs's F-A1 slice ONLY (`fuse::{TRAIT_NAME, prelude}`, fuse.rs 58-84 — a plain data-shaping
//       fn with no `eval::Evaluator` dependency, unlike F-A2's `check_fuse_laws`, which stays
//       deferred below). This CLOSES the STEP-4-landing FLAG that called `register_nodule_decls`
//       "entangled" — the entanglement was with `check_fuse_laws`, not `fuse::prelude`.
//     M-1013 eval PR-1 (appended below) — the FIRST eval.rs fragment: the Data/Ctor/Ident/Tuple/
//       Wildcard fraction of `Evaluator::try_match` (eval.rs 2005-2079), which is separable from
//       the CEK work-stack machine (`run_machine`/`eval_step`/`apply_frame`) and needs only the
//       already-ported `DataInfo`/`CtorInfo`/`types_lookup` registry. `Pattern::Lit` (kernel-`Value`
//       equality) stays OUT of scope, honestly refused (FLAG-semcore-35) — see `lval_try_match`.
//       This does NOT close the "eval.rs deferred" line below: the CEK machine itself (the bulk of
//       eval.rs, ~2k Rust lines) remains unported and is a DIFFERENT, much larger undertaking.
//     DEFERRED (NOT in this increment) — fuse.rs's F-A2 `check_fuse_laws` (RUNS `eval::Evaluator`,
//       which is not ported; its own `enumerate_finite_domain` also constructs `eval::L1Value`),
//       checkty.rs's checking LOGIC (~7k lines), elab.rs, eval.rs's CEK machine (`Evaluator::call`/
//       `run_machine`/`eval_step`/`apply_frame`/`enter_call`/`app_dispatch` and the rest of the
//       Env/PrimRegistry/SwapEngine-entangled core — the `try_match` fragment above is the one
//       exception), mono.rs (the heavy entangled core, ~15k lines total across these), the
//       whole-program L0-output differential, and the `cargo-mutants` witness.
//       These are FEASIBILITY-GATED on M-986 (the evaluator
//       elides only bare-body tail calls — no in-language loop today exceeds the 4096-depth
//       budget, `parse.myc`'s own FLAG-parse-11 finding) and M-987 (~n^3 L1-eval cost): a
//       self-hosted typechecker/elaborator run INSIDE the L1 evaluator over a whole program almost
//       certainly cannot complete at today's cost model. This is a REAL OPEN QUESTION for the
//       maintainer (widen kernel TCO vs. reduce eval cost vs. lean on AOT) — stated plainly, never
//       silently narrowed (G2/VR-5).
//
// Representation choices/deviations (each deliberate, honest, DOCUMENTED — VR-5/G2):
//
// FLAG-semcore-1 (self-contained; a TRIMMED copy of ast.myc's type vocabulary, not the whole
// file — M-982). Grading (grade.rs) walks the full `Expr` family, so this nodule copies in every
// AST type `Expr`/`FnDecl` transitively reference (Vis, Path, Paradigm, Scalar, Sparsity,
// AmbientParams, Strength, WidthRef, ParamKind, TraitRef, TypeParam, EffectBudget, FnSig, Param,
// TypeRef, BaseType, ExecutionMode, FnDecl, Literal, Pattern, Arm, Hypha, Expr) verbatim from
// `lib/compiler/ast.myc` — SAME spellings, SAME field order, so it stays diffable against that
// canonical source. Whole-program / item-level surface forms (TypeDecl, TraitDecl, ImplDecl,
// ViaDecl, ObjectDecl, InherentImplDecl, LowerRhs, LowerDecl, DeriveDecl, Item, Nodule, Phylum,
// UsePath, Ctor) are OMITTED — this increment grades individual `FnDecl` bodies, never a whole
// nodule/phylum, so those forms are out of scope. Accessor helpers ast.myc defines but this file
// never calls (e.g. `typeref_base`, `hypha_forage`, `fnsig_params`) are likewise omitted — the
// FIELD is still declared (so the type is fully structural), only the unused accessor fn is
// dropped. `ast.myc` remains the one canonical source; if a later increment needs a dropped
// piece, re-copy it from there (or, once cross-nodule execution lands — FLAG-token-4's tracked
// gap — `use compiler.ast` directly instead of copying).
//
// FLAG-semcore-2 (flat-namespace prefix scheme for the NEW checkty-vocabulary families). This
// nodule's copied AST types share ONE flat constructor namespace with several BRAND NEW families
// (`Ty`, `Width`, `DataInfo`/`CtorInfo`, `Pat`, `Head`, `Tree`, `Slot`, `UseOutcome`) — every bare
// name was diffed against every other family and against the copied ast.myc spellings (the
// FLAG-ast-5 discipline, generalized). Disjoint prefixes:
//   `Ty`   (the checked type, checkty.rs::Ty — distinct from ast.myc's surface `BaseType`, whose
//           OWN `Vsa`/`KwSubstrate` bare spellings this family must not collide with):
//           TyBinary/TyTernary/TyDense/TyVsa/TyData/TySubstrate/TySeq/TyBytes/TyFloat/TyVar/TyFn.
//   `Wd`   (checkty.rs::Width — distinct from ast.myc's surface `WidthRef`, whose OWN `WLit`/
//           `WName` bare spellings this family must not collide with): WdLit/WdVar.
//   `CI`/`DI` (CtorInfo/DataInfo record wrappers — unique, no collision).
//   `Mp`   (usefulness.rs/decision.rs's `Pat` — the MATRIX pattern, distinct from ast.myc's own
//           already-P-prefixed surface `Pattern` family (`PWildcard`/`PLit`/`PCtor`/…) and from
//           `Expr::Lit`): MpWild/MpCtor/MpLit.
//   `Hd`   (decision.rs's `Head` — distinct from `Mp`'s tags): HdCtor/HdLit.
//   `Tree`'s own `Leaf`/`Fail`/`Switch` and affine's `Skip`/`Live`/`Moved`/`NotAffine`/`FirstUse`/
//   `DoubleUse` are each checked against every other family here and against the full copied AST
//   set; none collide, so they stay BARE (documented, not merely assumed).
//
// FLAG-semcore-3 (recursion-depth budgets restated as an explicit threaded `depth: Binary{32}`
// parameter — the parse.myc FLAG-parse-7 / `enter_depth` convention, reused verbatim in shape).
// Rust's `RecursionBudget`/`BudgetError` (usefulness.rs, decision.rs, grade.rs) becomes a plain
// `depth: Binary{32}` argument threaded down through `useful_budgeted`/`compile_rows`/`grade`,
// charged by one shared `enter_depth` at the SAME 4096 ceiling as `checkty::MAX_CHECK_DEPTH` /
// `parse.myc::max_expr_depth`. The over-budget error is a plain `Bytes` message here, not a
// structured `BudgetError` enum — a real (harmless) narrowing: nothing in this increment's
// differential needs to distinguish "budget exceeded" from any other refusal kind.
//
// FLAG-semcore-4 (`BTreeMap<String, _>` -> ordered `Vec[Pair[Bytes, _]]` assoc list + linear
// lookup — the ast.myc FLAG-ast-6 convention). No map primitive is available self-contained
// (M-982); the type REGISTRY (`Vec[DataInfo]`, looked up by `types_lookup`) and the grading pass's
// function environment (`FnEnv = Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]]`, looked up by `fnenv_lookup`) are both
// ordered association lists. A real, documented narrowing versus a real `BTreeMap`: nothing here
// enforces key uniqueness — the caller must not construct a duplicate-keyed list (same caveat
// ast.myc's own `EffectBudget` narrowing already carries).
//
// FLAG-semcore-5 (usefulness.rs's `SpecializeRow` trait is NOT ported as a language-level
// trait/dictionary). Rust shares ONE `specialize_ctor`/`specialize_lit` implementation across the
// bare-matrix row (`Vec<Pat>`) and the decision-tree row (`Row`, which additionally carries an arm
// index) via that trait (M-641, DRY). This partial increment instead has TWO small, faithfully
// duplicated pairs — `specialize_ctor_pat`/`specialize_lit_pat` (bare `Vec[Pat]` rows, used by
// `useful`) and `specialize_ctor_row`/`specialize_lit_row` (`DRow`-carrying rows, used by
// `compile`) — rather than modeling a generic dictionary-passing scheme in a first increment
// (KISS/YAGNI/KC-3). Same algorithm, same behavior, just not code-shared via a trait — a structural
// (not semantic) narrowing.
//
// FLAG-semcore-6 (affine.rs's `Tracker` — a Rust `Cell`/`RefCell` interior-mutable OBJECT — is
// restated as a plain VALUE, `Vec[Slot]`, threaded explicitly by the caller; no wrapper "Tracker"
// type is declared at all). This is the value-semantics collapse the FLAG-semcore-3 depth-threading
// convention already established for depth budgets, applied to affine state. The
// inert/active split, `seeded`/`inert` constructors, and the `push`/`pop`/`truncate`/`snapshot`/
// `restore`/`merge_alt` CHECKER-INTEGRATION wiring are NOT ported — those exist only to mirror
// `crate::checkty::Cx`'s OWN scope stack, which this increment's un-ported checking logic does not
// have. Only the PURE state-transition core is ported: `slot_for_ty`, `slots_seeded`,
// `slots_use_at`, `union_merge_into` (renamed `merge_slot`/`union_merge_into` here, same names as
// the Rust helper) — everything this increment's differential actually exercises.
//
// FLAG-semcore-7 (`UseSite`/`Occurrence` Rust newtypes dropped; bare `Binary{32}`/
// `Vec[Binary{32}]` used directly). Both are already-transparent aliases on the Rust side
// (`UseSite { ordinal: u32 }` is used only as a plain ordinal carrier; `pub(crate) type Occurrence
// = Vec<usize>;` is a literal type alias) — a deliberate simplification, not a narrowing.
//
// FLAG-semcore-8 (decision.rs's column-selection heuristic simplified to scan only the FIRST row
// for its first non-wildcard column, rather than Rust's whole-matrix scan
// `rows.iter().any(|r| !matches!(r.pats[i], Wild))`). Still CORRECT: the caller only reaches
// column selection after the base-case guard has already established the first row is not
// all-wildcard, so the first row alone is guaranteed to have a non-wildcard column. This MAY
// produce a less book-optimal tree SHAPE than the oracle's whole-matrix scan when a later row
// would have picked a different (possibly more compact) column — a shape-fidelity narrowing, not
// a correctness one (both trees still route every input to the same arm).
//
// FLAG-semcore-9 (grade.rs's whole-program `check_guarantees` driver — the `own_names`/
// `impl_methods` iteration over the checker's resolved fn table — is NOT ported). Only the
// per-body walk is: `grade`/`grade_expr` and its helpers (`grade_match`, `grade_app`, `meet_all`,
// `bind_pattern`, `require`, `ret_grade`, `param_grade`), plus a thin `grade_fn_body` entry point
// this increment's differential drives directly. The whole-program driver needs the type
// checker's OWN resolved-fn-table wiring (own vs. imported, canonical resolved bodies) — out of
// scope for a partial increment that ports no checkty checking logic.
//
// FLAG-semcore-10 — RESOLVED (was: a REAL, NEWLY-SURFACED finding — Rust module-private
// visibility blocks a live-oracle differential for THIS increment, unlike every prior Stage).
// Original finding, kept for the record (append-only — VR-5/G2): `usefulness.rs`, `decision.rs`,
// `affine.rs`, and `grade.rs` are declared `pub(crate) mod` / plain `mod` in
// `crates/mycelium-l1/src/lib.rs` (`mod affine;`, `pub(crate) mod decision;`, `mod grade;`,
// `pub(crate) mod usefulness;`) — UNLIKE `ast.rs`/`token.rs`/`parse.rs`/`nodule.rs` (all `pub mod`,
// with the port-relevant items re-exported `pub`). An EXTERNAL integration-test crate
// (`crates/mycelium-l1/tests/*.rs`, where `compiler_stage5_semcore.rs` originally lived) sees only
// the crate's PUBLIC API surface, so it could not call `usefulness::useful`, `decision::compile`,
// `affine`'s `Tracker`/`use_at`, or `grade::check_guarantees` directly, and fell back to a
// HAND-DERIVED expected value per case — graded `Empirical`, weaker than every other stage's
// live-oracle posture.
//
// RESOLUTION (this leaf): the gate moved IN-CRATE, from `crates/mycelium-l1/tests/
// compiler_stage5_semcore.rs` to `crates/mycelium-l1/src/tests/compiler_stage5_semcore.rs`
// (`#[cfg(test)] mod tests;`, the established `src/tests/*.rs` white-box convention — precedent:
// `src/tests/{usefulness,decision,affine}.rs`). From there every `pub(crate)` item across all four
// modules IS reachable (`crate::usefulness::useful`, `crate::decision::{compile,
// has_reachable_fail}`, `crate::affine::{Tracker, union_merge_into}`), with ZERO visibility change
// to the trusted logic modules — only the test module (+ its one `mod` line in `src/tests/mod.rs`)
// was added. Every usefulness/decision/affine case now calls the real Rust oracle fn directly and
// asserts the `.myc` port's verdict against ITS live-computed result (never a hand-typed literal).
//
// The grade legs needed one more step (**FLAG-semcore-10-b**, a NEW finding this leaf surfaced):
// the only `pub(crate)` entry point into `grade.rs` is `check_guarantees`, which returns
// `Result<(), CheckError>` — pass/fail against a function's OWN declared return demand, not the
// raw computed `Strength`. The per-body walk that computes the raw grade (`Gx::grade`,
// `check_fn_grades`) carries NO visibility modifier, so it stays private to `crate::grade` even
// from this in-crate sibling test module. The exact live grade is recovered by PROBING: since
// `Strength::satisfies` is monotone in the demand and the lattice is 4 total-ordered levels
// (`Exact ⊐ Proven ⊐ Empirical ⊐ Declared`), re-checking the SAME body under a synthetic
// return-demand at each level (strongest first) and taking the first the body still satisfies
// recovers its exact grade — every bit sourced from a real `check_guarantees` call, never a
// fabricated constant. The two demand-VIOLATION cases need no probing (the failure is internal to
// an ascription/argument check, so `check_guarantees`'s `Err` is already the live verdict at any
// demand). Still FLAGGED UP for the maintainer/DN-26 owner: lifting `Gx`/`check_fn_grades` to
// `pub(crate)` would let a future revision skip the probing indirection and read the grade
// directly — Rust sources stay READ-ONLY in this leaf, so that visibility change is not made here.
//
// Net result: this increment's differential is now LIVE-ORACLE end to end (usefulness/decision/
// affine directly; grade via the documented probing indirection) — the DN-26 SS7.4 "checked
// against the live Rust oracle" contract every prior stage's differential relies on now holds
// here too, not merely `Empirical` hand-derivation.
nodule compiler.semcore;

// ── prelude (local; no cross-nodule import — FLAG-semcore-1 / M-982) ───────────────────────────
type Option[A] = Some(A) | None;
type Result[A, E] = Ok(A) | Err(E);
type Vec[A] = Nil | Cons(A, Vec[A]);
type Pair[A, B] = Pr(A, B);

// ── copied-in AST subset (verbatim spellings from lib/compiler/ast.myc — FLAG-semcore-1) ───────

// Vis: mirrors ast.myc::Vis (a field of `FnDecl`; grade never inspects its value).
type Vis = Private | Pub;

// Path: mirrors ast.myc::Path (a dotted path or bare name).
type Path = Pth(Vec[Bytes]);

fn path_segs(p: Path) => Vec[Bytes] =
  match p { Pth(segs) => segs };

// Paradigm: mirrors ast.myc::Paradigm (FLAG-ast-4 P-prefix, reused verbatim).
type Paradigm = PBinary | PTernary | PDense | PVsa;

// Scalar: mirrors ast.myc::Scalar (FLAG-ast-4 S-prefix, reused verbatim).
type Scalar = SF16 | SBf16 | SF32 | SF64;

// Sparsity: mirrors ast.myc::Sparsity (FLAG-ast-4 Sp-prefix, reused verbatim).
type Sparsity = SpDense | SpSparse(Binary{32});

// AmbientParams: mirrors ast.myc::AmbientParams (FLAG-ast-4/5 AP-prefix, reused verbatim).
type AmbientParams =
    APSize(Binary{32})
  | APDense(Binary{32}, Scalar)
  | APVsa(Bytes, Binary{32}, Sparsity);

// Strength: mirrors ast.myc::Strength (the guarantee-lattice tag; FLAG-ast-4 G-prefix, reused
// verbatim). Core to grade.rs's port — rank/meet/satisfies are all needed.
type Strength = GExact | GProven | GEmpirical | GDeclared;

fn strength_rank(s: Strength) => Binary{8} =
  match s {
    GDeclared => 0b0000_0000,
    GEmpirical => 0b0000_0001,
    GProven => 0b0000_0010,
    GExact => 0b0000_0011
  };

// strength_meet: the weaker (less-trusted) of the two grades (mirrors ast.myc::strength_meet).
fn strength_meet(a: Strength, b: Strength) => Strength =
  match lt(strength_rank(b), strength_rank(a)) {
    0b1 => b,
    _ => a
  };

// strength_satisfies: `actual.rank() >= demand.rank()` (mirrors ast.myc::strength_satisfies).
fn strength_satisfies(actual: Strength, demand: Strength) => Bool =
  match lt(strength_rank(actual), strength_rank(demand)) {
    0b1 => False,
    _ => True
  };

// WidthRef: mirrors ast.myc::WidthRef (a SURFACE width slot — distinct from checkty's own
// `Width` below, FLAG-semcore-2).
type WidthRef = WLit(Binary{32}) | WName(Bytes);

// ParamKind: mirrors ast.myc::ParamKind.
type ParamKind = PkType | PkWidth;

// TraitRef: mirrors ast.myc::TraitRef (a bound-position trait reference; field only, unused
// accessors dropped per FLAG-semcore-1).
type TraitRef = TRf(Bytes, Vec[TypeRef]);

// TypeParam: mirrors ast.myc::TypeParam (field only, unused accessors dropped).
type TypeParam = TP(Bytes, ParamKind, Vec[TraitRef]);

// EffectBudget: mirrors ast.myc::EffectBudget (FLAG-ast-6; field only).
type EffectBudget = EB(Bytes, Binary{64});

// FnSig: mirrors ast.myc::FnSig field-for-field. Only the 3 accessors grade.rs actually calls are
// kept (name, value_params, ret) — fnsig_params/fnsig_effects/fnsig_effect_budgets are unused here.
type FnSig = FS(Bytes, Vec[TypeParam], Vec[Param], TypeRef, Vec[Bytes], Vec[EffectBudget]);

fn fnsig_name(s: FnSig) => Bytes =
  match s { FS(n, _, _, _, _, _) => n };

fn fnsig_value_params(s: FnSig) => Vec[Param] =
  match s { FS(_, _, vp, _, _, _) => vp };

fn fnsig_ret(s: FnSig) => TypeRef =
  match s { FS(_, _, _, r, _, _) => r };

// Param: mirrors ast.myc::Param (a value parameter `name: type`).
type Param = Prm(Bytes, TypeRef);

fn param_name(p: Param) => Bytes =
  match p { Prm(n, _) => n };

fn param_ty(p: Param) => TypeRef =
  match p { Prm(_, t) => t };

// TypeRef / BaseType: mirror ast.myc::TypeRef / ast.myc::BaseType (mutually recursive — the
// checker's shell-first type registration resolves this regardless of declaration order, per
// ast.myc's own header note). Only `typeref_guarantee` is kept (grade never inspects the base).
type TypeRef = TR(BaseType, Option[Strength]);

fn typeref_guarantee(t: TypeRef) => Option[Strength] =
  match t { TR(_, g) => g };

// BaseType: mirrors ast.myc::BaseType verbatim (FLAG-ast-4/5 renames carried over unchanged —
// `Vsa`/`KwSubstrate` here are ast.myc's OWN surface spellings, distinct from this file's NEW
// `TyVsa`/`TySubstrate` checked-type family, FLAG-semcore-2).
type BaseType =
    KwBinary(WidthRef)
  | KwTernary(WidthRef)
  | KwDense(Binary{32}, Scalar)
  | Vsa(Bytes, Binary{32}, Sparsity)
  | KwSubstrate(Bytes)
  | KwSeq(TypeRef, Binary{32})
  | KwBytes
  | KwFloat
  | Named(Bytes, Vec[TypeRef])
  | Ambient(AmbientParams)
  | FnArrow(TypeRef, TypeRef)
  | Tuple(Vec[TypeRef]);

// ── register-family surface mirrors (M-1013 STEP 3, PR-1) ─────────────────────────────────────────
// Ctor: mirrors ast.rs::Ctor (a constructor name + its positional field TypeRefs). NEW ctor `Ct`
// (FLAG-semcore-2 prefix scheme — distinct from the surface `Kw*`/checked `Ty*` families and from the
// `CI` checked-ctor mirror below).
// M-1027 / DN-104: the 3rd field is the `sealed` (`priv`) flag — surface parity with ast.rs::Ctor.
// The checked `CtorInfo` (`CI`) mirror below does NOT carry it (the cross-nodule construction seal is
// enforced by the export-table layer, which is not ported to `.myc` — DN-104 §6 residual).
type Ctor = Ct(Bytes, Vec[TypeRef], Bool);

fn ct_name(c: Ctor) => Bytes =
  match c { Ct(n, _, _) => n };

fn ct_fields(c: Ctor) => Vec[TypeRef] =
  match c { Ct(_, f, _) => f };

// TypeDecl: mirrors ast.rs::TypeDecl field-for-field (vis, name, params, ctors — declaration order).
type TypeDecl = TD(Vis, Bytes, Vec[Bytes], Vec[Ctor]);

fn td_name(t: TypeDecl) => Bytes =
  match t { TD(_, n, _, _) => n };

fn td_params(t: TypeDecl) => Vec[Bytes] =
  match t { TD(_, _, p, _) => p };

fn td_ctors(t: TypeDecl) => Vec[Ctor] =
  match t { TD(_, _, _, c) => c };

// ExecutionMode: mirrors ast.myc::ExecutionMode (a field of `FnDecl`; unused by grade otherwise).
type ExecutionMode = Interpreted | Compiled;

// FnDecl: mirrors ast.myc::FnDecl field-for-field. Only `sig`/`body` accessors are kept.
type FnDecl = FD(Vis, Bool, Option[ExecutionMode], FnSig, Expr);

fn fndecl_sig(f: FnDecl) => FnSig =
  match f { FD(_, _, _, s, _) => s };

fn fndecl_body(f: FnDecl) => Expr =
  match f { FD(_, _, _, _, b) => b };

// Literal: mirrors ast.myc::Literal verbatim (FLAG-ast-4/5 renames carried over — `LBytes`/
// `LFloat`, FLAG-ast-8: no `#[non_exhaustive]` analog).
type Literal =
    Bin(Bytes)
  | Trit(Bytes)
  | Int(Binary{64})
  | AmbientInt(Paradigm, Binary{64})
  | List(Vec[Expr])
  | LBytes(Bytes)
  | Str(Bytes)
  | LFloat(Bytes);

// Pattern: mirrors ast.myc::Pattern verbatim (FLAG-ast-5 P-prefix throughout).
type Pattern =
    PWildcard
  | PLit(Literal)
  | PCtor(Bytes, Vec[Pattern])
  | PIdent(Bytes)
  | PTuple(Vec[Pattern])
  | POr(Vec[Pattern]);

// Arm: mirrors ast.myc::Arm (one `match` arm).
type Arm = Ar(Pattern, Expr);

fn arm_pattern(a: Arm) => Pattern =
  match a { Ar(p, _) => p };

fn arm_body(a: Arm) => Expr =
  match a { Ar(_, b) => b };

// Hypha: mirrors ast.myc::Hypha (only `body` accessor kept — grade never inspects `forage`).
type Hypha = Hy(Option[Expr], Expr);

fn hypha_body(h: Hypha) => Expr =
  match h { Hy(_, b) => b };

// Expr: mirrors ast.myc::Expr verbatim, field-for-field, same variant order.
// FLAG-semcore-37 / FLAG-try-3 (DN-102): `Wrapping` (M-791) and `Try` (`?`, M-1025) are REPRESENTED and
// traversed here (grade / collect_tuple_arities_expr / fvw all recurse into its child, mirroring
// `Consume`), but the self-hosted lexer/parser does not yet PRODUCE it (no `wrapping` keyword in
// token/lex; no parse rule) — surface parsing of `wrapping { e }` is deferred remaining work
// (never-silent, G2). The Rust reference frontend produces it (ast.rs::Expr::Wrapping).
type Expr =
    Let(Bytes, Option[TypeRef], Expr, Expr)
  | If(Expr, Expr, Expr)
  | Match(Expr, Vec[Arm])
  | For(Bytes, Expr, Bytes, Expr, Expr)
  | Swap(Expr, TypeRef, Path)
  | WithParadigm(Paradigm, Expr)
  | Wild(Expr)
  | Spore(Expr)
  | Wrapping(Expr)
  | Consume(Expr)
  // DN-102 (M-1025 ENB-2): the `?` try-operator node. REPRESENTED + traversed here (like
  // `Wrapping`/`Consume`), but the self-hosted lexer/parser does NOT yet PRODUCE it — the Rust
  // reference frontend does (ast.rs::Expr::Try), and `myc check` (Rust-backed) handles `?` in a
  // `.myc` file. Represented-not-produced (never-silent, G2; FLAG-try-3).
  | Try(Expr)
  | Colony(Vec[Hypha])
  | Lambda(Vec[Param], Expr)
  | App(Expr, Vec[Expr])
  | Fuse(Expr, Expr)
  | Reclaim(Expr, Expr)
  | Path(Path)
  | Lit(Literal)
  | Ascribe(Expr, TypeRef)
  | TupleLit(Vec[Expr]);

// ── small numeric helpers (Binary{32} zero/one/depth-ceiling literals) ──────────────────────────
fn zero32() => Binary{32} = 0b0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000;
fn one32() => Binary{32} = 0b0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0001;

// max_semcore_depth: SAME 4096 ceiling as checkty::MAX_CHECK_DEPTH / parse.myc::max_expr_depth
// (FLAG-semcore-3).
fn max_semcore_depth() => Binary{32} = 0b0000_0000_0000_0000_0001_0000_0000_0000;

// enter_depth: charge one level against the shared budget; `Err` on overflow (never a panic — the
// parse.myc FLAG-parse-7 convention, restated for this nodule's three budgeted recursions).
fn enter_depth(depth: Binary{32}) => Result[Binary{32}, Bytes] =
  let d2 = add_u(depth, one32()) in
  match lt(max_semcore_depth(), d2) {
    0b1 => Err("semcore: recursion budget exceeded (RFC-0041 SS4.7 restated; a never-silent refusal, never a host-stack overflow -- G2/VR-5)"),
    _ => Ok(d2)
  };

// names_contains: linear membership check over a `Vec[Bytes]` (used throughout for dedup /
// signature-completeness checks — the FLAG-semcore-4 assoc-list convention).
fn names_contains(names: Vec[Bytes], n: Bytes) => Bool =
  match names {
    Nil => False,
    Cons(h, t) => match bytes_eq(h, n) { 0b1 => True, _ => names_contains(t, n) }
  };

// ── Ty / Width / CtorInfo / DataInfo (checkty.rs's TYPE VOCABULARY only — FLAG-semcore-2) ──────

// Width: mirrors checkty.rs::Width (a `Binary{n}`/`Ternary{m}` width argument — concrete literal
// or abstract width variable).
type Width = WdLit(Binary{32}) | WdVar(Bytes);

// Ty: mirrors checkty.rs::Ty field-for-field (11 variants; `Box<Ty>` fields carry over as plain
// `Ty` per ast.myc's own shell-first-registration recursion note — no wrapper needed).
type Ty =
    TyBinary(Width)
  | TyTernary(Width)
  | TyDense(Binary{32}, Scalar)
  | TyVsa(Bytes, Binary{32}, Sparsity)
  | TyData(Bytes, Vec[Ty])
  | TySubstrate(Bytes)
  | TySeq(Ty, Binary{32})
  | TyBytes
  | TyFloat
  | TyVar(Bytes)
  | TyFn(Ty, Ty);

// CtorInfo: mirrors checkty.rs::CtorInfo (name, field types).
type CtorInfo = CI(Bytes, Vec[Ty]);

fn ci_name(c: CtorInfo) => Bytes =
  match c { CI(n, _) => n };

fn ci_fields(c: CtorInfo) => Vec[Ty] =
  match c { CI(_, f) => f };

// DataInfo: mirrors checkty.rs::DataInfo (name, type params, ctors in declaration order).
type DataInfo = DI(Bytes, Vec[Bytes], Vec[CtorInfo]);

fn di_name(d: DataInfo) => Bytes =
  match d { DI(n, _, _) => n };

fn di_ctors(d: DataInfo) => Vec[CtorInfo] =
  match d { DI(_, _, c) => c };

// types_lookup: the FLAG-semcore-4 ordered-assoc-list lookup standing in for
// `BTreeMap<String, DataInfo>`.
fn types_lookup(types: Vec[DataInfo], name: Bytes) => Option[DataInfo] =
  match types {
    Nil => None,
    Cons(d, rest) => match bytes_eq(di_name(d), name) {
      0b1 => Some(d),
      _ => types_lookup(rest, name)
    }
  };

// ── usefulness.rs port (Maranget U(P, q) — exhaustiveness/redundancy) ───────────────────────────

// Pat: mirrors usefulness.rs::Pat (the NORMALIZED matrix pattern — FLAG-semcore-2 Mp-prefix).
type Pat = MpWild | MpCtor(Bytes, Vec[Pat]) | MpLit(Bytes);

// pat_append / pat_len: small list helpers (non-tail, bounded by ONE row's arity — a handful of
// fields, never source length; mirrors nodule.myc::join_segs's count-bounded-recursion precedent).
fn pat_append(a: Vec[Pat], b: Vec[Pat]) => Vec[Pat] =
  match a { Nil => b, Cons(h, t) => Cons(h, pat_append(t, b)) };

fn pat_len(v: Vec[Pat]) => Binary{32} =
  match v { Nil => zero32(), Cons(_, t) => add_u(one32(), pat_len(t)) };

// ty_len: the arity-counting twin of `pat_len`, over a constructor's OWN field-type list
// (`Vec[Ty]`, not `Vec[Pat]` — a distinct monomorphic length fn since this language's total-fn
// discipline rules out a single generic one here, FLAG-semcore-5's KISS/YAGNI rationale extended).
fn ty_len(v: Vec[Ty]) => Binary{32} =
  match v { Nil => zero32(), Cons(_, t) => add_u(one32(), ty_len(t)) };

// wild_n: `n` fresh wildcards (bounded by a constructor's own arity).
fn wild_n(n: Binary{32}) => Vec[Pat] =
  match eq(n, zero32()) {
    0b1 => Nil,
    _ => Cons(MpWild, wild_n(sub_u(n, one32())))
  };

// ty_append: mirrors the Rust `ct2.extend_from_slice(...)` column-type splicing.
fn ty_append(a: Vec[Ty], b: Vec[Ty]) => Vec[Ty] =
  match a { Nil => b, Cons(h, t) => Cons(h, ty_append(t, b)) };

// ct_head / ct_tail: single-level column-type accessors (the `Nil` arm is an internal-invariant
// edge — never hit by a well-formed call where `col_types` is parallel to the query — a harmless
// sentinel value, not a silent behavior change to any reachable case).
fn ct_head(ts: Vec[Ty]) => Ty =
  match ts { Cons(h, _) => h, Nil => TyBytes };

fn ct_tail(ts: Vec[Ty]) => Vec[Ty] =
  match ts { Cons(_, t) => t, Nil => Nil };

// signature: the finite constructor signature of `ty`, or `None` if its domain is open
// (`Binary`/`Ternary` — mirrors usefulness.rs::signature; the trailing wildcard is the
// established `_ => …` idiom over a big-variant sum type, parse.myc's own `Tok` classifiers).
fn signature(ty: Ty, types: Vec[DataInfo]) => Option[DataInfo] =
  match ty { TyData(n, _) => types_lookup(types, n), _ => None };

// ctorinfo_fields_by_name / ctor_fields_of: the field types of constructor `c` (mirrors
// usefulness.rs::ctor_fields; empty if not found — a well-typed matrix never misses).
fn ctorinfo_fields_by_name(ctors: Vec[CtorInfo], c: Bytes) => Vec[Ty] =
  match ctors {
    Nil => Nil,
    Cons(ci, rest) => match bytes_eq(ci_name(ci), c) {
      0b1 => ci_fields(ci),
      _ => ctorinfo_fields_by_name(rest, c)
    }
  };

fn ctor_fields_of(ty: Ty, c: Bytes, types: Vec[DataInfo]) => Vec[Ty] =
  match signature(ty, types) {
    None => Nil,
    Some(d) => ctorinfo_fields_by_name(di_ctors(d), c)
  };

// specialize_ctor_pat / specialize_lit_pat: mirror usefulness.rs::specialize_ctor/specialize_lit
// over a BARE `Vec[Pat]` matrix (FLAG-semcore-5 — no shared `SpecializeRow` trait; this is the
// `useful`-side copy, `specialize_ctor_row`/`specialize_lit_row` below is the `compile`-side one).
fn specialize_ctor_pat(matrix: Vec[Vec[Pat]], c: Bytes, a: Binary{32}) => Vec[Vec[Pat]] =
  match matrix {
    Nil => Nil,
    Cons(row, rest) => match row {
      Nil => specialize_ctor_pat(rest, c, a),
      Cons(first, cols) => match first {
        MpCtor(n, subs) => match bytes_eq(n, c) {
          0b1 => Cons(pat_append(subs, cols), specialize_ctor_pat(rest, c, a)),
          _ => specialize_ctor_pat(rest, c, a)
        },
        MpWild => Cons(pat_append(wild_n(a), cols), specialize_ctor_pat(rest, c, a)),
        MpLit(_) => specialize_ctor_pat(rest, c, a)
      }
    }
  };

fn specialize_lit_pat(matrix: Vec[Vec[Pat]], k: Bytes) => Vec[Vec[Pat]] =
  match matrix {
    Nil => Nil,
    Cons(row, rest) => match row {
      Nil => specialize_lit_pat(rest, k),
      Cons(first, cols) => match first {
        MpLit(j) => match bytes_eq(j, k) {
          0b1 => Cons(cols, specialize_lit_pat(rest, k)),
          _ => specialize_lit_pat(rest, k)
        },
        MpWild => Cons(cols, specialize_lit_pat(rest, k)),
        MpCtor(_, _) => specialize_lit_pat(rest, k)
      }
    }
  };

// default_matrix: `D(P)` — rows headed by a wildcard, leading column dropped.
fn default_matrix(matrix: Vec[Vec[Pat]]) => Vec[Vec[Pat]] =
  match matrix {
    Nil => Nil,
    Cons(row, rest) => match row {
      Nil => default_matrix(rest),
      Cons(first, cols) => match first {
        MpWild => Cons(cols, default_matrix(rest)),
        MpCtor(_, _) => default_matrix(rest),
        MpLit(_) => default_matrix(rest)
      }
    }
  };

// head_ctors: the (deduped) constructor names appearing in the matrix's first column.
fn head_ctors(matrix: Vec[Vec[Pat]]) => Vec[Bytes] =
  match matrix {
    Nil => Nil,
    Cons(row, rest) => match row {
      Nil => head_ctors(rest),
      Cons(first, _) => match first {
        MpCtor(n, _) =>
          let tail = head_ctors(rest) in
          match names_contains(tail, n) { True => tail, False => Cons(n, tail) },
        MpWild => head_ctors(rest),
        MpLit(_) => head_ctors(rest)
      }
    }
  };

// ctors_all_present / find_missing_ctor: shared by usefulness AND decision's completeness checks.
fn ctors_all_present(ctors: Vec[CtorInfo], present: Vec[Bytes]) => Bool =
  match ctors {
    Nil => True,
    Cons(c, rest) => match names_contains(present, ci_name(c)) {
      True => ctors_all_present(rest, present),
      False => False
    }
  };

fn find_missing_ctor(ctors: Vec[CtorInfo], present: Vec[Bytes]) => Option[CtorInfo] =
  match ctors {
    Nil => None,
    Cons(c, rest) => match names_contains(present, ci_name(c)) {
      True => find_missing_ctor(rest, present),
      False => Some(c)
    }
  };

// missing_head: the witness head for an incomplete column (mirrors usefulness.rs's inline
// `missing.map_or(Pat::Wild, ...)`).
fn missing_head(m: Option[CtorInfo]) => Pat =
  match m { None => MpWild, Some(ci) => MpCtor(ci_name(ci), wild_n(ty_len(ci_fields(ci)))) };

// pat_split_at: split a witness vector at `n` (mirrors usefulness.rs's `w.split_off(a)`).
fn pat_split_at(w: Vec[Pat], n: Binary{32}) => Pair[Vec[Pat], Vec[Pat]] =
  match eq(n, zero32()) {
    0b1 => Pr(Nil, w),
    _ => match w {
      Nil => Pr(Nil, Nil),
      Cons(h, t) => match pat_split_at(t, sub_u(n, one32())) {
        Pr(hs, rest) => Pr(Cons(h, hs), rest)
      }
    }
  };

// rebuild_ctor / prepend: re-fold a witness whose first `a` elements are constructor `c`'s
// sub-witnesses (mirrors usefulness.rs verbatim).
fn rebuild_ctor(c: Bytes, a: Binary{32}, w: Vec[Pat]) => Vec[Pat] =
  match pat_split_at(w, a) { Pr(headpats, restpats) => Cons(MpCtor(c, headpats), restpats) };

fn prepend(head: Pat, rest: Vec[Pat]) => Vec[Pat] =
  Cons(head, rest);

// matrix_is_empty_to_witness: the `q.is_empty()` base case's witness (`Some([])` iff no row
// remains).
fn matrix_is_empty_to_witness(matrix: Vec[Vec[Pat]]) => Option[Vec[Pat]] =
  match matrix { Nil => Some(Nil), Cons(_, _) => None };

// useful: `U(P, q)` entry point — a fresh per-query budget (mirrors usefulness.rs::useful).
fn useful(types: Vec[DataInfo], matrix: Vec[Vec[Pat]], q: Vec[Pat], col_types: Vec[Ty])
    => Result[Option[Vec[Pat]], Bytes] =
  useful_budgeted(zero32(), types, matrix, q, col_types);

// useful_budgeted: the budget-charged recursion (mirrors usefulness.rs::useful_budgeted).
fn useful_budgeted(depth: Binary{32}, types: Vec[DataInfo], matrix: Vec[Vec[Pat]], q: Vec[Pat],
    col_types: Vec[Ty]) => Result[Option[Vec[Pat]], Bytes] =
  match enter_depth(depth) {
    Err(e) => Err(e),
    Ok(d2) => match q {
      Nil => Ok(matrix_is_empty_to_witness(matrix)),
      Cons(q0, qrest) => match q0 {
        MpCtor(c, subs) => useful_ctor(d2, types, matrix, qrest, col_types, c, subs),
        MpLit(k) => useful_lit(d2, types, matrix, qrest, col_types, k),
        MpWild => useful_wild(d2, types, matrix, qrest, col_types)
      }
    }
  };

fn useful_ctor(depth: Binary{32}, types: Vec[DataInfo], matrix: Vec[Vec[Pat]], qrest: Vec[Pat],
    col_types: Vec[Ty], c: Bytes, subs: Vec[Pat]) => Result[Option[Vec[Pat]], Bytes] =
  let a = pat_len(subs) in
  let m2 = specialize_ctor_pat(matrix, c, a) in
  let q2 = pat_append(subs, qrest) in
  let ct2 = ty_append(ctor_fields_of(ct_head(col_types), c, types), ct_tail(col_types)) in
  match useful_budgeted(depth, types, m2, q2, ct2) {
    Err(e) => Err(e),
    Ok(w) => match w {
      None => Ok(None),
      Some(witness) => Ok(Some(rebuild_ctor(c, a, witness)))
    }
  };

fn useful_lit(depth: Binary{32}, types: Vec[DataInfo], matrix: Vec[Vec[Pat]], qrest: Vec[Pat],
    col_types: Vec[Ty], k: Bytes) => Result[Option[Vec[Pat]], Bytes] =
  let m2 = specialize_lit_pat(matrix, k) in
  match useful_budgeted(depth, types, m2, qrest, ct_tail(col_types)) {
    Err(e) => Err(e),
    Ok(w) => match w {
      None => Ok(None),
      Some(witness) => Ok(Some(prepend(MpLit(k), witness)))
    }
  };

fn useful_wild(depth: Binary{32}, types: Vec[DataInfo], matrix: Vec[Vec[Pat]], qrest: Vec[Pat],
    col_types: Vec[Ty]) => Result[Option[Vec[Pat]], Bytes] =
  match signature(ct_head(col_types), types) {
    None => useful_wild_open(depth, types, matrix, qrest, col_types),
    Some(d) =>
      let present = head_ctors(matrix) in
      match ctors_all_present(di_ctors(d), present) {
        True => useful_wild_complete(depth, types, matrix, qrest, col_types, di_ctors(d)),
        False => useful_wild_incomplete(depth, types, matrix, qrest, col_types, d, present)
      }
  };

fn useful_wild_open(depth: Binary{32}, types: Vec[DataInfo], matrix: Vec[Vec[Pat]], qrest: Vec[Pat],
    col_types: Vec[Ty]) => Result[Option[Vec[Pat]], Bytes] =
  let m2 = default_matrix(matrix) in
  match useful_budgeted(depth, types, m2, qrest, ct_tail(col_types)) {
    Err(e) => Err(e),
    Ok(w) => match w {
      None => Ok(None),
      Some(witness) => Ok(Some(prepend(MpWild, witness)))
    }
  };

fn useful_wild_incomplete(depth: Binary{32}, types: Vec[DataInfo], matrix: Vec[Vec[Pat]],
    qrest: Vec[Pat], col_types: Vec[Ty], d: DataInfo, present: Vec[Bytes])
    => Result[Option[Vec[Pat]], Bytes] =
  let m2 = default_matrix(matrix) in
  match useful_budgeted(depth, types, m2, qrest, ct_tail(col_types)) {
    Err(e) => Err(e),
    Ok(w) => match w {
      None => Ok(None),
      Some(witness) =>
        let missing = find_missing_ctor(di_ctors(d), present) in
        Ok(Some(prepend(missing_head(missing), witness)))
    }
  };

fn useful_wild_complete(depth: Binary{32}, types: Vec[DataInfo], matrix: Vec[Vec[Pat]],
    qrest: Vec[Pat], col_types: Vec[Ty], ctors: Vec[CtorInfo]) => Result[Option[Vec[Pat]], Bytes] =
  match ctors {
    Nil => Ok(None),
    Cons(ci, rest) =>
      let a = ty_len(ci_fields(ci)) in
      let m2 = specialize_ctor_pat(matrix, ci_name(ci), a) in
      let q2 = pat_append(wild_n(a), qrest) in
      let ct2 = ty_append(ci_fields(ci), ct_tail(col_types)) in
      match useful_budgeted(depth, types, m2, q2, ct2) {
        Err(e) => Err(e),
        Ok(w) => match w {
          Some(witness) => Ok(Some(rebuild_ctor(ci_name(ci), a, witness))),
          None => useful_wild_complete(depth, types, matrix, qrest, col_types, rest)
        }
      }
  };

// render: render a witness pattern for a diagnostic (mirrors usefulness.rs::render; the b:/t:
// literal-key rewrite is SKIPPED here — cosmetic-only, not exercised by this increment's
// differential, which compares verdict SHAPE, not rendered text).
fn render(p: Pat) => Bytes =
  match p {
    MpWild => "_",
    MpLit(k) => k,
    MpCtor(n, subs) => match subs {
      Nil => n,
      Cons(_, _) => bytes_concat(n, bytes_concat("(", bytes_concat(render_list(subs), ")")))
    }
  };

fn render_list(subs: Vec[Pat]) => Bytes =
  match subs {
    Nil => "",
    Cons(h, t) => match t {
      Nil => render(h),
      Cons(_, _) => bytes_concat(render(h), bytes_concat(", ", render_list(t)))
    }
  };

// ── decision.rs port (Maranget decision-tree compilation) ───────────────────────────────────────

// Head: mirrors decision.rs::Head (FLAG-semcore-2 Hd-prefix).
type Head = HdCtor(Bytes, Binary{32}) | HdLit(Bytes);

// Tree: mirrors decision.rs::Tree (no Box needed — recursion note above; `Occurrence` inlined as
// `Vec[Binary{32}]`, FLAG-semcore-7).
type Tree = Leaf(Binary{32}) | Fail | Switch(Vec[Binary{32}], Vec[Pair[Head, Tree]], Option[Tree]);

// DRow: mirrors decision.rs::Row (a matrix row carrying its surface arm index).
type DRow = DRw(Vec[Pat], Binary{32});

fn drow_pats(r: DRow) => Vec[Pat] =
  match r { DRw(p, _) => p };

fn drow_arm(r: DRow) => Binary{32} =
  match r { DRw(_, a) => a };

// specialize_ctor_row / specialize_lit_row: the DRow-carrying twin of the `_pat` versions above
// (FLAG-semcore-5 — no shared trait; the arm index rides through unchanged).
fn specialize_ctor_row(rows: Vec[DRow], c: Bytes, a: Binary{32}) => Vec[DRow] =
  match rows {
    Nil => Nil,
    Cons(r, rest) => match drow_pats(r) {
      Nil => specialize_ctor_row(rest, c, a),
      Cons(first, cols) => match first {
        MpCtor(n, subs) => match bytes_eq(n, c) {
          0b1 => Cons(DRw(pat_append(subs, cols), drow_arm(r)), specialize_ctor_row(rest, c, a)),
          _ => specialize_ctor_row(rest, c, a)
        },
        MpWild =>
          Cons(DRw(pat_append(wild_n(a), cols), drow_arm(r)), specialize_ctor_row(rest, c, a)),
        MpLit(_) => specialize_ctor_row(rest, c, a)
      }
    }
  };

fn specialize_lit_row(rows: Vec[DRow], k: Bytes) => Vec[DRow] =
  match rows {
    Nil => Nil,
    Cons(r, rest) => match drow_pats(r) {
      Nil => specialize_lit_row(rest, k),
      Cons(first, cols) => match first {
        MpLit(j) => match bytes_eq(j, k) {
          0b1 => Cons(DRw(cols, drow_arm(r)), specialize_lit_row(rest, k)),
          _ => specialize_lit_row(rest, k)
        },
        MpWild => Cons(DRw(cols, drow_arm(r)), specialize_lit_row(rest, k)),
        MpCtor(_, _) => specialize_lit_row(rest, k)
      }
    }
  };

// default_rows: `D(P)` over `DRow`s.
fn default_rows(rows: Vec[DRow]) => Vec[DRow] =
  match rows {
    Nil => Nil,
    Cons(r, rest) => match drow_pats(r) {
      Nil => default_rows(rest),
      Cons(first, cols) => match first {
        MpWild => Cons(DRw(cols, drow_arm(r)), default_rows(rest)),
        MpCtor(_, _) => default_rows(rest),
        MpLit(_) => default_rows(rest)
      }
    }
  };

// row_all_wild: whether every column of one row is a wildcard.
fn row_all_wild(pats: Vec[Pat]) => Bool =
  match pats {
    Nil => True,
    Cons(p, rest) => match p {
      MpWild => row_all_wild(rest),
      MpCtor(_, _) => False,
      MpLit(_) => False
    }
  };

// first_nonwild_idx: the FLAG-semcore-8 simplified column-selection heuristic — the first
// non-wildcard column of ONE row (called on the first row only, which the caller has already
// established is not all-wild).
fn first_nonwild_idx(pats: Vec[Pat], idx: Binary{32}) => Binary{32} =
  match pats {
    Nil => idx,
    Cons(p, rest) => match p {
      MpWild => first_nonwild_idx(rest, add_u(idx, one32())),
      MpCtor(_, _) => idx,
      MpLit(_) => idx
    }
  };

// extract_occ / extract_ty / extract_pat: remove the `i`-th element, returning it paired with the
// remainder in original relative order (the building block of "rotate column `i` to the front").
fn extract_occ(v: Vec[Vec[Binary{32}]], i: Binary{32}) => Pair[Vec[Binary{32}], Vec[Vec[Binary{32}]]] =
  match eq(i, zero32()) {
    0b1 => match v { Cons(h, t) => Pr(h, t), Nil => Pr(Nil, Nil) },
    _ => match v {
      Cons(h, t) => match extract_occ(t, sub_u(i, one32())) { Pr(picked, rem) => Pr(picked, Cons(h, rem)) },
      Nil => Pr(Nil, Nil)
    }
  };

fn extract_ty(v: Vec[Ty], i: Binary{32}) => Pair[Ty, Vec[Ty]] =
  match eq(i, zero32()) {
    0b1 => match v { Cons(h, t) => Pr(h, t), Nil => Pr(TyBytes, Nil) },
    _ => match v {
      Cons(h, t) => match extract_ty(t, sub_u(i, one32())) { Pr(picked, rem) => Pr(picked, Cons(h, rem)) },
      Nil => Pr(TyBytes, Nil)
    }
  };

fn extract_pat(v: Vec[Pat], i: Binary{32}) => Pair[Pat, Vec[Pat]] =
  match eq(i, zero32()) {
    0b1 => match v { Cons(h, t) => Pr(h, t), Nil => Pr(MpWild, Nil) },
    _ => match v {
      Cons(h, t) => match extract_pat(t, sub_u(i, one32())) { Pr(picked, rem) => Pr(picked, Cons(h, rem)) },
      Nil => Pr(MpWild, Nil)
    }
  };

fn rotate_pat_to_front(v: Vec[Pat], i: Binary{32}) => Vec[Pat] =
  match extract_pat(v, i) { Pr(picked, rem) => Cons(picked, rem) };

fn rotate_rows_to_front(rows: Vec[DRow], i: Binary{32}) => Vec[DRow] =
  match rows {
    Nil => Nil,
    Cons(r, rest) =>
      Cons(DRw(rotate_pat_to_front(drow_pats(r), i), drow_arm(r)), rotate_rows_to_front(rest, i))
  };

// u32_append / occ_append / cases_append: small list-splicing helpers.
fn u32_append(a: Vec[Binary{32}], b: Vec[Binary{32}]) => Vec[Binary{32}] =
  match a { Nil => b, Cons(h, t) => Cons(h, u32_append(t, b)) };

fn occ_append(a: Vec[Vec[Binary{32}]], b: Vec[Vec[Binary{32}]]) => Vec[Vec[Binary{32}]] =
  match a { Nil => b, Cons(h, t) => Cons(h, occ_append(t, b)) };

fn cases_append(a: Vec[Pair[Head, Tree]], b: Vec[Pair[Head, Tree]]) => Vec[Pair[Head, Tree]] =
  match a { Nil => b, Cons(h, t) => Cons(h, cases_append(t, b)) };

// child_occ: the `a` child occurrences `occ0 ++ [j]` (j = 0..a) followed by the remaining columns.
fn child_occ(occ_rest: Vec[Vec[Binary{32}]], occ0: Vec[Binary{32}], a: Binary{32})
    => Vec[Vec[Binary{32}]] =
  occ_append(child_occ_acc(occ0, zero32(), a), occ_rest);

fn child_occ_acc(occ0: Vec[Binary{32}], j: Binary{32}, a: Binary{32}) => Vec[Vec[Binary{32}]] =
  match lt(j, a) {
    0b1 => Cons(u32_append(occ0, Cons(j, Nil)), child_occ_acc(occ0, add_u(j, one32()), a)),
    _ => Nil
  };

// gather_ctor_names / gather_lit_names: first-seen, deduped head names in column 0.
fn gather_ctor_names(rows: Vec[DRow]) => Vec[Bytes] =
  match rows {
    Nil => Nil,
    Cons(r, rest) => match drow_pats(r) {
      Nil => gather_ctor_names(rest),
      Cons(first, _) => match first {
        MpCtor(n, _) =>
          let tail = gather_ctor_names(rest) in
          match names_contains(tail, n) { True => tail, False => Cons(n, tail) },
        MpWild => gather_ctor_names(rest),
        MpLit(_) => gather_ctor_names(rest)
      }
    }
  };

fn gather_lit_names(rows: Vec[DRow]) => Vec[Bytes] =
  match rows {
    Nil => Nil,
    Cons(r, rest) => match drow_pats(r) {
      Nil => gather_lit_names(rest),
      Cons(first, _) => match first {
        MpLit(k) =>
          let tail = gather_lit_names(rest) in
          match names_contains(tail, k) { True => tail, False => Cons(k, tail) },
        MpWild => gather_lit_names(rest),
        MpCtor(_, _) => gather_lit_names(rest)
      }
    }
  };

// signature_complete: whether `present` covers `ty0`'s whole finite signature.
fn signature_complete(ty0: Ty, types: Vec[DataInfo], present: Vec[Bytes]) => Bool =
  match signature(ty0, types) {
    None => False,
    Some(d) => ctors_all_present(di_ctors(d), present)
  };

// build_ctor_cases(_from): one `(Head::Ctor, subtree)` case per ctor of `ty0`'s signature that
// appears in `present`, in SIGNATURE order (mirrors decision.rs::compile_rows's ctor loop).
fn build_ctor_cases(depth: Binary{32}, types: Vec[DataInfo], rows: Vec[DRow], ty0: Ty,
    occ0: Vec[Binary{32}], occ_rest: Vec[Vec[Binary{32}]], tys_rest: Vec[Ty], present: Vec[Bytes])
    => Result[Vec[Pair[Head, Tree]], Bytes] =
  match signature(ty0, types) {
    None => Ok(Nil),
    Some(d) => build_ctor_cases_from(depth, types, rows, occ0, occ_rest, tys_rest, di_ctors(d), present)
  };

fn build_ctor_cases_from(depth: Binary{32}, types: Vec[DataInfo], rows: Vec[DRow],
    occ0: Vec[Binary{32}], occ_rest: Vec[Vec[Binary{32}]], tys_rest: Vec[Ty], ctors: Vec[CtorInfo],
    present: Vec[Bytes]) => Result[Vec[Pair[Head, Tree]], Bytes] =
  match ctors {
    Nil => Ok(Nil),
    Cons(ci, rest) => match names_contains(present, ci_name(ci)) {
      False => build_ctor_cases_from(depth, types, rows, occ0, occ_rest, tys_rest, rest, present),
      True =>
        let a = ty_len(ci_fields(ci)) in
        let sub_rows = specialize_ctor_row(rows, ci_name(ci), a) in
        let sub_occ = child_occ(occ_rest, occ0, a) in
        let sub_tys = ty_append(ci_fields(ci), tys_rest) in
        match compile_rows(depth, types, sub_rows, sub_occ, sub_tys) {
          Err(e) => Err(e),
          Ok(subtree) =>
            match build_ctor_cases_from(depth, types, rows, occ0, occ_rest, tys_rest, rest, present) {
              Err(e) => Err(e),
              Ok(more) => Ok(Cons(Pr(HdCtor(ci_name(ci), a), subtree), more))
            }
        }
    }
  };

// build_lit_cases: one `(Head::Lit, subtree)` case per literal head, first-seen order.
fn build_lit_cases(depth: Binary{32}, types: Vec[DataInfo], rows: Vec[DRow],
    occ_rest: Vec[Vec[Binary{32}]], tys_rest: Vec[Ty], lits: Vec[Bytes])
    => Result[Vec[Pair[Head, Tree]], Bytes] =
  match lits {
    Nil => Ok(Nil),
    Cons(k, rest) => match compile_rows(depth, types, specialize_lit_row(rows, k), occ_rest, tys_rest) {
      Err(e) => Err(e),
      Ok(subtree) => match build_lit_cases(depth, types, rows, occ_rest, tys_rest, rest) {
        Err(e) => Err(e),
        Ok(more) => Ok(Cons(Pr(HdLit(k), subtree), more))
      }
    }
  };

// compile: entry point — a fresh per-compilation budget (mirrors decision.rs::compile).
fn compile(types: Vec[DataInfo], matrix: Vec[Vec[Pat]], arms: Vec[Binary{32}],
    occ: Vec[Vec[Binary{32}]], tys: Vec[Ty]) => Result[Tree, Bytes] =
  compile_rows(zero32(), types, zip_rows(matrix, arms), occ, tys);

fn zip_rows(matrix: Vec[Vec[Pat]], arms: Vec[Binary{32}]) => Vec[DRow] =
  match matrix {
    Nil => Nil,
    Cons(pats, mrest) => match arms {
      Nil => Nil,
      Cons(arm, arest) => Cons(DRw(pats, arm), zip_rows(mrest, arest))
    }
  };

// compile_rows: the budget-charged recursion (mirrors decision.rs::compile_rows).
fn compile_rows(depth: Binary{32}, types: Vec[DataInfo], rows: Vec[DRow], occ: Vec[Vec[Binary{32}]],
    tys: Vec[Ty]) => Result[Tree, Bytes] =
  match enter_depth(depth) {
    Err(e) => Err(e),
    Ok(d2) => match rows {
      Nil => Ok(Fail),
      Cons(first, _) => match row_all_wild(drow_pats(first)) {
        True => Ok(Leaf(drow_arm(first))),
        False => compile_switch(d2, types, rows, occ, tys, first_nonwild_idx(drow_pats(first), zero32()))
      }
    }
  };

fn compile_switch(depth: Binary{32}, types: Vec[DataInfo], rows: Vec[DRow], occ: Vec[Vec[Binary{32}]],
    tys: Vec[Ty], col: Binary{32}) => Result[Tree, Bytes] =
  let rows2 = rotate_rows_to_front(rows, col) in
  match extract_occ(occ, col) { Pr(occ0, occ_rest) =>
  match extract_ty(tys, col) { Pr(ty0, tys_rest) =>
    let present = gather_ctor_names(rows2) in
    let complete = signature_complete(ty0, types, present) in
    match build_ctor_cases(depth, types, rows2, ty0, occ0, occ_rest, tys_rest, present) {
      Err(e) => Err(e),
      Ok(ctor_cases) =>
        let lits = gather_lit_names(rows2) in
        match build_lit_cases(depth, types, rows2, occ_rest, tys_rest, lits) {
          Err(e) => Err(e),
          Ok(lit_cases) =>
            let cases = cases_append(ctor_cases, lit_cases) in
            match complete {
              True => Ok(Switch(occ0, cases, None)),
              False => match compile_rows(depth, types, default_rows(rows2), occ_rest, tys_rest) {
                Err(e) => Err(e),
                Ok(deftree) => Ok(Switch(occ0, cases, Some(deftree)))
              }
            }
        }
    }
  }};

// has_reachable_fail: whether the tree contains a reachable `Fail` (mirrors decision.rs verbatim).
fn has_reachable_fail(t: Tree) => Bool =
  match t {
    Fail => True,
    Leaf(_) => False,
    Switch(_, cases, deft) => match cases_any_reachable_fail(cases) {
      True => True,
      False => match deft { None => False, Some(d) => has_reachable_fail(d) }
    }
  };

fn cases_any_reachable_fail(cases: Vec[Pair[Head, Tree]]) => Bool =
  match cases {
    Nil => False,
    Cons(c, rest) => match c {
      Pr(_, t) => match has_reachable_fail(t) { True => True, False => cases_any_reachable_fail(rest) }
    }
  };

// tree_eval: a small TEST-ONLY reference evaluator (mirrors decision.rs's own module-doc-mentioned
// `eval_tree` reference — "it verifies the compiler; it does not run programs"). Walks the tree
// against one concrete (fully-ground, no `MpWild`) value pattern, returning the arm index reached,
// or `None` if a `Fail` is reached. Occurrence-indexed lookup into the concrete value is done via
// `pat_at_occ` (a small ground-value navigator — NOT part of decision.rs itself, purely this
// increment's differential-driving harness).
fn tree_eval(t: Tree, value: Pat) => Option[Binary{32}] =
  match t {
    Fail => None,
    Leaf(arm) => Some(arm),
    Switch(occ, cases, deft) => tree_eval_switch(pat_at_occ(value, occ), cases, deft, value)
  };

fn tree_eval_switch(scrutinee: Pat, cases: Vec[Pair[Head, Tree]], deft: Option[Tree], value: Pat)
    => Option[Binary{32}] =
  match cases {
    Nil => tree_eval_deft(deft, value),
    Cons(c, rest) => match c {
      Pr(h, sub) => match head_matches(h, scrutinee) {
        True => tree_eval(sub, value),
        False => tree_eval_switch(scrutinee, rest, deft, value)
      }
    }
  };

fn tree_eval_deft(deft: Option[Tree], value: Pat) => Option[Binary{32}] =
  match deft { None => None, Some(d) => tree_eval(d, value) };

fn head_matches(h: Head, scrutinee: Pat) => Bool =
  match h {
    HdCtor(n, _) => match scrutinee {
      MpCtor(sn, _) => match bytes_eq(n, sn) { 0b1 => True, _ => False },
      MpWild => False,
      MpLit(_) => False
    },
    HdLit(k) => match scrutinee {
      MpLit(sk) => match bytes_eq(k, sk) { 0b1 => True, _ => False },
      MpWild => False,
      MpCtor(_, _) => False
    }
  };

// pat_at_occ: navigate a ground value pattern via a field-index occurrence (root = `Nil`).
fn pat_at_occ(value: Pat, occ: Vec[Binary{32}]) => Pat =
  match occ {
    Nil => value,
    Cons(i, rest) => match value {
      MpCtor(_, subs) => pat_at_occ(pat_nth(subs, i), rest),
      MpWild => value,
      MpLit(_) => value
    }
  };

fn pat_nth(v: Vec[Pat], i: Binary{32}) => Pat =
  match eq(i, zero32()) {
    0b1 => match v { Cons(h, _) => h, Nil => MpWild },
    _ => match v { Cons(_, t) => pat_nth(t, sub_u(i, one32())), Nil => MpWild }
  };

// ── affine.rs port (the static use-once tracker for `Substrate` bindings — FLAG-semcore-6) ─────
// Only the PURE state-transition core is ported (`slot_for_ty`, `slots_seeded`, `slots_use_at`,
// `union_merge_into`) — the Rust `Tracker` object's inert/active split and its
// push/pop/truncate/snapshot/restore/merge_alt checker-integration wiring are NOT ported (no
// `Cx`-equivalent scope stack exists in this partial increment to mirror). `Vec[Slot]` IS the
// tracker: a plain value, threaded explicitly by the caller (never mutated in place).

// Slot: mirrors affine.rs::Slot (one scope slot's affine state).
type Slot = Skip | Live(Bytes) | Moved(Bytes, Binary{32});

// UseOutcome: mirrors affine.rs::UseOutcome (the outcome of recording a use at some index).
type UseOutcome = NotAffine | FirstUse | DoubleUse(Bytes, Binary{32}, Binary{32});

// slot_for_ty: the slot a fresh binding of type `ty` starts in (mirrors affine.rs::Slot::for_ty;
// the trailing-wildcard idiom — every non-`TySubstrate` type is `Skip`).
fn slot_for_ty(ty: Ty) => Slot =
  match ty { TySubstrate(tag) => Live(tag), _ => Skip };

// slots_seeded: one slot per entry of `tys` (mirrors affine.rs::Tracker::seeded's per-parameter
// seeding, restated as a pure fn over the parameter TYPE list).
fn slots_seeded(tys: Vec[Ty]) => Vec[Slot] =
  match tys { Nil => Nil, Cons(t, rest) => Cons(slot_for_ty(t), slots_seeded(rest)) };

// slots_use_at: record a use (move) of the binding at scope index `idx`, returning the UPDATED
// slots vector paired with the outcome (mirrors affine.rs::Tracker::use_at; `ordinal` is the
// caller's own monotonic use counter — FLAG-semcore-7, no wrapper `UseSite` type).
fn slots_use_at(slots: Vec[Slot], idx: Binary{32}, ordinal: Binary{32}) => Pair[Vec[Slot], UseOutcome] =
  match eq(idx, zero32()) {
    0b1 => slots_use_here(slots, ordinal),
    _ => match slots {
      Nil => Pr(Nil, NotAffine),
      Cons(s, rest) => match slots_use_at(rest, sub_u(idx, one32()), ordinal) {
        Pr(rest2, outcome) => Pr(Cons(s, rest2), outcome)
      }
    }
  };

fn slots_use_here(slots: Vec[Slot], ordinal: Binary{32}) => Pair[Vec[Slot], UseOutcome] =
  match slots {
    Nil => Pr(Nil, NotAffine),
    Cons(s, rest) => match s {
      Skip => Pr(Cons(Skip, rest), NotAffine),
      Live(tag) => Pr(Cons(Moved(tag, ordinal), rest), FirstUse),
      Moved(tag, first) => Pr(Cons(Moved(tag, first), rest), DoubleUse(tag, first, ordinal))
    }
  };

// merge_slot / union_merge_into: the conservative branch-merge rule (mirrors affine.rs verbatim —
// a slot moved in EITHER alternative is moved afterward). A length mismatch between `acc` and
// `other` is an internal-invariant violation (mirrors the Rust `debug_assert_eq!`); this total-fn
// port stops merging at the shorter side rather than panicking (never-silent by construction — no
// call site in this increment's differential produces mismatched snapshots).
fn union_merge_into(acc: Vec[Slot], other: Vec[Slot]) => Vec[Slot] =
  match acc {
    Nil => Nil,
    Cons(a, arest) => match other {
      Nil => acc,
      Cons(o, orest) => Cons(merge_slot(a, o), union_merge_into(arest, orest))
    }
  };

fn merge_slot(a: Slot, o: Slot) => Slot =
  match a {
    Live(_) => match o { Moved(tag, first) => Moved(tag, first), Live(_) => a, Skip => a },
    Moved(_, _) => a,
    Skip => a
  };

// ── grade.rs port (RFC-0018 SS4.3 stage-1a static guarantee grading — FLAG-semcore-9) ───────────
// Only the PER-BODY walk is ported: `grade`/`grade_expr` and its helpers, plus a thin
// `grade_fn_body` entry point. `check_guarantees`'s whole-program `own_names`/`impl_methods`
// driver is NOT ported (FLAG-semcore-9's header note).

// CheckError: mirrors checkty.rs::CheckError (site, message) — the one error surface `grade`
// needs; no checking LOGIC accompanies it (this file ports no checkty.rs logic at all).
type CheckError = CE(Bytes, Bytes);

fn ce_site(e: CheckError) => Bytes =
  match e { CE(s, _) => s };

fn ce_message(e: CheckError) => Bytes =
  match e { CE(_, m) => m };

// FnEnv: the FLAG-semcore-4 ordered-assoc-list standing in for the checker's resolved
// `BTreeMap<String, FnDecl>` fn table.
fn fnenv_lookup(fns: Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], name: Bytes) => Option[FnDecl] =
  match fns {
    Nil => None,
    Cons(entry, rest) => match entry {
      Pr(n, fd) => match bytes_eq(n, name) { 0b1 => Some(fd), _ => fnenv_lookup(rest, name) }
    }
  };

// ret_grade / param_grade: the modular-bottom defaults (mirrors grade.rs verbatim — an
// unannotated demand/advertisement is `GDeclared`, the weakest grade).
fn ret_grade(fd: FnDecl) => Strength =
  match typeref_guarantee(fnsig_ret(fndecl_sig(fd))) { Some(g) => g, None => GDeclared };

fn param_grade(p: Param) => Strength =
  match typeref_guarantee(param_ty(p)) { Some(g) => g, None => GDeclared };

// scope_lookup: a lexical stack of `(name, grade)`, most-recent-first (`Cons` = push; shadowing =
// head-first scan finds the most recent binding — mirrors the Rust `scope.iter().rev().find`).
fn scope_lookup(scope: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Strength]], name: Bytes) => Option[Strength] =
  match scope {
    Nil => None,
    Cons(entry, rest) => match entry {
      Pr(n, g) => match bytes_eq(n, name) { 0b1 => Some(g) , _ => scope_lookup(rest, name) }
    }
  };

// require: the honesty check `have >= demand` (G-Sub; mirrors grade.rs::require, `Option`-returning
// rather than `Result<(),_>` — no unit type needed self-contained).
fn require(have: Strength, demand: Strength, site: Bytes, what: Bytes) => Option[CheckError] =
  match strength_satisfies(have, demand) {
    True => None,
    False => Some(CE(site, bytes_concat(what, " does not satisfy the demanded guarantee (RFC-0018 SS4.3 -- VR-5/G2)")))
  };

// grade: the budgeted entry point (mirrors grade.rs::Gx::grade's per-recursion budget charge).
fn grade(depth: Binary{32}, fns: Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], scope: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Strength]],
    site: Bytes, e: Expr) => Result[Strength, CheckError] =
  match enter_depth(depth) {
    Err(_) => Err(CE(site, "guarantee grading exceeded the recursion budget (RFC-0041 SS4.7 restated; refused never-silently, never a host-stack overflow -- G2/VR-5)")),
    Ok(d2) => grade_expr(d2, fns, scope, site, e)
  };

// grade_expr: the per-variant dispatch (mirrors grade.rs::Gx::grade's big `match e { ... }`,
// field-for-field against ast.myc's `Expr` — every variant explicit, M-980 split-match idiom).
fn grade_expr(depth: Binary{32}, fns: Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], scope: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Strength]],
    site: Bytes, e: Expr) => Result[Strength, CheckError] =
  match e {
    Let(name, ty, bound, body) => grade_let(depth, fns, scope, site, name, ty, bound, body),
    If(cond, conseq, alt) => grade_if(depth, fns, scope, site, cond, conseq, alt),
    Match(scrutinee, arms) => grade_match(depth, fns, scope, site, scrutinee, arms),
    For(x, xs, acc, init, body) => grade_for(depth, fns, scope, site, x, xs, acc, init, body),
    Swap(value, _, _) => match grade(depth, fns, scope, site, value) {
      Err(err) => Err(err),
      Ok(_) => Ok(GExact)
    },
    WithParadigm(_, body) => grade(depth, fns, scope, site, body),
    Wild(_) => Ok(GDeclared),
    Spore(_) => Ok(GDeclared),
    Wrapping(_) => Ok(GDeclared),
    Consume(b) => grade(depth, fns, scope, site, b),
    Try(b) => grade(depth, fns, scope, site, b),
    Colony(hyphae) => grade_colony(depth, fns, scope, site, hyphae),
    Lambda(_, _) => Ok(GDeclared),
    App(head, args) => grade_app(depth, fns, scope, site, head, args),
    Fuse(left, right) => grade_fuse(depth, fns, scope, site, left, right),
    Reclaim(pol, body) => grade_reclaim(depth, fns, scope, site, pol, body),
    Path(p) => Ok(grade_path(scope, p)),
    Lit(lit) => grade_lit(depth, fns, scope, site, lit),
    Ascribe(inner, t) => grade_ascribe(depth, fns, scope, site, inner, t),
    TupleLit(elems) => meet_all(depth, fns, scope, site, elems)
  };

// grade_path: G-Var — a single-segment path is a bound variable (`GExact` if unbound: a nullary
// constructor/constant); a multi-segment path is conservatively `GExact` too (the checker already
// refuses those; a residual one here is never reached by a well-formed body).
fn grade_path(scope: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Strength]], p: Path) => Strength =
  match path_segs(p) {
    Nil => GExact,
    Cons(seg, rest) => match rest {
      Nil => match scope_lookup(scope, seg) { Some(g) => g, None => GExact },
      Cons(_, _) => GExact
    }
  };

// grade_lit: G-Const — a literal is `Exact` by construction; a list literal is the meet of its
// elements (G-Con).
fn grade_lit(depth: Binary{32}, fns: Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], scope: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Strength]],
    site: Bytes, lit: Literal) => Result[Strength, CheckError] =
  match lit {
    List(es) => meet_all(depth, fns, scope, site, es),
    Bin(_) => Ok(GExact),
    Trit(_) => Ok(GExact),
    Int(_) => Ok(GExact),
    AmbientInt(_, _) => Ok(GExact),
    LBytes(_) => Ok(GExact),
    Str(_) => Ok(GExact),
    LFloat(_) => Ok(GExact)
  };

// grade_let: G-Let / G-Weaken — grade the bound expr, weaken to the ascription if written, bind,
// then take the meet with the body's grade.
fn grade_let(depth: Binary{32}, fns: Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], scope: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Strength]],
    site: Bytes, name: Bytes, ty: Option[TypeRef], bound: Expr, body: Expr)
    => Result[Strength, CheckError] =
  match grade(depth, fns, scope, site, bound) {
    Err(err) => Err(err),
    Ok(g_bound) => match let_bind_grade(ty, g_bound, site, name) {
      Err(err) => Err(err),
      Ok(bind) => match grade(depth, fns, Cons(Pr(name, bind), scope), site, body) {
        Err(err) => Err(err),
        Ok(g_body) => Ok(strength_meet(bind, g_body))
      }
    }
  };

fn let_bind_grade(ty: Option[TypeRef], g_bound: Strength, site: Bytes, name: Bytes)
    => Result[Strength, CheckError] =
  match ty {
    None => Ok(g_bound),
    Some(t) => match typeref_guarantee(t) {
      None => Ok(g_bound),
      Some(g) => match require(g_bound, g, site, bytes_concat("let-ascription for ", name)) {
        Some(err) => Err(err),
        None => Ok(g)
      }
    }
  };

// grade_if: Design A — the condition is walked (to enforce demands inside it) but does NOT
// degrade the result; the result is the meet of both branch bodies.
fn grade_if(depth: Binary{32}, fns: Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], scope: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Strength]],
    site: Bytes, cond: Expr, conseq: Expr, alt: Expr) => Result[Strength, CheckError] =
  match grade(depth, fns, scope, site, cond) {
    Err(err) => Err(err),
    Ok(_) => match grade(depth, fns, scope, site, conseq) {
      Err(err) => Err(err),
      Ok(t) => match grade(depth, fns, scope, site, alt) {
        Err(err) => Err(err),
        Ok(f) => Ok(strength_meet(t, f))
      }
    }
  };

// bind_pattern(s): push every variable a pattern binds at grade `g_s` (G-Match/A's field-binder
// data-provenance rule); `POr` is unreachable post-check (the checker desugars it) — a defensive
// no-op here (this language has no abort/panic primitive to mirror Rust's invariant-violation
// panic, so the no-op IS the honest total-fn restatement, documented rather than silent).
fn bind_pattern(scope: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Strength]], pat: Pattern, g_s: Strength)
    => Vec[Pair[Bytes, Strength]] =
  match pat {
    PWildcard => scope,
    PLit(_) => scope,
    PIdent(name) => Cons(Pr(name, g_s), scope),
    PCtor(_, subs) => bind_patterns(scope, subs, g_s),
    PTuple(subs) => bind_patterns(scope, subs, g_s),
    POr(_) => scope
  };

fn bind_patterns(scope: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Strength]], pats: Vec[Pattern], g_s: Strength)
    => Vec[Pair[Bytes, Strength]] =
  match pats {
    Nil => scope,
    Cons(p, rest) => bind_patterns(bind_pattern(scope, p, g_s), rest, g_s)
  };

// grade_match: G-Match/A — the scrutinee's grade does not appear in the result; the result is the
// meet of the arm bodies (each graded under its own pattern-bound scope).
fn grade_match(depth: Binary{32}, fns: Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], scope: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Strength]],
    site: Bytes, scrutinee: Expr, arms: Vec[Arm]) => Result[Strength, CheckError] =
  match grade(depth, fns, scope, site, scrutinee) {
    Err(err) => Err(err),
    Ok(g_s) => grade_arms(depth, fns, scope, site, arms, g_s)
  };

fn grade_arms(depth: Binary{32}, fns: Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], scope: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Strength]],
    site: Bytes, arms: Vec[Arm], g_s: Strength) => Result[Strength, CheckError] =
  match arms {
    Nil => Ok(GDeclared),
    Cons(arm, rest) =>
      let scope2 = bind_pattern(scope, arm_pattern(arm), g_s) in
      match grade(depth, fns, scope2, site, arm_body(arm)) {
        Err(err) => Err(err),
        Ok(g_arm) => match rest {
          Nil => Ok(g_arm),
          Cons(_, _) => match grade_arms(depth, fns, scope, site, rest, g_s) {
            Err(err) => Err(err),
            Ok(g_more) => Ok(strength_meet(g_arm, g_more))
          }
        }
      }
  };

// grade_for: the fixpoint-avoiding fold rule — the accumulator is graded at the BOTTOM (`GDeclared`)
// inside the body (sound without iterating to a fixpoint); the result is the meet of init/xs/body.
fn grade_for(depth: Binary{32}, fns: Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], scope: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Strength]],
    site: Bytes, x: Bytes, xs: Expr, acc: Bytes, init: Expr, body: Expr)
    => Result[Strength, CheckError] =
  match grade(depth, fns, scope, site, xs) {
    Err(err) => Err(err),
    Ok(g_xs) => match grade(depth, fns, scope, site, init) {
      Err(err) => Err(err),
      Ok(g_init) =>
        let scope2 = Cons(Pr(acc, GDeclared), Cons(Pr(x, g_xs), scope)) in
        match grade(depth, fns, scope2, site, body) {
          Err(err) => Err(err),
          Ok(g_body) => Ok(strength_meet(strength_meet(g_init, g_xs), g_body))
        }
    }
  };

// grade_colony: the colony's observable is its LAST hypha; leading hyphae are still walked (to
// enforce demands inside them) but do not contribute to the result grade.
fn grade_colony(depth: Binary{32}, fns: Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], scope: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Strength]],
    site: Bytes, hyphae: Vec[Hypha]) => Result[Strength, CheckError] =
  match hyphae {
    Nil => Ok(GExact),
    Cons(h, rest) => match rest {
      Nil => grade(depth, fns, scope, site, hypha_body(h)),
      Cons(_, _) => match grade(depth, fns, scope, site, hypha_body(h)) {
        Err(err) => Err(err),
        Ok(_) => grade_colony(depth, fns, scope, site, rest)
      }
    }
  };

// grade_fuse: DN-58 SSA/SSB — the meet of both operands (composition takes the weakest).
fn grade_fuse(depth: Binary{32}, fns: Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], scope: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Strength]],
    site: Bytes, left: Expr, right: Expr) => Result[Strength, CheckError] =
  match grade(depth, fns, scope, site, left) {
    Err(err) => Err(err),
    Ok(lg) => match grade(depth, fns, scope, site, right) {
      Err(err) => Err(err),
      Ok(rg) => Ok(strength_meet(lg, rg))
    }
  };

// grade_reclaim: DN-58 SSB — the policy expr is walked (to surface any policy-grade violation), then
// the result is the body's grade.
fn grade_reclaim(depth: Binary{32}, fns: Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], scope: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Strength]],
    site: Bytes, pol: Expr, body: Expr) => Result[Strength, CheckError] =
  match grade(depth, fns, scope, site, pol) {
    Err(err) => Err(err),
    Ok(_) => grade(depth, fns, scope, site, body)
  };

// grade_ascribe: G-Weaken — an `@ g` ascription demands the inferred grade satisfy `g`; the
// ascribed expr then carries `g`. A bare type ascription (no `@ g`) is grade-transparent.
fn grade_ascribe(depth: Binary{32}, fns: Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], scope: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Strength]],
    site: Bytes, inner: Expr, t: TypeRef) => Result[Strength, CheckError] =
  match grade(depth, fns, scope, site, inner) {
    Err(err) => Err(err),
    Ok(g_inner) => match typeref_guarantee(t) {
      None => Ok(g_inner),
      Some(g) => match require(g_inner, g, site, "ascription") {
        Some(err) => Err(err),
        None => Ok(g)
      }
    }
  };

// meet_all: the meet of every expression's grade (`GExact` for an empty list — the meet identity).
fn meet_all(depth: Binary{32}, fns: Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], scope: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Strength]],
    site: Bytes, es: Vec[Expr]) => Result[Strength, CheckError] =
  match es {
    Nil => Ok(GExact),
    Cons(e, rest) => match grade(depth, fns, scope, site, e) {
      Err(err) => Err(err),
      Ok(g) => match meet_all(depth, fns, scope, site, rest) {
        Err(err) => Err(err),
        Ok(more) => Ok(strength_meet(g, more))
      }
    }
  };

// app_head_fn: resolve an `App` head to a KNOWN user function (a single-segment `Path` present in
// `fns`), else `None` (constructor / prim / trait-method — no graded signature in stage 1a).
fn app_head_fn(fns: Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], head: Expr) => Option[FnDecl] =
  match head {
    Path(p) => match path_segs(p) {
      Cons(seg, rest) => match rest { Nil => fnenv_lookup(fns, seg), Cons(_, _) => None },
      Nil => None
    },
    _ => None
  };

// grade_app: G-App (a known callee: check each arg against its param's demand, result is the
// callee's declared return grade) / G-Con-fallback (anything else: the conservative meet of args).
fn grade_app(depth: Binary{32}, fns: Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], scope: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Strength]],
    site: Bytes, head: Expr, args: Vec[Expr]) => Result[Strength, CheckError] =
  match app_head_fn(fns, head) {
    Some(fd) => grade_call(depth, fns, scope, site, fd, args),
    None => meet_all(depth, fns, scope, site, args)
  };

fn grade_call(depth: Binary{32}, fns: Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], scope: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Strength]],
    site: Bytes, fd: FnDecl, args: Vec[Expr]) => Result[Strength, CheckError] =
  match check_args(depth, fns, scope, site, fnsig_value_params(fndecl_sig(fd)), args) {
    Err(err) => Err(err),
    Ok(_) => Ok(ret_grade(fd))
  };

fn check_args(depth: Binary{32}, fns: Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], scope: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Strength]],
    site: Bytes, params: Vec[Param], args: Vec[Expr]) => Result[Binary{32}, CheckError] =
  match params {
    Nil => Ok(zero32()),
    Cons(p, prest) => match args {
      Nil => Ok(zero32()),
      Cons(a, arest) => match grade(depth, fns, scope, site, a) {
        Err(err) => Err(err),
        Ok(g_a) => match require(g_a, param_grade(p), site, "argument") {
          Some(err) => Err(err),
          None => check_args(depth, fns, scope, site, prest, arest)
        }
      }
    }
  };

// params_to_scope / grade_fn_body: the thin per-body entry point this increment's differential
// drives directly (FLAG-semcore-9 — no whole-program `own_names`/`impl_methods` driver).
fn params_to_scope(params: Vec[Param]) => Vec[Pair[Bytes, Strength]] =
  match params {
    Nil => Nil,
    Cons(p, rest) => Cons(Pr(param_name(p), param_grade(p)), params_to_scope(rest))
  };

fn grade_fn_body(fns: Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], fd: FnDecl) => Result[Strength, CheckError] =
  let site = fnsig_name(fndecl_sig(fd)) in
  let scope0 = params_to_scope(fnsig_value_params(fndecl_sig(fd))) in
  match grade(zero32(), fns, scope0, site, fndecl_body(fd)) {
    Err(err) => Err(err),
    Ok(body_grade) => match require(body_grade, ret_grade(fd), site, "function body") {
      Some(err) => Err(err),
      None => Ok(body_grade)
    }
  };

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// checkty.rs TYPE ALGEBRA (M-740 Stage 5, increment 2 — M-1007). The pure type-substitution quartet.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Ports checkty.rs's four PURE type-algebra leaves — `has_var`, `type_head`, `subst_ty`,
// `param_subst` (checkty.rs::has_var/type_head/subst_ty/param_subst) — the substitution primitives
// the WHOLE checker/elaborator/monomorphizer build on (RFC-0007 SS11.2/SS11.3). All four are pure
// functions of a `Ty` with NO dependency on checkty's checking LOGIC, the L1 evaluator, or the L0
// IR, so they port cleanly AHEAD of the heavy entangled core (DN-26 SS7.1 SCC) and each carries a
// LIVE-ORACLE differential (crates/mycelium-l1/src/tests/compiler_stage5_typealg.rs — the four
// `pub`/`pub(crate)` Rust fns are reachable from an in-crate `src/tests/` module, so every case
// asserts the `.myc` verdict against the real checkty fn's own computed result, never a hand-derived
// constant — the FLAG-semcore-10 live-oracle posture, held here from the start).
//
// FLAG-semcore-11 (`BTreeMap<String, Ty>` -> ordered `Vec[Pair[Bytes, Ty]]` assoc list — the
// FLAG-semcore-4 convention restated for the substitution environment). `subst_ty`'s Rust signature
// takes `&BTreeMap<String, Ty>`; here it is the same ordered assoc list + linear `ty_subst_lookup`
// the type/fn registries already use. `param_subst` BUILDS that assoc list by zipping a
// parameter-name list with an argument-type list (mirroring `params.iter().zip(args).collect()` — a
// length mismatch yields a partial map, exactly as the Rust doc states, never a panic). No
// key-uniqueness is enforced (the same documented narrowing FLAG-semcore-4 already carries).
//
// FLAG-semcore-12 (`ty_eq` is DIFFERENTIAL-SUPPORT scaffolding, not a checkty.rs port). Rust compares
// `Ty` via `#[derive(PartialEq, Eq)]`; there is no hand-written `ty_eq` in checkty.rs. This nodule
// has no derived equality, so `ty_eq` (+ `width_eq`/`scalar_eq`/`sparsity_eq`/`ty_list_eq`) restates
// that derived structural equality explicitly, field-for-field, so the `subst_ty`/`param_subst`
// differential can compare a computed `Ty` against the live oracle's `Ty` in-language. Documented as
// support scaffolding faithful to `Ty: PartialEq`, not a silent addition to the ported surface.
//
// No depth budget is threaded (unlike useful_budgeted/compile_rows — FLAG-semcore-3): every function
// here recurses ONLY on strict sub-terms of a finite `Ty`/`Vec[Ty]` (the render/render_list
// structural-recursion shape this nodule already uses), so termination is structural — matching the
// Rust originals, which carry no RecursionBudget on these leaves.

// ── Bool adapters over the Binary{1}-returning primitives (eq / bytes_eq) ────────────────────────
fn eq_u(a: Binary{32}, b: Binary{32}) => Bool =
  match eq(a, b) { 0b1 => True, _ => False };

fn beq(a: Bytes, b: Bytes) => Bool =
  match bytes_eq(a, b) { 0b1 => True, _ => False };

fn and_(a: Bool, b: Bool) => Bool =
  match a { True => b, False => False };

// ── has_var: does `ty` mention any abstract type/width parameter? (checkty.rs::has_var) ──────────
// A width-var (`Binary{N}`/`Ternary{N}`) is abstract; a concrete width-lit is not (DN-42/M-753).
fn width_is_var(w: Width) => Bool =
  match w { WdVar(_) => True, WdLit(_) => False };

fn has_var(ty: Ty) => Bool =
  match ty {
    TyVar(_) => True,
    TyData(_, args) => any_has_var(args),
    TyFn(a, r) => match has_var(a) { True => True, False => has_var(r) },
    TySeq(elem, _) => has_var(elem),
    TyBinary(w) => width_is_var(w),
    TyTernary(w) => width_is_var(w),
    TyDense(_, _) => False,
    TyVsa(_, _, _) => False,
    TySubstrate(_) => False,
    TyBytes => False,
    TyFloat => False
  };

fn any_has_var(tys: Vec[Ty]) => Bool =
  match tys {
    Nil => False,
    Cons(h, t) => match has_var(h) { True => True, False => any_has_var(t) }
  };

// ── type_head: the coherence head-key of a stage-1 type (checkty.rs::type_head) ──────────────────
// `Var`/`Fn` are not legal instance heads -> None (RFC-0024 SS3 / RFC-0019 SS4.5); the width/elem/
// model-erased head-keying of Binary/Ternary/Dense/Vsa/Seq is the documented stage-1 coherence
// simplification, mirrored verbatim.
fn type_head(ty: Ty) => Option[Bytes] =
  match ty {
    TyBinary(_) => Some("Binary"),
    TyTernary(_) => Some("Ternary"),
    TyDense(_, _) => Some("Dense"),
    TyVsa(_, _, _) => Some("Vsa"),
    TySubstrate(t) => Some(bytes_concat("Substrate:", t)),
    TySeq(_, _) => Some("Seq"),
    TyBytes => Some("Bytes"),
    TyFloat => Some("Float"),
    TyData(n, _) => Some(bytes_concat("Data:", n)),
    TyVar(_) => None,
    TyFn(_, _) => None
  };

// ── subst_ty: replace each bound `Ty::Var`/width-var by its binding in the assoc-list `s`; an
// unbound var is left as-is (still in scope). Total; never inserts a Swap (S1). (checkty.rs::subst_ty)
fn ty_subst_lookup(s: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Ty]], v: Bytes) => Option[Ty] =
  match s {
    Nil => None,
    Cons(entry, rest) => match entry {
      Pr(k, t) => match bytes_eq(k, v) { 0b1 => Some(t), _ => ty_subst_lookup(rest, v) }
    }
  };

fn subst_ty(ty: Ty, s: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Ty]]) => Ty =
  match ty {
    TyVar(v) => match ty_subst_lookup(s, v) { Some(t) => t, None => TyVar(v) },
    TyData(n, args) => TyData(n, subst_ty_list(args, s)),
    TyFn(a, r) => TyFn(subst_ty(a, s), subst_ty(r, s)),
    TySeq(elem, n) => TySeq(subst_ty(elem, s), n),
    TyBinary(w) => subst_binary_width(w, s),
    TyTernary(w) => subst_ternary_width(w, s),
    TyDense(d, sc) => TyDense(d, sc),
    TyVsa(m, dim, sp) => TyVsa(m, dim, sp),
    TySubstrate(t) => TySubstrate(t),
    TyBytes => TyBytes,
    TyFloat => TyFloat
  };

fn subst_ty_list(tys: Vec[Ty], s: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Ty]]) => Vec[Ty] =
  match tys { Nil => Nil, Cons(h, t) => Cons(subst_ty(h, s), subst_ty_list(t, s)) };

// subst_binary_width / subst_ternary_width: DN-42/M-753 width-var substitution via the carrier
// convention — a width-var binding is stored as `v -> TyBinary(WdLit(n))` regardless of paradigm; on
// extraction we re-emit Binary or Ternary as appropriate. An unbound / unrecognised carrier is left
// as-is (defensive; mirrors the Rust `unwrap_or_else(|| ty.clone())` + `_ => ty.clone()`).
fn subst_binary_width(w: Width, s: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Ty]]) => Ty =
  match w {
    WdLit(n) => TyBinary(WdLit(n)),
    WdVar(v) => match ty_subst_lookup(s, v) {
      None => TyBinary(WdVar(v)),
      Some(carrier) => match carrier {
        TyBinary(cw) => match cw { WdLit(n) => TyBinary(WdLit(n)), WdVar(_) => TyBinary(WdVar(v)) },
        _ => TyBinary(WdVar(v))
      }
    }
  };

fn subst_ternary_width(w: Width, s: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Ty]]) => Ty =
  match w {
    WdLit(n) => TyTernary(WdLit(n)),
    WdVar(v) => match ty_subst_lookup(s, v) {
      None => TyTernary(WdVar(v)),
      Some(carrier) => match carrier {
        TyBinary(cw) => match cw { WdLit(n) => TyTernary(WdLit(n)), WdVar(_) => TyTernary(WdVar(v)) },
        _ => TyTernary(WdVar(v))
      }
    }
  };

// ── param_subst: zip a data type's declared parameter names with its concrete arguments into the
// FLAG-semcore-11 assoc-list (checkty.rs::param_subst). A length mismatch -> a partial map.
fn param_subst(params: Vec[Bytes], args: Vec[Ty]) => Vec[Pair[Bytes, Ty]] =
  match params {
    Nil => Nil,
    Cons(p, prest) => match args {
      Nil => Nil,
      Cons(a, arest) => Cons(Pr(p, a), param_subst(prest, arest))
    }
  };

// ── ty_eq: explicit structural equality restating `Ty: PartialEq` (FLAG-semcore-12 scaffolding) ──
fn scalar_eq(a: Scalar, b: Scalar) => Bool =
  match a {
    SF16 => match b { SF16 => True, _ => False },
    SBf16 => match b { SBf16 => True, _ => False },
    SF32 => match b { SF32 => True, _ => False },
    SF64 => match b { SF64 => True, _ => False }
  };

fn sparsity_eq(a: Sparsity, b: Sparsity) => Bool =
  match a {
    SpDense => match b { SpDense => True, SpSparse(_) => False },
    SpSparse(ka) => match b { SpSparse(kb) => eq_u(ka, kb), SpDense => False }
  };

fn width_eq(a: Width, b: Width) => Bool =
  match a {
    WdLit(na) => match b { WdLit(nb) => eq_u(na, nb), WdVar(_) => False },
    WdVar(va) => match b { WdVar(vb) => beq(va, vb), WdLit(_) => False }
  };

fn ty_eq(a: Ty, b: Ty) => Bool =
  match a {
    TyBinary(wa) => match b { TyBinary(wb) => width_eq(wa, wb), _ => False },
    TyTernary(wa) => match b { TyTernary(wb) => width_eq(wa, wb), _ => False },
    TyDense(da, sa) => match b { TyDense(db, sb) => and_(eq_u(da, db), scalar_eq(sa, sb)), _ => False },
    TyVsa(ma, dima, spa) => match b { TyVsa(mb, dimb, spb) => and_(and_(beq(ma, mb), eq_u(dima, dimb)), sparsity_eq(spa, spb)), _ => False },
    TyData(na, argsa) => match b { TyData(nb, argsb) => and_(beq(na, nb), ty_list_eq(argsa, argsb)), _ => False },
    TySubstrate(ta) => match b { TySubstrate(tb) => beq(ta, tb), _ => False },
    TySeq(ea, na) => match b { TySeq(eb, nb) => and_(ty_eq(ea, eb), eq_u(na, nb)), _ => False },
    TyBytes => match b { TyBytes => True, _ => False },
    TyFloat => match b { TyFloat => True, _ => False },
    TyVar(va) => match b { TyVar(vb) => beq(va, vb), _ => False },
    TyFn(aa, ra) => match b { TyFn(ab, rb) => and_(ty_eq(aa, ab), ty_eq(ra, rb)), _ => False }
  };

fn ty_list_eq(a: Vec[Ty], b: Vec[Ty]) => Bool =
  match a {
    Nil => match b { Nil => True, Cons(_, _) => False },
    Cons(ha, ta) => match b { Nil => False, Cons(hb, tb) => and_(ty_eq(ha, hb), ty_list_eq(ta, tb)) }
  };

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// checkty.rs TYPE ALGEBRA (M-740 Stage 5, increment 3 — M-1008). Unification + type resolution.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Ports checkty.rs's next type-algebra layer, building on increment 2 (M-1007):
//   * `unify`      (checkty.rs::unify)      — one-sided unification of a declared `Ty` against a
//     concrete `Ty`, ACCUMULATING a parameter substitution. The never-silent conflict path (a
//     second, conflicting binding is an explicit mismatch, never a silent re-coercion — G2/VR-5).
//   * `resolve_ty` (checkty.rs::resolve_ty) — surface `TypeRef` -> checked `Ty` (+ its guarantee).
//   * `tuple_type_name`/`tuple_ctor_name`/`synthetic_tuple_data` (checkty.rs, M-826) — the
//     synthetic-tuple helpers (injective `Tuple$N`/`MkTuple$N` naming + on-demand `DataInfo`).
// Pure `Ty`-algebra (no checking logic, no evaluator); each has a reachable live Rust oracle
// (`pub(crate)`/`pub`) for the in-crate differential (compiler_stage5_unify.rs).
//
// FLAG-semcore-13 (`unify`'s `&mut BTreeMap<String, Ty>` -> a THREADED
// `Vec[Pair[Bytes, Ty]]` returned on `Ok`, the FLAG-semcore-6 value-threaded collapse over the
// FLAG-semcore-11 assoc-list). Rust mutates `s` in place and returns `Result<(), _>`; here `unify`
// takes the current substitution and RETURNS the extended one on `Ok` (an unchanged `s` on the
// no-op arms). A binding is prepended (`Cons(Pr(v, t), s)`) — first-match lookup shadows, so this
// reproduces `BTreeMap::insert`'s lookup semantics (no key-uniqueness enforced — the standing
// FLAG-semcore-4 narrowing). The `site` string is DROPPED (error text carries no `site` prefix —
// the same harmless narrowing FLAG-semcore-3 already takes; the differential asserts Ok/Err +
// the resulting `Ty`/substitution, never the message bytes).
//
// FLAG-semcore-14 (`unify`'s vestigial `(_, Ty::Var(_)) if decl == actual` arm collapses into the
// general `decl == actual` fallback). In Rust that arm sits AFTER `(Ty::Var(v), _)`, so it is only
// reachable when `decl` is NON-`Var` and `actual` IS `Var` — but then `decl == actual` can never
// hold (a non-`Var` never structurally equals a `Var`), so its guard is unsatisfiable and it
// always falls through to the `_ if decl == actual` catch. This port omits the dead arm and lets
// `(nonvar, TyVar)` reach the same `ty_eq(decl, actual)` fallback — a behaviour-preserving
// collapse, documented (not a silent drop — G2).
//
// FLAG-semcore-15 (the decimal-render helper `dec_u32`, introduced here). Rust's
// `format!("{n}")` renders a `usize`/`u32` as base-10 digits; semcore's existing encoders emit only
// `0b`-literals, so `tuple_type_name`/`synthetic_tuple_data` (and, next, mono's mangling — M-1009,
// which REUSES this helper) need a base-10 renderer. It is a bounded divmod-by-10 recursion
// (<= 10 iterations for any `Binary{32}`, no M-986/M-987 concern) over the never-silent `div_u`/
// `rem_u` prims, itself differential-tested against the oracle's decimal output.

// ── dec_u32: render a Binary{32} as base-10 Bytes (FLAG-semcore-15; Rust `format!("{n}")`) ───────
fn dec_digit(d: Binary{32}) => Bytes =
  match eq(d, 0b0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000) { 0b1 => "0", _ =>
  match eq(d, 0b0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0001) { 0b1 => "1", _ =>
  match eq(d, 0b0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0010) { 0b1 => "2", _ =>
  match eq(d, 0b0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0011) { 0b1 => "3", _ =>
  match eq(d, 0b0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0100) { 0b1 => "4", _ =>
  match eq(d, 0b0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0101) { 0b1 => "5", _ =>
  match eq(d, 0b0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0110) { 0b1 => "6", _ =>
  match eq(d, 0b0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0111) { 0b1 => "7", _ =>
  match eq(d, 0b0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_1000) { 0b1 => "8", _ => "9"
  }}}}}}}}};

fn ten32() => Binary{32} = 0b0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_1010;

// Base-10 render, big-endian: n < 10 -> one digit; else render n/10 then append n%10 (<= 10 iters).
fn dec_u32(n: Binary{32}) => Bytes =
  match lt(n, ten32()) {
    0b1 => dec_digit(n),
    _ => bytes_concat(dec_u32(div_u(n, ten32())), dec_digit(rem_u(n, ten32())))
  };

// ── synthetic tuple helpers (checkty.rs::tuple_type_name/tuple_ctor_name/synthetic_tuple_data) ───
// Injective over `n` (`$` is not a surface-identifier char), so these cannot collide with a
// user-defined type/ctor (M-826, KC-3).
fn tuple_type_name(n: Binary{32}) => Bytes = bytes_concat("Tuple$", dec_u32(n));

fn tuple_ctor_name(n: Binary{32}) => Bytes = bytes_concat("MkTuple$", dec_u32(n));

// tuple_params: the `n` type-parameter names `T0 .. T{n-1}` (Rust `(0..n).map(|i| format!("T{i}"))`).
fn tuple_params_from(i: Binary{32}, n: Binary{32}) => Vec[Bytes] =
  match lt(i, n) {
    0b1 => Cons(bytes_concat("T", dec_u32(i)), tuple_params_from(add_u(i, one32()), n)),
    _ => Nil
  };

// vars_of: one `TyVar(p)` field per parameter name (Rust `params.iter().map(|p| Ty::Var(p))`).
fn vars_of(params: Vec[Bytes]) => Vec[Ty] =
  match params { Nil => Nil, Cons(p, rest) => Cons(TyVar(p), vars_of(rest)) };

fn synthetic_tuple_data(n: Binary{32}) => DataInfo =
  let params = tuple_params_from(zero32(), n) in
  DI(tuple_type_name(n), params, Cons(CI(tuple_ctor_name(n), vars_of(params)), Nil));

// ── resolve_ty: surface `TypeRef` -> checked `Ty` (+ its declared guarantee). (checkty.rs) ───────
// typeref_base: re-added here (FLAG-semcore-1 dropped it as unused; resolve_ty needs it).
fn typeref_base(t: TypeRef) => BaseType = match t { TR(b, _) => b };

fn di_params(d: DataInfo) => Vec[Bytes] =
  match d { DI(_, p, _) => p };

// resolve_widthref_*: a surface `WidthRef` (WLit/WName) becomes a checked `Width` under the given
// paradigm (Rust's per-`BaseType::Binary/Ternary` inline `match &t.base` arms).
fn resolve_widthref_binary(w: WidthRef) => Ty =
  match w { WLit(n) => TyBinary(WdLit(n)), WName(v) => TyBinary(WdVar(v)) };

fn resolve_widthref_ternary(w: WidthRef) => Ty =
  match w { WLit(n) => TyTernary(WdLit(n)), WName(v) => TyTernary(WdVar(v)) };

// vsa_kernel_model_id: the surface->kernel VSA model-id canonicalization (checkty.rs; M-892).
fn vsa_kernel_model_id(surface: Bytes) => Bytes =
  match bytes_eq(surface, "MAP_I") { 0b1 => "MAP-I", _ =>
  match bytes_eq(surface, "MAP_B") { 0b1 => "MAP-B", _ => surface }};

// tref_len / names_len: monomorphic length counters (Vec[TypeRef] / Vec[Bytes]) — the arity check.
fn tref_len(v: Vec[TypeRef]) => Binary{32} =
  match v { Nil => zero32(), Cons(_, t) => add_u(one32(), tref_len(t)) };

fn names_len(v: Vec[Bytes]) => Binary{32} =
  match v { Nil => zero32(), Cons(_, t) => add_u(one32(), names_len(t)) };

fn args_is_empty(v: Vec[TypeRef]) => Bool =
  match v { Nil => True, Cons(_, _) => False };

fn resolve_base(types: Vec[DataInfo], tyvars: Vec[Bytes], b: BaseType) => Result[Ty, Bytes] =
  match b {
    KwBinary(w) => Ok(resolve_widthref_binary(w)),
    KwTernary(w) => Ok(resolve_widthref_ternary(w)),
    KwDense(d, sc) => Ok(TyDense(d, sc)),
    KwSubstrate(tag) => Ok(TySubstrate(tag)),
    KwSeq(elem, len) => match resolve_ty(types, tyvars, elem) {
      Err(e) => Err(e),
      Ok(pr) => match pr { Pr(ety, _) => Ok(TySeq(ety, len)) }
    },
    KwBytes => Ok(TyBytes),
    KwFloat => Ok(TyFloat),
    Vsa(model, dim, sp) => Ok(TyVsa(vsa_kernel_model_id(model), dim, sp)),
    Named(name, args) => resolve_named(types, tyvars, name, args),
    Ambient(_) => Err("internal: an unresolved paradigm-less repr `{...}` reached the checker -- the ambient resolution pass should have filled it (RFC-0012 SS4.3)"),
    FnArrow(param, ret) => match resolve_ty(types, tyvars, param) {
      Err(e) => Err(e),
      Ok(pp) => match pp { Pr(pty, _) => match resolve_ty(types, tyvars, ret) {
        Err(e) => Err(e),
        Ok(pr) => match pr { Pr(rty, _) => Ok(TyFn(pty, rty)) }
      }}
    },
    Tuple(elems) => resolve_tuple(types, tyvars, elems)
  };

// resolve_args: map resolve_ty over each surface arg, short-circuiting on the first Err (Rust's
// `for a in args { resolved.push(resolve_ty(..)?.0) }`; the guarantee of each arg is discarded).
fn resolve_args(types: Vec[DataInfo], tyvars: Vec[Bytes], args: Vec[TypeRef]) => Result[Vec[Ty], Bytes] =
  match args {
    Nil => Ok(Nil),
    Cons(a, rest) => match resolve_ty(types, tyvars, a) {
      Err(e) => Err(e),
      Ok(pr) => match pr { Pr(aty, _) => match resolve_args(types, tyvars, rest) {
        Err(e) => Err(e),
        Ok(more) => Ok(Cons(aty, more))
      }}
    }
  };

fn resolve_named(types: Vec[DataInfo], tyvars: Vec[Bytes], name: Bytes, args: Vec[TypeRef]) => Result[Ty, Bytes] =
  match and_(args_is_empty(args), names_contains(tyvars, name)) {
    True => Ok(TyVar(name)),
    False => match types_lookup(types, name) {
      None => Err(bytes_concat("unknown type `", bytes_concat(name, "`"))),
      Some(decl) => match eq_u(tref_len(args), names_len(di_params(decl))) {
        False => Err(bytes_concat("`", bytes_concat(name, bytes_concat("` takes ", bytes_concat(dec_u32(names_len(di_params(decl))), bytes_concat(" type argument(s), got ", bytes_concat(dec_u32(tref_len(args)), " (RFC-0007 SS11.3)"))))))),
        True => match resolve_args(types, tyvars, args) {
          Err(e) => Err(e),
          Ok(resolved) => Ok(TyData(name, resolved))
        }
      }
    }
  };

fn resolve_tuple(types: Vec[DataInfo], tyvars: Vec[Bytes], elems: Vec[TypeRef]) => Result[Ty, Bytes] =
  let tname = tuple_type_name(tref_len(elems)) in
  match types_lookup(types, tname) {
    None => Err(bytes_concat("internal: synthetic tuple type `", bytes_concat(tname, "` not registered -- `register_tuple_types` must run before the checker (M-826; never silent)"))),
    Some(_) => match resolve_args(types, tyvars, elems) {
      Err(e) => Err(e),
      Ok(resolved) => Ok(TyData(tname, resolved))
    }
  };

fn resolve_ty(types: Vec[DataInfo], tyvars: Vec[Bytes], t: TypeRef) => Result[Pair[Ty, Option[Strength]], Bytes] =
  match resolve_base(types, tyvars, typeref_base(t)) {
    Err(e) => Err(e),
    Ok(base) => Ok(Pr(base, typeref_guarantee(t)))
  };

// ── first_duplicate / resolve_ctors (checkty.rs register-family; M-1013 STEP 3, PR-1) ─────────────
// first_duplicate: the first value that appears more than once in `xs`, left to right, if any —
// checkty.rs's dup-param/dup-name guard. Rust threads a `BTreeSet`; the port threads a `seen` list
// (the FLAG-semcore-4 assoc-list posture) and reuses `names_contains`. Pure preimage — the CALLER
// turns a `Some` into an explicit refusal (never silent — G2).
fn first_duplicate(xs: Vec[Bytes]) => Option[Bytes] =
  first_duplicate_go(Nil, xs);

fn first_duplicate_go(seen: Vec[Bytes], xs: Vec[Bytes]) => Option[Bytes] =
  match xs {
    Nil => None,
    Cons(x, rest) => match names_contains(seen, x) {
      True => Some(x),
      False => first_duplicate_go(Cons(x, seen), rest)
    }
  };

// resolve_ctors: for each surface `Ctor`, resolve every field `TypeRef` with the decl's type params
// in scope (reusing the `resolve_ty`/`resolve_args` family), refusing a duplicate constructor name.
// Mirrors checkty.rs::resolve_ctors arm-for-arm: the `seen` list carries the ctor-names-to-the-left
// for the dup check (Rust's `ctors.iter().any(..)`), and the result preserves declaration order
// (prepend-on-return). Never-silent `Err` on a duplicate ctor and on any field-resolution failure
// (G2/VR-5). The resolve_ty guarantee slot is discarded exactly as in Rust (`let (ty, _) = ..`).
fn resolve_ctors(types: Vec[DataInfo], td: TypeDecl) => Result[Vec[CtorInfo], Bytes] =
  resolve_ctors_go(types, td_params(td), Nil, td_ctors(td));

fn resolve_ctors_go(types: Vec[DataInfo], tyvars: Vec[Bytes], seen: Vec[Bytes], cs: Vec[Ctor])
    => Result[Vec[CtorInfo], Bytes] =
  match cs {
    Nil => Ok(Nil),
    Cons(c, rest) => match names_contains(seen, ct_name(c)) {
      True => Err(bytes_concat("duplicate constructor `", bytes_concat(ct_name(c), "`"))),
      False => match resolve_args(types, tyvars, ct_fields(c)) {
        Err(e) => Err(e),
        Ok(fields) => match resolve_ctors_go(types, tyvars, Cons(ct_name(c), seen), rest) {
          Err(e) => Err(e),
          Ok(more) => Ok(Cons(CI(ct_name(c), fields), more))
        }
      }
    }
  };

// ── register_types: build the type registry from a nodule (checkty.rs::register_types; M-1013 STEP 3, PR-2/PR-2b) ──
// FULL Nodule/Item mirrors (PR-2b, closing FLAG-semcore-30). `register_types`' OWN two-pass
// registration reads only `Item::Type`, but the M-826 tuple pre-pass `collect_tuple_arities` walks the
// tuple-relevant CONTENT of every item kind (fn bodies, `match` patterns, fn/trait/impl signatures), so
// the mirror carries those variants field-for-field. Each variant mirrors `ast.rs::Item` verbatim; the
// three item kinds `collect_tuple_arities_item` skips (`Use(_) | Default(_) | Derive(_) => {}` — note
// the oracle skips `Derive` even though `DeriveDecl` carries a `for_ty`, so it collapses faithfully)
// share the single tuple-free `ItOther`. Field-for-field with ast.rs: `Nodule { path, std_sys, items }`.
//
// Object/InherentImpl reach `collect_tuple_arities` only when `register_types` is driven on a RAW
// nodule (as the marshalling differential does); the real `check_phylum` pipeline structurally
// desugars them to `Type + Impl + Fn` items in a Phase-0 pass BEFORE registration (checkty.rs
// `check_phylum_inner`), so in production their tuples arrive via the desugared items. Porting the arms
// anyway keeps the port arm-for-arm faithful to `collect_tuple_arities` itself (never a silent gap — a
// raw-nodule caller gets exactly the oracle's answer).
type TraitDecl = TrD(Vis, Bytes, Vec[Bytes], Vec[FnSig]);

fn trd_sigs(t: TraitDecl) => Vec[FnSig] =
  match t { TrD(_, _, _, s) => s };

type ImplDecl = ImD(Bytes, Vec[TypeRef], TypeRef, Vec[FnDecl]);

fn imd_trait_args(i: ImplDecl) => Vec[TypeRef] =
  match i { ImD(_, a, _, _) => a };

fn imd_for_ty(i: ImplDecl) => TypeRef =
  match i { ImD(_, _, f, _) => f };

fn imd_methods(i: ImplDecl) => Vec[FnDecl] =
  match i { ImD(_, _, _, m) => m };

// DN-103 / M-1026: first field is the impl-level type-parameter slot (unbounded names, Nil for the
// plain M-664 block). The desugar-prepend is Rust-only (pre-desugared before this mirror runs).
type InherentImplDecl = IID(Vec[Bytes], TypeRef, Vec[FnDecl]);

fn iid_for_ty(i: InherentImplDecl) => TypeRef =
  match i { IID(_, f, _) => f };

fn iid_methods(i: InherentImplDecl) => Vec[FnDecl] =
  match i { IID(_, _, m) => m };

// ViaDecl: mirrors ast.rs::ViaDecl field-for-field (field_idx, trait_name, trait_args). No accessor —
// `collect_tuple_arities_item`'s Object arm does NOT walk `via_decls` (a dead field, kept only so
// `ObjectDecl` is field-for-field faithful; the oracle skips it too).
type ViaDecl = VD(Binary{32}, Bytes, Vec[TypeRef]);

type ObjectDecl = OD(Vis, Bytes, Vec[Bytes], Ctor, Vec[ViaDecl], Vec[ImplDecl], Vec[FnDecl]);

fn od_ctor(o: ObjectDecl) => Ctor =
  match o { OD(_, _, _, c, _, _, _) => c };

fn od_impls(o: ObjectDecl) => Vec[ImplDecl] =
  match o { OD(_, _, _, _, _, i, _) => i };

fn od_fns(o: ObjectDecl) => Vec[FnDecl] =
  match o { OD(_, _, _, _, _, _, f) => f };

// LowerRhs / LowerDecl: mirror ast.rs::LowerRhs / ast.rs::LowerDecl (DN-54 §10). Only `rhs` grades.
type LowerRhs = LrExpr(Expr) | LrImpl(ImplDecl);

type LowerDecl = LD(Bytes, Vec[Bytes], LowerRhs);

fn ld_rhs(l: LowerDecl) => LowerRhs =
  match l { LD(_, _, r) => r };

// UsePath: mirrors ast.rs::UsePath / ast.myc::UsePath field-for-field (`UP` ctor, same spelling as
// ast.myc — M-1013 STEP 4, resolve_imports increment). `path`: the imported path (a specific import
// names the item; a glob names the prefix whose `pub` names import). `glob`: true for `use a.b.*`.
type UsePath = UP(Path, Bool);

fn usepath_path(u: UsePath) => Path =
  match u { UP(p, _) => p };

fn usepath_glob(u: UsePath) => Bool =
  match u { UP(_, g) => g };

// Item gains ItUse (M-1013 STEP 4): the trimmed register-family mirror (FLAG-semcore-30's note)
// previously collapsed `Use`/`Default`/`Derive` into the single tuple-free `ItOther`, which was
// faithful for `collect_tuple_arities` (none of the three carry tuple-relevant content) but is NOT
// faithful for `resolve_imports`, which reads `Item::Use(UsePath)` directly (checkty.rs 1423-1533).
// `Default`/`Derive` remain folded into `ItOther` (still tuple-free and not read by resolve_imports).
type Item =
    ItType(TypeDecl)
  | ItFn(FnDecl)
  | ItTrait(TraitDecl)
  | ItImpl(ImplDecl)
  | ItObject(ObjectDecl)
  | ItLower(LowerDecl)
  | ItInherentImpl(InherentImplDecl)
  | ItUse(UsePath)
  | ItOther;
type Nodule = Nod(Path, Bool, Vec[Item]);

fn nodule_items(n: Nodule) => Vec[Item] =
  match n { Nod(_, _, its) => its };

// ── M-826 tuple pre-pass (checkty.rs::collect_tuple_arities — FULL walk, all legs) ─────────────────
// FLAG-semcore-30 CLOSED (M-1013 STEP 3, PR-2b). The pre-pass now walks EVERY leg the Rust oracle
// does, arm-for-arm: type-decl ctor fields, fn bodies (the `Expr` walk), `match` patterns (the
// `Pattern` walk), and fn/trait/impl signatures (the `FnSig` walk) — pre-registering every synthetic
// `Tuple$N` referenced anywhere in the nodule, so a tuple used ONLY in (say) a fn body or a `match`
// arm is registered before `resolve_ty` needs it. The never-silent floor is unchanged: any `Tuple$N`
// still missing at `resolve_ty` time is `resolve_tuple`'s explicit "synthetic tuple type ... not
// registered" `Err` (G2/VR-5). Arities are collected into a `Vec[Binary{32}]` (duplicates harmless —
// `register_tuple_arities` below is presence-checked, standing in for Rust's `BTreeSet` +
// `or_insert_with`; order-insensitive by the same token, so the threaded acc's order is irrelevant).
// No depth guard (matching the oracle: this is a pre-order SCAN, not evaluation — checkty.rs §793).
//
// `_typeref` / `_trefs` / `_ctors` (below) are unchanged from PR-2 — already arm-for-arm faithful to
// checkty.rs::collect_tuple_arities_typeref and its list folds; the new `_sig` / `_pattern` / `_expr`
// / `_item` legs reuse them.
fn collect_tuple_arities_typeref(t: TypeRef, acc: Vec[Binary{32}]) => Vec[Binary{32}] =
  match typeref_base(t) {
    Tuple(elems) => collect_tuple_arities_trefs(Cons(tref_len(elems), acc), elems),
    KwSeq(elem, _) => collect_tuple_arities_typeref(elem, acc),
    Named(_, args) => collect_tuple_arities_trefs(acc, args),
    FnArrow(a, b) => collect_tuple_arities_typeref(b, collect_tuple_arities_typeref(a, acc)),
    _ => acc
  };

fn collect_tuple_arities_trefs(acc: Vec[Binary{32}], ts: Vec[TypeRef]) => Vec[Binary{32}] =
  match ts {
    Nil => acc,
    Cons(h, rest) => collect_tuple_arities_trefs(collect_tuple_arities_typeref(h, acc), rest)
  };

fn collect_tuple_arities_ctors(acc: Vec[Binary{32}], cs: Vec[Ctor]) => Vec[Binary{32}] =
  match cs {
    Nil => acc,
    Cons(c, rest) => collect_tuple_arities_ctors(collect_tuple_arities_trefs(acc, ct_fields(c)), rest)
  };

// expr_len / pattern_len: monomorphic length counters (Vec[Expr] / Vec[Pattern]) — the tuple-literal /
// tuple-pattern arity (mirrors Rust's `elems.len()` / `subs.len()`; the tref_len/pat_len twins).
fn expr_len(v: Vec[Expr]) => Binary{32} =
  match v { Nil => zero32(), Cons(_, t) => add_u(one32(), expr_len(t)) };

fn pattern_len(v: Vec[Pattern]) => Binary{32} =
  match v { Nil => zero32(), Cons(_, t) => add_u(one32(), pattern_len(t)) };

// ── signature leg (checkty.rs::collect_tuple_arities_sig): each value-param type, then the return type.
fn collect_tuple_arities_params(acc: Vec[Binary{32}], ps: Vec[Param]) => Vec[Binary{32}] =
  match ps {
    Nil => acc,
    Cons(p, rest) => collect_tuple_arities_params(collect_tuple_arities_typeref(param_ty(p), acc), rest)
  };

fn collect_tuple_arities_sig(acc: Vec[Binary{32}], sig: FnSig) => Vec[Binary{32}] =
  collect_tuple_arities_typeref(fnsig_ret(sig), collect_tuple_arities_params(acc, fnsig_value_params(sig)));

fn collect_tuple_arities_sigs(acc: Vec[Binary{32}], sigs: Vec[FnSig]) => Vec[Binary{32}] =
  match sigs {
    Nil => acc,
    Cons(s, rest) => collect_tuple_arities_sigs(collect_tuple_arities_sig(acc, s), rest)
  };

// ── pattern leg (checkty.rs::collect_tuple_arities_pattern): a `PTuple` of arity N needs `Tuple$N`
// registered even when never constructed (M-826 self-review M1 — a destructured-only tuple). Recurses
// through ctor sub-patterns and or-pattern alternatives; PWildcard/PLit/PIdent are leaves.
fn collect_tuple_arities_pattern(acc: Vec[Binary{32}], p: Pattern) => Vec[Binary{32}] =
  match p {
    PTuple(subs) => collect_tuple_arities_patterns(Cons(pattern_len(subs), acc), subs),
    PCtor(_, subs) => collect_tuple_arities_patterns(acc, subs),
    POr(alts) => collect_tuple_arities_patterns(acc, alts),
    PWildcard => acc,
    PLit(_) => acc,
    PIdent(_) => acc
  };

fn collect_tuple_arities_patterns(acc: Vec[Binary{32}], ps: Vec[Pattern]) => Vec[Binary{32}] =
  match ps {
    Nil => acc,
    Cons(p, rest) => collect_tuple_arities_patterns(collect_tuple_arities_pattern(acc, p), rest)
  };

// collect_tuple_arities_opt_typeref: the `if let Some(t) = ty` guard on the `Let` arm's ascription.
fn collect_tuple_arities_opt_typeref(acc: Vec[Binary{32}], oty: Option[TypeRef]) => Vec[Binary{32}] =
  match oty { None => acc, Some(t) => collect_tuple_arities_typeref(t, acc) };

// ── expression leg (checkty.rs::collect_tuple_arities_expr): all 18 `Expr` variants, arm-for-arm.
// `TupleLit(elems)` inserts arity `elems.len()`; every other arm recurses into its sub-exprs / sub-types
// exactly as the oracle. `Path`/`Lit` are leaves — note the oracle does NOT recurse into `Lit`, so a
// tuple nested in a `List` literal is a leaf here too (faithful to checkty.rs §1007; VR-5, not "fixed").
fn collect_tuple_arities_expr(acc: Vec[Binary{32}], e: Expr) => Vec[Binary{32}] =
  match e {
    TupleLit(elems) => collect_tuple_arities_exprs(Cons(expr_len(elems), acc), elems),
    Let(_, oty, bound, body) =>
      collect_tuple_arities_expr(
        collect_tuple_arities_expr(collect_tuple_arities_opt_typeref(acc, oty), bound),
        body),
    If(cond, conseq, alt) =>
      collect_tuple_arities_expr(
        collect_tuple_arities_expr(collect_tuple_arities_expr(acc, cond), conseq),
        alt),
    Match(scrut, arms) => collect_tuple_arities_arms(collect_tuple_arities_expr(acc, scrut), arms),
    For(_, xs, _, init, body) =>
      collect_tuple_arities_expr(
        collect_tuple_arities_expr(collect_tuple_arities_expr(acc, xs), init),
        body),
    Swap(value, _, _) => collect_tuple_arities_expr(acc, value),
    WithParadigm(_, body) => collect_tuple_arities_expr(acc, body),
    Wild(b) => collect_tuple_arities_expr(acc, b),
    Spore(b) => collect_tuple_arities_expr(acc, b),
    Wrapping(b) => collect_tuple_arities_expr(acc, b),
    Consume(b) => collect_tuple_arities_expr(acc, b),
    Try(b) => collect_tuple_arities_expr(acc, b),
    Colony(hs) => collect_tuple_arities_hyphae(acc, hs),
    Lambda(ps, body) => collect_tuple_arities_expr(collect_tuple_arities_params(acc, ps), body),
    App(head, args) => collect_tuple_arities_exprs(collect_tuple_arities_expr(acc, head), args),
    Fuse(l, r) => collect_tuple_arities_expr(collect_tuple_arities_expr(acc, l), r),
    Reclaim(pol, body) => collect_tuple_arities_expr(collect_tuple_arities_expr(acc, pol), body),
    Path(_) => acc,
    Lit(_) => acc,
    Ascribe(inner, t) => collect_tuple_arities_typeref(t, collect_tuple_arities_expr(acc, inner))
  };

fn collect_tuple_arities_exprs(acc: Vec[Binary{32}], es: Vec[Expr]) => Vec[Binary{32}] =
  match es {
    Nil => acc,
    Cons(e, rest) => collect_tuple_arities_exprs(collect_tuple_arities_expr(acc, e), rest)
  };

fn collect_tuple_arities_arm(acc: Vec[Binary{32}], a: Arm) => Vec[Binary{32}] =
  collect_tuple_arities_expr(collect_tuple_arities_pattern(acc, arm_pattern(a)), arm_body(a));

fn collect_tuple_arities_arms(acc: Vec[Binary{32}], arms: Vec[Arm]) => Vec[Binary{32}] =
  match arms {
    Nil => acc,
    Cons(a, rest) => collect_tuple_arities_arms(collect_tuple_arities_arm(acc, a), rest)
  };

fn collect_tuple_arities_hyphae(acc: Vec[Binary{32}], hs: Vec[Hypha]) => Vec[Binary{32}] =
  match hs {
    Nil => acc,
    Cons(h, rest) => collect_tuple_arities_hyphae(collect_tuple_arities_expr(acc, hypha_body(h)), rest)
  };

// ── fn-decl + impl legs (the sig+body pair, and the trait_args+for_ty+methods bundle reused by the
// Impl / Object / Lower(Impl) arms) — checkty.rs::collect_tuple_arities_item's shared inner loops.
fn collect_tuple_arities_fndecl(acc: Vec[Binary{32}], fd: FnDecl) => Vec[Binary{32}] =
  collect_tuple_arities_expr(collect_tuple_arities_sig(acc, fndecl_sig(fd)), fndecl_body(fd));

fn collect_tuple_arities_fndecls(acc: Vec[Binary{32}], fds: Vec[FnDecl]) => Vec[Binary{32}] =
  match fds {
    Nil => acc,
    Cons(fd, rest) => collect_tuple_arities_fndecls(collect_tuple_arities_fndecl(acc, fd), rest)
  };

fn collect_tuple_arities_impl(acc: Vec[Binary{32}], id: ImplDecl) => Vec[Binary{32}] =
  collect_tuple_arities_fndecls(
    collect_tuple_arities_typeref(imd_for_ty(id), collect_tuple_arities_trefs(acc, imd_trait_args(id))),
    imd_methods(id));

fn collect_tuple_arities_impls(acc: Vec[Binary{32}], ids: Vec[ImplDecl]) => Vec[Binary{32}] =
  match ids {
    Nil => acc,
    Cons(id, rest) => collect_tuple_arities_impls(collect_tuple_arities_impl(acc, id), rest)
  };

// collect_tuple_arities_item: checkty.rs::collect_tuple_arities_item, arm-for-arm. `ItOther` (Use /
// Default / Derive) is the oracle's `=> {}` no-op. Object/InherentImpl are pre-desugared in the real
// pipeline (see the mirror header above) but ported faithfully for a raw-nodule caller.
fn collect_tuple_arities_item(acc: Vec[Binary{32}], it: Item) => Vec[Binary{32}] =
  match it {
    ItType(td) => collect_tuple_arities_ctors(acc, td_ctors(td)),
    ItFn(fd) => collect_tuple_arities_fndecl(acc, fd),
    ItTrait(tr) => collect_tuple_arities_sigs(acc, trd_sigs(tr)),
    ItImpl(id) => collect_tuple_arities_impl(acc, id),
    ItObject(od) =>
      collect_tuple_arities_fndecls(
        collect_tuple_arities_impls(
          collect_tuple_arities_trefs(acc, ct_fields(od_ctor(od))),
          od_impls(od)),
        od_fns(od)),
    ItLower(ld) => match ld_rhs(ld) {
      LrExpr(e) => collect_tuple_arities_expr(acc, e),
      LrImpl(id) => collect_tuple_arities_impl(acc, id)
    },
    ItInherentImpl(iid) =>
      collect_tuple_arities_fndecls(collect_tuple_arities_typeref(iid_for_ty(iid), acc), iid_methods(iid)),
    ItUse(_) => acc,
    ItOther => acc
  };

// collect_tuple_arities: the FULL walk — every item's tuple-relevant content (checkty.rs §793).
fn collect_tuple_arities(items: Vec[Item], acc: Vec[Binary{32}]) => Vec[Binary{32}] =
  match items {
    Nil => acc,
    Cons(it, rest) => collect_tuple_arities(rest, collect_tuple_arities_item(acc, it))
  };

// register_tuple_arities: pre-register a synthetic `Tuple$N` for each collected arity, but only if
// absent (checkty.rs's `types.entry(tname).or_insert_with(|| synthetic_tuple_data(arity))`). A
// duplicate arity in `arities` is a no-op the second time (the presence check dedups it).
fn register_tuple_arities(types: Vec[DataInfo], arities: Vec[Binary{32}]) => Vec[DataInfo] =
  match arities {
    Nil => types,
    Cons(n, rest) => match types_lookup(types, tuple_type_name(n)) {
      Some(_) => register_tuple_arities(types, rest),
      None => register_tuple_arities(Cons(synthetic_tuple_data(n), types), rest)
    }
  };

// register_shells: Pass 1 — a shell `DI(name, params, Nil)` per `Item::Type` so recursive/forward
// field references resolve (checkty.rs's first loop). Never-silent refusals, in Rust's exact order:
// a duplicate type PARAMETER (`first_duplicate`) is checked FIRST, then a duplicate type NAME
// (`types_lookup` over the accumulated registry — which includes the seeded prelude, so redeclaring
// `Bool` collides exactly as in Rust). EVERY non-Type item is skipped — the faithful mirror of the
// oracle's `if let Item::Type(td) = item` (only a type declaration declares a data type; the
// un-trimmed Fn/Trait/Impl/Object/Lower/InherentImpl/`ItOther` kinds are all non-declarations here).
fn register_shells(types: Vec[DataInfo], items: Vec[Item]) => Result[Vec[DataInfo], Bytes] =
  match items {
    Nil => Ok(types),
    Cons(it, rest) => match it {
      ItType(td) => match first_duplicate(td_params(td)) {
        Some(dup) => Err(bytes_concat("duplicate type parameter `", bytes_concat(dup, bytes_concat("` in `", bytes_concat(td_name(td), "`"))))),
        None => match types_lookup(types, td_name(td)) {
          Some(_) => Err("duplicate type declaration"),
          None => register_shells(Cons(DI(td_name(td), td_params(td), Nil), types), rest)
        }
      },
      _ => register_shells(types, rest)
    }
  };

// types_set_ctors: replace the ctors of the (shell) entry named `name`, preserving its params —
// checkty.rs's `types.get_mut(&td.name).expect("registered above").ctors = ctors`. `register_shells`
// registered every `Item::Type`, so `name` is always present; a not-found (invariant-impossible)
// entry leaves the list unchanged (the wild-free, value-threaded analogue of Rust's `.expect`: no
// panic, no silent fabrication — G2).
fn types_set_ctors(types: Vec[DataInfo], name: Bytes, ctors: Vec[CtorInfo]) => Vec[DataInfo] =
  match types {
    Nil => Nil,
    Cons(d, rest) => match bytes_eq(di_name(d), name) {
      0b1 => Cons(DI(name, di_params(d), ctors), rest),
      _ => Cons(d, types_set_ctors(rest, name, ctors))
    }
  };

// fill_ctors: Pass 2 — resolve each `Item::Type`'s ctors (all shells now present) and write them into
// the registry (checkty.rs's second loop). Never-silent: any field-resolution or duplicate-ctor
// failure short-circuits to `Err` (reusing PR-1's `resolve_ctors`).
fn fill_ctors(types: Vec[DataInfo], items: Vec[Item]) => Result[Vec[DataInfo], Bytes] =
  match items {
    Nil => Ok(types),
    Cons(it, rest) => match it {
      ItType(td) => match resolve_ctors(types, td) {
        Err(e) => Err(e),
        Ok(ctors) => fill_ctors(types_set_ctors(types, td_name(td), ctors), rest)
      },
      _ => fill_ctors(types, rest)
    }
  };

// register_types: the two-pass data-declaration registration, value-threaded over the assoc-list
// registry (checkty.rs::register_types). Order matches Rust exactly: (0) the FULL M-826 tuple pre-pass
// (all legs — FLAG-semcore-30 CLOSED, PR-2b), (1) shell-register each type, (2) fill each type's ctors.
// Returns the mutated registry or the first never-silent refusal.
fn register_types(types: Vec[DataInfo], nod: Nodule) => Result[Vec[DataInfo], Bytes] =
  let items = nodule_items(nod) in
  let with_tuples = register_tuple_arities(types, collect_tuple_arities(items, Nil)) in
  match register_shells(with_tuples, items) {
    Err(e) => Err(e),
    Ok(shelled) => fill_ctors(shelled, items)
  };

// ── register_traits: the TRAIT pass (checkty.rs::register_traits 3016-3083; M-1013 STEP 3) ─────────
// Ports checkty.rs's two-pass trait registration, value-threaded over an assoc-list registry
// `Vec[TraitInfo]` (the FLAG-semcore-4 stand-in for `BTreeMap<String, TraitInfo>`, exactly as
// `register_types` stands in for the types map). Arm-for-arm with the oracle:
//   * PASS 1 (`register_traits_pass1`, mirroring checkty.rs 3021-3057) — for each `Item::Trait(td)`:
//     reject a duplicate type PARAMETER (`first_duplicate(td.params)`, 3024), a duplicate trait NAME
//     (`traits.contains_key`, 3030), and a within-trait duplicate METHOD name (3034-3041); then check
//     every method signature RESOLVES with the trait's params extended by the method's OWN type-param
//     names in scope as tyvars (3042-3047), and insert `TraitInfo{name, params, sigs}` (3049-3056).
//   * PASS 2 (`register_traits_bounds`, mirroring checkty.rs 3063-3081) — over the COMPLETE registry,
//     so a bound may forward-reference a later trait: every method type-parameter BOUND must name a
//     KNOWN trait (3067). An unknown bound is an explicit never-silent `Err` (G2/VR-5), never a
//     silently-registered ill-formed requirement.
// Registry ORDER is insertion-reversed (prepend `Cons`) vs the oracle's sorted `BTreeMap`; every
// consumer here is order-insensitive (`traits_contains` is set-membership; the differential decodes
// the returned `Vec` into a name-keyed map), and pass 2 returns Ok or the FIRST refusal only — so the
// port and the oracle agree on Ok / any-refusal regardless of order. Guarantee: `Declared` (a
// structural registry check, not a theorem — checkty.rs 3010's LR-2 tag).

// TraitInfo: mirrors checkty.rs::TraitInfo (264-272) — { name, params (tyvar names), sigs (SURFACE
// FnSigs, stored verbatim) }. Modeled as a presence-checked `Vec[TraitInfo]` keyed by name, exactly
// as `register_types`' output is a `Vec[DataInfo]` (NOT a map).
type TraitInfo = TrInfo(Bytes, Vec[Bytes], Vec[FnSig]);

fn trinfo_name(t: TraitInfo) => Bytes =
  match t { TrInfo(n, _, _) => n };

fn trinfo_sigs(t: TraitInfo) => Vec[FnSig] =
  match t { TrInfo(_, _, s) => s };

// TraitDecl accessors: name (field 1) / params (field 2). `trd_sigs` (field 3) already exists above;
// `td_name`/`td_params` are TypeDecl's, so TraitDecl needs its own (distinct ADT).
fn trd_name(t: TraitDecl) => Bytes =
  match t { TrD(_, n, _, _) => n };

fn trd_params(t: TraitDecl) => Vec[Bytes] =
  match t { TrD(_, _, p, _) => p };

// FnSig type-params accessor (FS field 1) — the 3 grade accessors above (name/value_params/ret)
// omitted it as unused; the trait pass needs it (method type-params → tyvar scope + bound checks).
fn fnsig_type_params(s: FnSig) => Vec[TypeParam] =
  match s { FS(_, tps, _, _, _, _) => tps };

// TypeParam / TraitRef accessors (checkty.rs reads `tp.name` / `tp.kind` / `tp.bounds` / `b.name`).
fn tp_name(t: TypeParam) => Bytes =
  match t { TP(n, _, _) => n };

fn tp_kind(t: TypeParam) => ParamKind =
  match t { TP(_, k, _) => k };

fn tp_bounds(t: TypeParam) => Vec[TraitRef] =
  match t { TP(_, _, b) => b };

fn traitref_name(r: TraitRef) => Bytes =
  match r { TRf(n, _) => n };

// fnsig_tyvar_names: mirrors FnSig::param_names (ast.rs 447-460) — the method's TYPE-kind type-param
// names only (width params are dropped; they cannot stand in the tyvar scope, DN-42 §7). Distinct
// from the value-parameter `param_names(Vec[Param])` above (that maps `Vec[Param]`; this filters
// `Vec[TypeParam]` by `PkType`).
fn fnsig_tyvar_names(s: FnSig) => Vec[Bytes] =
  type_param_type_names(fnsig_type_params(s));

fn type_param_type_names(tps: Vec[TypeParam]) => Vec[Bytes] =
  match tps {
    Nil => Nil,
    Cons(tp, rest) => match tp_kind(tp) {
      PkType => Cons(tp_name(tp), type_param_type_names(rest)),
      _ => type_param_type_names(rest)
    }
  };

// traits_contains: `traits.contains_key(name)` over the assoc-list registry (set membership by name).
fn traits_contains(traits: Vec[TraitInfo], name: Bytes) => Bool =
  match traits {
    Nil => False,
    Cons(tr, rest) => match bytes_eq(trinfo_name(tr), name) {
      0b1 => True,
      _ => traits_contains(rest, name)
    }
  };

// check_sig_resolves: checkty.rs 3088-3099 — every value-param type, then the ret, must `resolve_ty`
// under `tyvars`; `Ok(True)` (a unit sentinel; the resolved types + their guarantee slot are
// discarded exactly as Rust's `resolve_ty(...)?` ignores its value) or the FIRST `Err`.
fn check_sig_resolves(types: Vec[DataInfo], tyvars: Vec[Bytes], sig: FnSig) => Result[Bool, Bytes] =
  match check_params_resolve(types, tyvars, fnsig_value_params(sig)) {
    Err(e) => Err(e),
    Ok(_) => match resolve_ty(types, tyvars, fnsig_ret(sig)) {
      Err(e) => Err(e),
      Ok(_) => Ok(True)
    }
  };

fn check_params_resolve(types: Vec[DataInfo], tyvars: Vec[Bytes], params: Vec[Param]) => Result[Bool, Bytes] =
  match params {
    Nil => Ok(True),
    Cons(p, rest) => match resolve_ty(types, tyvars, param_ty(p)) {
      Err(e) => Err(e),
      Ok(_) => check_params_resolve(types, tyvars, rest)
    }
  };

// register_traits: the two-pass entry (checkty.rs 3016-3083). Returns the registry or the first refusal.
fn register_traits(types: Vec[DataInfo], nod: Nodule) => Result[Vec[TraitInfo], Bytes] =
  match register_traits_pass1(types, Nil, nodule_items(nod)) {
    Err(e) => Err(e),
    Ok(traits) => match register_traits_bounds(traits, traits) {
      Err(e) => Err(e),
      Ok(_) => Ok(traits)
    }
  };

// PASS 1 — checkty.rs 3021-3057. Every non-Trait item is skipped (the mirror of `let Item::Trait(td)
// = item else { continue }`); each trait's checks run in the oracle's order (dup param -> dup name ->
// method checks -> insert).
fn register_traits_pass1(types: Vec[DataInfo], acc: Vec[TraitInfo], items: Vec[Item]) => Result[Vec[TraitInfo], Bytes] =
  match items {
    Nil => Ok(acc),
    Cons(it, rest) => match it {
      ItTrait(td) => match first_duplicate(trd_params(td)) {
        Some(dup) => Err(bytes_concat("duplicate type parameter `", bytes_concat(dup, bytes_concat("` in trait `", bytes_concat(trd_name(td), "`"))))),
        None => match traits_contains(acc, trd_name(td)) {
          True => Err("duplicate trait declaration"),
          False => match check_trait_methods(types, trd_name(td), trd_params(td), Nil, trd_sigs(td)) {
            Err(e) => Err(e),
            Ok(_) => register_traits_pass1(types, Cons(TrInfo(trd_name(td), trd_params(td), trd_sigs(td)), acc), rest)
          }
        }
      },
      _ => register_traits_pass1(types, acc, rest)
    }
  };

// check_trait_methods: the within-trait method loop (checkty.rs 3034-3048). `seen` tracks distinct
// method names; each sig resolves with `tyvars = trait.params ++ method.param_names()` (3045-3046).
fn check_trait_methods(types: Vec[DataInfo], trait_name: Bytes, params: Vec[Bytes], seen: Vec[Bytes], sigs: Vec[FnSig]) => Result[Bool, Bytes] =
  match sigs {
    Nil => Ok(True),
    Cons(s, rest) => match names_contains(seen, fnsig_name(s)) {
      True => Err(bytes_concat("duplicate method `", bytes_concat(fnsig_name(s), bytes_concat("` in trait `", bytes_concat(trait_name, "`"))))),
      False => match check_sig_resolves(types, names_append(params, fnsig_tyvar_names(s)), s) {
        Err(e) => Err(e),
        Ok(_) => check_trait_methods(types, trait_name, params, Cons(fnsig_name(s), seen), rest)
      }
    }
  };

// PASS 2 — checkty.rs 3063-3081. Over the COMPLETE registry (`all`), so a bound may forward-reference
// a later-declared trait. Every method type-parameter bound must name a KNOWN trait, else an explicit
// refusal naming the site + the offending bound (mirroring the oracle's message shape).
fn register_traits_bounds(all: Vec[TraitInfo], traits: Vec[TraitInfo]) => Result[Bool, Bytes] =
  match traits {
    Nil => Ok(True),
    Cons(tr, rest) => match check_trait_sig_bounds(all, trinfo_name(tr), trinfo_sigs(tr)) {
      Err(e) => Err(e),
      Ok(_) => register_traits_bounds(all, rest)
    }
  };

fn check_trait_sig_bounds(all: Vec[TraitInfo], trname: Bytes, sigs: Vec[FnSig]) => Result[Bool, Bytes] =
  match sigs {
    Nil => Ok(True),
    Cons(s, rest) => match check_sig_tp_bounds(all, trname, fnsig_name(s), fnsig_type_params(s)) {
      Err(e) => Err(e),
      Ok(_) => check_trait_sig_bounds(all, trname, rest)
    }
  };

fn check_sig_tp_bounds(all: Vec[TraitInfo], trname: Bytes, method: Bytes, tps: Vec[TypeParam]) => Result[Bool, Bytes] =
  match tps {
    Nil => Ok(True),
    Cons(tp, rest) => match check_tp_bounds(all, trname, method, tp_name(tp), tp_bounds(tp)) {
      Err(e) => Err(e),
      Ok(_) => check_sig_tp_bounds(all, trname, method, rest)
    }
  };

// unknown_bound_msg: the never-silent refusal text for pass 2 (checkty.rs 3068-3076) — names the site
// (`trait <T> method <m>`) and the offending bound (`<param>: <bound>`). Built in `let`-pieces to keep
// the concatenation legibly balanced.
fn unknown_bound_msg(trname: Bytes, method: Bytes, pname: Bytes, bound: Bytes) => Bytes =
  let a = bytes_concat("trait `", bytes_concat(trname, "` method `")) in
  let b = bytes_concat(method, bytes_concat("`: unknown trait `", bound)) in
  let c = bytes_concat("` in the bound `", bytes_concat(pname, bytes_concat(": ", bound))) in
  bytes_concat(a, bytes_concat(b, bytes_concat(c, "` (RFC-0019 SS4.1 -- a method's type-parameter bound must name a declared trait)")));

fn check_tp_bounds(all: Vec[TraitInfo], trname: Bytes, method: Bytes, pname: Bytes, bounds: Vec[TraitRef]) => Result[Bool, Bytes] =
  match bounds {
    Nil => Ok(True),
    Cons(b, rest) => match traits_contains(all, traitref_name(b)) {
      True => check_tp_bounds(all, trname, method, pname, rest),
      False => Err(unknown_bound_msg(trname, method, pname, traitref_name(b)))
    }
  };

// ── register_instances: the IMPL pass — registration + coherence (checkty.rs::register_instances ──
// 3116-3238; M-1013 STEP 3, PR-3). Ports checkty.rs's impl-registration/coherence pass, value-threaded
// over an assoc-list instance registry `Vec[InstanceInfo]` (the FLAG-semcore-4 stand-in for
// `BTreeMap<(String,String), InstanceInfo>` keyed by `(trait_name, type_head(for_ty))`, exactly as
// `register_types`/`register_traits` stand in for their maps). Arm-for-arm with the oracle, in the
// EXACT order (checkty.rs 3131-3235): for each `Item::Impl(id)` --
//   (1) the trait must EXIST in `traits` (3135-3143) else "unknown trait";
//   (2) resolve `for_ty` and each `trait_arg` CONCRETELY (empty tyvars -- 3146-3150);
//   (3) ARITY: `trait_args.len() == tr.params.len()` (3152-3163) else refuse;
//   (4) `type_head(for_ty)` must be `Some` (3165-3174) else "bare type variable is not a legal head";
//   (5) ORPHAN rule -- phylum-wide, pub-blind (M-662; 3175-3209): legal iff `trait_local`
//       (coherence.traits has the trait) OR `type_local` (for_ty is a `Data` in coherence.types, OR a
//       primitive repr -- Binary/Ternary/Dense/Vsa/Substrate/Seq/Bytes/Float -> true; Var/Fn -> false),
//       else orphan refusal;
//   (6) GLOBAL UNIQUENESS: `(trait_name, head)` must be free (3210-3224) else overlapping-instance;
//   (7) `check_impl_method_set` -- the impl's method-name SET must EXACTLY match the trait's required
//       sig names (3225-3226 / 3243-3284): a missing OR extra method (and a duplicate) is refused;
//   (8) insert `InstanceInfo{trait_name, trait_args, for_ty, methods = id.methods.map(m.sig.name)}`.
// Every refusal is never-silent (G2/VR-5), mirroring the oracle's site + reason. Registry ORDER is
// insertion-reversed (prepend `Cons`) vs the oracle's sorted `BTreeMap`; every consumer is
// order-insensitive (uniqueness is a `(trait, head)` membership scan; the differential decodes the
// returned `Vec` into a `(trait, head)`-keyed map), and the loop returns `Ok` or the FIRST refusal
// only -- so port and oracle agree on Ok / any-refusal regardless of order. Guarantee: `Declared` --
// the coherence argument is Declared-with-argument per RFC-0019/LR-2 (checkty.rs 3101-3102's tag),
// NOT machine-checked; the port keeps the oracle's tag (never upgraded -- VR-5).

// InstanceInfo: mirrors checkty.rs::InstanceInfo (277-286) -- { trait_name, trait_args (concrete Ty),
// for_ty (concrete Ty), methods (provided method names) }. Modeled as a presence-checked
// `Vec[InstanceInfo]` keyed by `(trait_name, type_head(for_ty))`, exactly as the other register-family
// outputs are Vecs (NOT maps).
type InstanceInfo = InstInfo(Bytes, Vec[Ty], Ty, Vec[Bytes]);

fn instinfo_trait_name(i: InstanceInfo) => Bytes =
  match i { InstInfo(n, _, _, _) => n };

fn instinfo_for_ty(i: InstanceInfo) => Ty =
  match i { InstInfo(_, _, f, _) => f };

// CoherenceView: mirrors checkty.rs::CoherenceView (1318-1323) -- the pub-blind phylum-wide name view
// the orphan rule reads: (all trait names, all data-type names), each a `Vec[Bytes]` name-list (the
// FLAG-semcore-4 assoc-list stand-in for the oracle's two `BTreeSet<String>`; membership via
// `names_contains`).
type CoherenceView = CV(Vec[Bytes], Vec[Bytes]);

fn cv_traits(c: CoherenceView) => Vec[Bytes] =
  match c { CV(t, _) => t };

fn cv_types(c: CoherenceView) => Vec[Bytes] =
  match c { CV(_, t) => t };

// ImplDecl trait-name accessor (ImD field 1) -- the register-family tuple pre-pass read only
// args/for_ty/methods; the impl pass needs the trait name (lookup + instance key + messages).
fn imd_trait_name(i: ImplDecl) => Bytes =
  match i { ImD(n, _, _, _) => n };

// TraitInfo params accessor (TrInfo field 2) -- the trait pass registered it; the arity check reads it.
fn trinfo_params(t: TraitInfo) => Vec[Bytes] =
  match t { TrInfo(_, p, _) => p };

// traits_lookup: `traits.get(name)` over the assoc-list registry (the ENTRY, not just membership --
// register_instances needs the `TraitInfo` for the arity + method-set checks).
fn traits_lookup(traits: Vec[TraitInfo], name: Bytes) => Option[TraitInfo] =
  match traits {
    Nil => None,
    Cons(tr, rest) => match bytes_eq(trinfo_name(tr), name) {
      0b1 => Some(tr),
      _ => traits_lookup(rest, name)
    }
  };

// impl_method_names / trait_required_names: the impl's provided method NAMES (`m.sig.name`, i.e.
// `fnsig_name(fndecl_sig(m))`) and the trait's required method NAMES (`s.name` over the trait's sigs) --
// the two name-sets `check_impl_method_set` compares (checkty.rs 3245-3248).
fn impl_method_names(id: ImplDecl) => Vec[Bytes] =
  method_sig_names(imd_methods(id));

fn method_sig_names(ms: Vec[FnDecl]) => Vec[Bytes] =
  match ms {
    Nil => Nil,
    Cons(m, rest) => Cons(fnsig_name(fndecl_sig(m)), method_sig_names(rest))
  };

fn trait_required_names(sigs: Vec[FnSig]) => Vec[Bytes] =
  match sigs {
    Nil => Nil,
    Cons(s, rest) => Cons(fnsig_name(s), trait_required_names(rest))
  };

// check_impl_method_set: the impl's method SET must EXACTLY match the trait's requirement SET
// (checkty.rs::check_impl_method_set 3243-3284). In the oracle's ORDER: (a) every required name is
// provided (else "missing method"); (b) every provided name is required (else "has method ... not in
// trait"); (c) no provided name appears twice (else "provides ... more than once"). All three are
// explicit never-silent refusals (G2) -- never a silently-filled or silently-dropped method.
fn check_impl_method_set(tr: TraitInfo, id: ImplDecl) => Result[Bool, Bytes] =
  let required = trait_required_names(trinfo_sigs(tr)) in
  let provided = impl_method_names(id) in
  match check_methods_present(trinfo_name(tr), required, provided) {
    Err(e) => Err(e),
    Ok(_) => match check_methods_no_extra(trinfo_name(tr), required, provided) {
      Err(e) => Err(e),
      Ok(_) => match first_duplicate(provided) {
        Some(dup) => Err(bytes_concat("impl of `", bytes_concat(trinfo_name(tr), bytes_concat("` provides method `", bytes_concat(dup, "` more than once"))))),
        None => Ok(True)
      }
    }
  };

// (a) every required method name must be present in `provided` (checkty.rs 3249-3256).
fn check_methods_present(trname: Bytes, required: Vec[Bytes], provided: Vec[Bytes]) => Result[Bool, Bytes] =
  match required {
    Nil => Ok(True),
    Cons(need, rest) => match names_contains(provided, need) {
      True => check_methods_present(trname, rest, provided),
      False => Err(bytes_concat("impl of `", bytes_concat(trname, bytes_concat("` is missing method `", bytes_concat(need, "`")))))
    }
  };

// (b) every provided method name must be required -- no extra methods (checkty.rs 3257-3267).
fn check_methods_no_extra(trname: Bytes, required: Vec[Bytes], provided: Vec[Bytes]) => Result[Bool, Bytes] =
  match provided {
    Nil => Ok(True),
    Cons(have, rest) => match names_contains(required, have) {
      True => check_methods_no_extra(trname, required, rest),
      False => Err(bytes_concat("impl of `", bytes_concat(trname, bytes_concat("` has method `", bytes_concat(have, bytes_concat("` not in trait `", bytes_concat(trname, "`")))))))
    }
  };

// type_local: the orphan rule's `type_local` arm (checkty.rs 3182-3198), matching the `for_ty` variant
// EXACTLY as the oracle -- a `Data` head is local iff its name is in coherence.types; every primitive
// repr (Binary/Ternary/Dense/Vsa/Substrate/Seq/Bytes/Float) is phylum-owned (always true); `Var`/`Fn`
// are not legal heads (false -- kept for exhaustiveness, never a silent accept, G2; `type_head` refuses
// them upstream so these two arms are unreachable in practice).
fn type_local(coherence_types: Vec[Bytes], for_ty: Ty) => Bool =
  match for_ty {
    TyData(n, _) => names_contains(coherence_types, n),
    TyBinary(_) => True,
    TyTernary(_) => True,
    TyDense(_, _) => True,
    TyVsa(_, _, _) => True,
    TySubstrate(_) => True,
    TySeq(_, _) => True,
    TyBytes => True,
    TyFloat => True,
    TyVar(_) => False,
    TyFn(_, _) => False
  };

// orphan_ok: legal iff trait_local OR type_local (checkty.rs 3181-3199).
fn orphan_ok(coherence: CoherenceView, trait_name: Bytes, for_ty: Ty) => Bool =
  match names_contains(cv_traits(coherence), trait_name) {
    True => True,
    False => type_local(cv_types(coherence), for_ty)
  };

// instance_head_eq: does `for_ty`'s head equal `head`? A stored instance always has a `Some` head (it
// passed the type_head check), so the `None` arm is an unreachable-in-practice `False` -- never a
// silent match (G2).
fn instance_head_eq(for_ty: Ty, head: Bytes) => Bool =
  match type_head(for_ty) {
    Some(h) => beq(h, head),
    None => False
  };

// instances_contains_key: `instances.contains_key((trait_name, head))` over the assoc-list registry --
// the global-uniqueness scan (checkty.rs 3213-3214). The stored `(trait, head)` is recomputed from the
// instance's `for_ty` (the registry keeps the full for_ty, not the erased head).
fn instances_contains_key(acc: Vec[InstanceInfo], trait_name: Bytes, head: Bytes) => Bool =
  match acc {
    Nil => False,
    Cons(inst, rest) => match and_(beq(instinfo_trait_name(inst), trait_name), instance_head_eq(instinfo_for_ty(inst), head)) {
      True => True,
      False => instances_contains_key(rest, trait_name, head)
    }
  };

// register_instances: the two-level loop (checkty.rs 3130-3237). Returns the instance registry or the
// FIRST refusal. `register_one_instance` threads the accumulated registry so the uniqueness scan sees
// earlier-registered instances (the oracle's growing `BTreeMap`).
fn register_instances(types: Vec[DataInfo], traits: Vec[TraitInfo], coherence: CoherenceView, nod: Nodule) => Result[Vec[InstanceInfo], Bytes] =
  register_instances_go(types, traits, coherence, Nil, nodule_items(nod));

fn register_instances_go(types: Vec[DataInfo], traits: Vec[TraitInfo], coherence: CoherenceView, acc: Vec[InstanceInfo], items: Vec[Item]) => Result[Vec[InstanceInfo], Bytes] =
  match items {
    Nil => Ok(acc),
    Cons(it, rest) => match it {
      ItImpl(id) => match register_one_instance(types, traits, coherence, acc, id) {
        Err(e) => Err(e),
        Ok(acc2) => register_instances_go(types, traits, coherence, acc2, rest)
      },
      _ => register_instances_go(types, traits, coherence, acc, rest)
    }
  };

// register_one_instance: the per-impl body (checkty.rs 3132-3235) -- the eight checks in the oracle's
// EXACT order. `resolve_ty`'s guarantee slot is discarded (`let (for_ty, _) = ..`), matching the oracle.
fn register_one_instance(types: Vec[DataInfo], traits: Vec[TraitInfo], coherence: CoherenceView, acc: Vec[InstanceInfo], id: ImplDecl) => Result[Vec[InstanceInfo], Bytes] =
  match traits_lookup(traits, imd_trait_name(id)) {
    None => Err(bytes_concat("`impl` for unknown trait `", bytes_concat(imd_trait_name(id), "` (RFC-0019 SS4.5)"))),
    Some(tr) => match resolve_ty(types, Nil, imd_for_ty(id)) {
      Err(e) => Err(e),
      Ok(forpr) => match forpr { Pr(for_ty, _) =>
        match resolve_args(types, Nil, imd_trait_args(id)) {
          Err(e) => Err(e),
          Ok(trait_args) => match eq_u(ty_len(trait_args), names_len(trinfo_params(tr))) {
            False => Err(arity_mismatch_msg(trinfo_name(tr), names_len(trinfo_params(tr)), ty_len(trait_args))),
            True => match type_head(for_ty) {
              None => Err("an `impl ... for` a bare type variable / function type is not a legal instance head in stage-1 (no blanket instances -- RFC-0019 SS4.5); the `for` type must be concrete"),
              Some(head) => match orphan_ok(coherence, imd_trait_name(id), for_ty) {
                False => Err(orphan_msg(imd_trait_name(id))),
                True => match instances_contains_key(acc, imd_trait_name(id), head) {
                  True => Err(overlapping_msg(imd_trait_name(id), head)),
                  False => match check_impl_method_set(tr, id) {
                    Err(e) => Err(e),
                    Ok(_) => Ok(Cons(InstInfo(imd_trait_name(id), trait_args, for_ty, impl_method_names(id)), acc))
                  }
                }
              }
            }
          }
        }
      }
    }
  };

// The three never-silent refusal messages, mirroring the oracle's site + reason wording (checkty.rs
// 3152-3163 / 3199-3209 / 3214-3224). Built in `bytes_concat` pieces (the file's established idiom).
fn arity_mismatch_msg(trname: Bytes, want: Binary{32}, got: Binary{32}) => Bytes =
  bytes_concat("trait `", bytes_concat(trname, bytes_concat("` takes ", bytes_concat(dec_u32(want), bytes_concat(" type argument(s), but this `impl` supplies ", bytes_concat(dec_u32(got), " (RFC-0019 SS4.5)"))))));

fn orphan_msg(trname: Bytes) => Bytes =
  bytes_concat("orphan instance: `impl ", bytes_concat(trname, " for ...` -- neither the trait nor the `for` type is declared in any nodule of this phylum (RFC-0019 SS4.5 orphan rule, phylum-wide; M-662)"));

fn overlapping_msg(trname: Bytes, head: Bytes) => Bytes =
  bytes_concat("overlapping instance -- coherence/global-uniqueness violation (RFC-0019 SS4.5): a second `impl ", bytes_concat(trname, bytes_concat(" for` a `", bytes_concat(head, "` type. Stage-1 keys per (trait, type-head), so two instances on the same head conflict"))));

// ── unify: one-sided unification, threading the FLAG-semcore-13 substitution (checkty.rs::unify) ──
// same_ty_len: the `a1.len() == a2.len()` guard on the Data arm (a two-list structural length eq).
fn same_ty_len(a: Vec[Ty], b: Vec[Ty]) => Bool =
  match a {
    Nil => match b { Nil => True, Cons(_, _) => False },
    Cons(_, ta) => match b { Nil => False, Cons(_, tb) => same_ty_len(ta, tb) }
  };

// The `_ if decl == actual` fallback (arm 8) + the `_ => Err` mismatch (arm 9), and the collapsed
// FLAG-semcore-14 dead arm: an unhandled pair unifies iff it is already structurally equal.
fn unify_eq_or_mismatch(decl: Ty, actual: Ty, s: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Ty]]) => Result[Vec[Pair[Bytes, Ty]], Bytes] =
  match ty_eq(decl, actual) {
    True => Ok(s),
    False => Err("cannot match declared against actual type (RFC-0007 SS11.3 -- never a silent swap)")
  };

// unify_var: the `(Ty::Var(v), _)` arm — a prior binding to a DIFFERENT type is a never-silent
// conflict; otherwise bind `v -> actual` (VR-5/G2).
fn unify_var(v: Bytes, actual: Ty, s: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Ty]]) => Result[Vec[Pair[Bytes, Ty]], Bytes] =
  match ty_subst_lookup(s, v) {
    None => Ok(Cons(Pr(v, actual), s)),
    Some(bound) => match ty_eq(bound, actual) {
      True => Ok(Cons(Pr(v, actual), s)),
      False => Err(bytes_concat("type parameter `", bytes_concat(v, "` would have to be two distinct types -- an ambiguous instantiation, not a guess (RFC-0007 SS11.3)")))
    }
  };

// unify_width_carrier: the shared width-var binding logic. The carrier is ALWAYS a `TyBinary`
// (`WdLit(n)` for a concrete width, `WdVar(v2)` for a width-var) regardless of the paradigm — the
// DN-42/M-753 carrier convention `subst_ty` reads back. A conflicting prior binding is never-silent.
fn unify_width_carrier(v: Bytes, carrier: Ty, s: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Ty]]) => Result[Vec[Pair[Bytes, Ty]], Bytes] =
  match ty_subst_lookup(s, v) {
    None => Ok(Cons(Pr(v, carrier), s)),
    Some(bound) => match ty_eq(bound, carrier) {
      True => Ok(Cons(Pr(v, carrier), s)),
      False => Err(bytes_concat("width parameter `", bytes_concat(v, "` would have to be two distinct widths -- a width mismatch, not a coercion (DN-42 SS4 / VR-5)")))
    }
  };

// unify_width: a width-var `decl` (Binary or Ternary) against an actual of the SAME paradigm. A
// concrete-width actual binds `v -> TyBinary(WdLit(n))`; a width-var actual binds `v ->
// TyBinary(WdVar(v2))`. Any cross-paradigm / non-width actual falls through to eq/mismatch.
fn unify_binary_width(v: Bytes, actual: Ty, decl: Ty, s: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Ty]]) => Result[Vec[Pair[Bytes, Ty]], Bytes] =
  match actual {
    TyBinary(w2) => match w2 {
      WdLit(n) => unify_width_carrier(v, TyBinary(WdLit(n)), s),
      WdVar(v2) => unify_width_carrier(v, TyBinary(WdVar(v2)), s)
    },
    _ => unify_eq_or_mismatch(decl, actual, s)
  };

fn unify_ternary_width(v: Bytes, actual: Ty, decl: Ty, s: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Ty]]) => Result[Vec[Pair[Bytes, Ty]], Bytes] =
  match actual {
    TyTernary(w2) => match w2 {
      WdLit(n) => unify_width_carrier(v, TyBinary(WdLit(n)), s),
      WdVar(v2) => unify_width_carrier(v, TyBinary(WdVar(v2)), s)
    },
    _ => unify_eq_or_mismatch(decl, actual, s)
  };

fn unify(decl: Ty, actual: Ty, s: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Ty]]) => Result[Vec[Pair[Bytes, Ty]], Bytes] =
  match decl {
    TyVar(v) => unify_var(v, actual, s),
    TyData(n1, a1) => match actual {
      TyData(n2, a2) => match and_(beq(n1, n2), same_ty_len(a1, a2)) {
        True => unify_list(a1, a2, s),
        False => unify_eq_or_mismatch(decl, actual, s)
      },
      _ => unify_eq_or_mismatch(decl, actual, s)
    },
    TyFn(a1, r1) => match actual {
      TyFn(a2, r2) => match unify(a1, a2, s) { Err(e) => Err(e), Ok(s1) => unify(r1, r2, s1) },
      _ => unify_eq_or_mismatch(decl, actual, s)
    },
    TySeq(e1, n1) => match actual {
      TySeq(e2, n2) => match eq_u(n1, n2) { True => unify(e1, e2, s), False => unify_eq_or_mismatch(decl, actual, s) },
      _ => unify_eq_or_mismatch(decl, actual, s)
    },
    TyBinary(w1) => match w1 {
      WdVar(v) => unify_binary_width(v, actual, decl, s),
      WdLit(_) => unify_eq_or_mismatch(decl, actual, s)
    },
    TyTernary(w1) => match w1 {
      WdVar(v) => unify_ternary_width(v, actual, decl, s),
      WdLit(_) => unify_eq_or_mismatch(decl, actual, s)
    },
    TyDense(_, _) => unify_eq_or_mismatch(decl, actual, s),
    TyVsa(_, _, _) => unify_eq_or_mismatch(decl, actual, s),
    TySubstrate(_) => unify_eq_or_mismatch(decl, actual, s),
    TyBytes => unify_eq_or_mismatch(decl, actual, s),
    TyFloat => unify_eq_or_mismatch(decl, actual, s)
  };

fn unify_list(a1: Vec[Ty], a2: Vec[Ty], s: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Ty]]) => Result[Vec[Pair[Bytes, Ty]], Bytes] =
  match a1 {
    Nil => Ok(s),
    Cons(h1, t1) => match a2 {
      Nil => Ok(s),
      Cons(h2, t2) => match unify(h1, h2, s) { Err(e) => Err(e), Ok(s1) => unify_list(t1, t2, s1) }
    }
  };

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// mono.rs NAME-MANGLING FAMILY (M-740 Stage 5, increment 4 — M-1009). Pure Ty->Bytes transformers.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Ports mono.rs's monomorphization name-mangling family: `mangle_ty`, `scalar_tag`, `mangle_decl`,
// `mangle_ctor`, `mangle_method`, `mangle_arrow`, `apply_fn_name`, `mangle_ty_or_fn`,
// `mangle_decl_with_wargs`, `mangle_hof_decl` (mono.rs::mangle_*). The RFC-0003 SS3 / RFC-0024 SS4A
// injective mangling scheme — the queryable identity of every resolved instance. All are pure
// `Ty`/name -> `Bytes` string functions depending only on the increment-1 `Ty` vocabulary
// (INDEPENDENT of M-1007/M-1008). The mangling stays injective across the repr/data boundary (the
// `#` nullary-data tag; the `$`/`%`/`~` joints are non-surface-identifier chars — never a silent
// alias, G2). Live oracle: mono::mangle_* (`pub(crate)`), reachable in-crate; the string-output
// differential is a direct `bytes_eq` comparison (compiler_stage5_mangle.rs — the cleanest witness).
//
// FLAG-semcore-16 (reuses `dec_u32` from increment 3 — FLAG-semcore-15). Rust's `format!("{n}")`
// decimal render is `dec_u32` here; M-1008 introduced it (its `tuple_type_name` needed it too), so
// this increment REUSES it rather than re-introducing it (DRY — the sequential ports share the one
// helper; the issue framed it as M-1009's dependency because the increments were independently
// scoped, but landed sequentially they share it).
//
// FLAG-semcore-17 — RESOLVED (M-1013 STEP 6, further down this file). `mangle_ty_in_ty` and
// `item_key` were DEFERRED here, not ported, because `mangle_ty_in_ty` (a `Ty -> Ty` rewrite) was a
// Rust MODULE-PRIVATE `fn` with NO reachable `pub(crate)` oracle, and `item_key` was likewise
// module-private AND depends on mono's `Item` work-item type (not in this nodule's copied
// vocabulary). Porting either would have landed UN-witnessable code — exactly the failure the
// FLAG-semcore-10 live-oracle discipline exists to prevent (a port with no differential is
// `Declared` at best). RESOLUTION: both are now ported, in the mono.rs TYPE ROUND-TRIP + WORK-ITEM
// section at the end of this file — `mangle_ty_in_ty`, `item_key`, `closure_field_ty`,
// `closure_param_ref`, `ty_to_source_ref`, `ty_to_ref`, `ty_to_ref_tagged` were widened to
// `pub(crate)` in `mono.rs` (zero logic change, the STEP-3/4/5 visibility-widening precedent), and
// mono's own `Item` enum (a purely structural `Bytes`/`Ty`/`Width`/pair work-item, no `Env`
// dependency) is likewise widened and mirrored as this nodule's `WorkItem` (a fresh name — `Item` is
// already taken by this nodule's own ast-level nodule-item sum, FLAG-semcore-2 discipline).

// ── small numeric literal + bytes helpers the mangling needs ─────────────────────────────────────
fn three32() => Binary{32} = 0b0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0000_0011;

// replace_dash: `model.replace('-', '_')` (the VSA kernel-model-id fragment is `$`-joined and its
// `-` — not an identifier char — maps to `_`; injective over the model-id alphabet). O(len) over the
// short model id via 1-char slices.
fn replace_dash_at(s: Bytes, i: Binary{32}, n: Binary{32}) => Bytes =
  match lt(i, n) {
    0b1 => let ch = bytes_slice(s, i, add_u(i, one32())) in
           bytes_concat(
             match bytes_eq(ch, "-") { 0b1 => "_", _ => ch },
             replace_dash_at(s, add_u(i, one32()), n)
           ),
    _ => ""
  };

fn replace_dash(s: Bytes) => Bytes = replace_dash_at(s, zero32(), bytes_len(s));

// strip_fn_prefix: `arrow.strip_prefix("Fn$").unwrap_or(arrow)` — strip a leading "Fn$" if present.
fn strip_fn_prefix(a: Bytes) => Bytes =
  match lt(bytes_len(a), three32()) {
    0b1 => a,
    _ => match bytes_eq(bytes_slice(a, zero32(), three32()), "Fn$") {
      0b1 => bytes_slice(a, three32(), bytes_len(a)),
      _ => a
    }
  };

// ── scalar_tag (mono.rs::scalar_tag) — the F16/BF16/F32/F64 tag inside mangle_ty ────────────────
fn scalar_tag(s: Scalar) => Bytes =
  match s { SF16 => "F16", SBf16 => "BF16", SF32 => "F32", SF64 => "F64" };

// vsa_sp_tag: the VSA sparsity fragment (`Dense` -> "Dn", `Sparse(k)` -> "Sp{k}").
fn vsa_sp_tag(sp: Sparsity) => Bytes =
  match sp { SpDense => "Dn", SpSparse(k) => bytes_concat("Sp", dec_u32(k)) };

// mangle_ty_args: the `$`-joined argument fragments of an applied data type / a decl's type args
// (`for a in args { push('$'); push(mangle_ty(a)) }`).
fn mangle_ty_args(args: Vec[Ty]) => Bytes =
  match args {
    Nil => "",
    Cons(h, t) => bytes_concat(bytes_concat("$", mangle_ty(h)), mangle_ty_args(t))
  };

// ── mangle_ty (mono.rs::mangle_ty) — a `Ty` to a flat identifier-suffix fragment (injective) ────
fn mangle_ty(t: Ty) => Bytes =
  match t {
    TyBinary(w) => match w { WdLit(n) => bytes_concat("Binary", dec_u32(n)), WdVar(v) => bytes_concat("BinaryVAR_", v) },
    TyTernary(w) => match w { WdLit(m) => bytes_concat("Ternary", dec_u32(m)), WdVar(v) => bytes_concat("TernaryVAR_", v) },
    TyDense(d, sc) => bytes_concat("Dense", bytes_concat(dec_u32(d), scalar_tag(sc))),
    TyVsa(model, dim, sp) => bytes_concat("Vsa", bytes_concat(dec_u32(dim), bytes_concat(vsa_sp_tag(sp), bytes_concat("$", replace_dash(model))))),
    TySubstrate(tag) => bytes_concat("Substrate", tag),
    TySeq(elem, n) => bytes_concat("Seq", bytes_concat(dec_u32(n), bytes_concat("$", mangle_ty(elem)))),
    TyBytes => "Bytes",
    TyFloat => "Float",
    TyData(n, args) => match args {
      Nil => bytes_concat(n, "#"),
      Cons(_, _) => bytes_concat(n, mangle_ty_args(args))
    },
    TyVar(v) => bytes_concat("VAR_", v),
    TyFn(a, r) => bytes_concat("HOF_FN_", bytes_concat(mangle_ty(a), bytes_concat("__TO__", mangle_ty(r))))
  };

// ── mangle_decl / mangle_ctor (mono.rs) — a decl (or ctor) name at concrete type args ───────────
// Empty targs => the original name byte-for-byte (monomorphic code untouched).
fn mangle_decl(name: Bytes, targs: Vec[Ty]) => Bytes =
  match targs { Nil => name, Cons(_, _) => bytes_concat(name, mangle_ty_args(targs)) };

fn mangle_ctor(name: Bytes, targs: Vec[Ty]) => Bytes = mangle_decl(name, targs);

// ── mangle_method (mono.rs) — a trait method to `method$Trait$ForTy` ────────────────────────────
fn mangle_method(method: Bytes, trait_name: Bytes, for_ty: Ty) => Bytes =
  bytes_concat(method, bytes_concat("$", bytes_concat(trait_name, bytes_concat("$", mangle_ty(for_ty)))));

// ── mangle_arrow / mangle_ty_or_fn / apply_fn_name (mono.rs, RFC-0024 SS4A) ─────────────────────
// mangle_ty_or_fn: like mangle_ty but a `Ty::Fn` becomes the arrow tag-sum `Fn$A$B` (mutually
// recursive with mangle_arrow — a nested arrow names its inner arrow's tag-sum).
fn mangle_ty_or_fn(t: Ty) => Bytes =
  match t { TyFn(a, b) => mangle_arrow(a, b), _ => mangle_ty(t) };

fn mangle_arrow(a: Ty, b: Ty) => Bytes =
  bytes_concat("Fn$", bytes_concat(mangle_ty_or_fn(a), bytes_concat("$", mangle_ty_or_fn(b))));

// apply_fn_name: the dispatcher name for an arrow mangle `Fn$A$B` -> `apply$A$B`.
fn apply_fn_name(arrow: Bytes) => Bytes = bytes_concat("apply$", strip_fn_prefix(arrow));

// ── mangle_decl_with_wargs / mangle_hof_decl (mono.rs, DN-42/M-753 step-c, RFC-0024 SS4) ────────
// warg_tag: one width argument's `$`-joined fragment (`Binary{n}` for a Lit; the never-reached
// `WVAR_{v}` marker for a Var — mono refuses undetermined params first, mirrored honestly).
fn warg_tag(w: Width) => Bytes =
  match w { WdLit(n) => bytes_concat("Binary", dec_u32(n)), WdVar(v) => bytes_concat("WVAR_", v) };

fn warg_joints(wargs: Vec[Width]) => Bytes =
  match wargs { Nil => "", Cons(w, rest) => bytes_concat(bytes_concat("$", warg_tag(w)), warg_joints(rest)) };

fn mangle_decl_with_wargs(name: Bytes, targs: Vec[Ty], wargs: Vec[Width]) => Bytes =
  bytes_concat(mangle_decl(name, targs), warg_joints(wargs));

// pairs_is_empty: the `fn_args.is_empty() && dyn_fns.is_empty()` guard (over Vec[Pair[u32, Bytes]]).
fn pairs_is_empty(p: Vec[Pair[Binary{32}, Bytes]]) => Bool =
  match p { Nil => True, Cons(_, _) => False };

// hof_fn_joints: the static fn-argument segments `%{idx}:{callee}` (the `%` fresh-var joint).
fn hof_fn_joints(fa: Vec[Pair[Binary{32}, Bytes]]) => Bytes =
  match fa {
    Nil => "",
    Cons(p, rest) => match p { Pr(idx, callee) =>
      bytes_concat(bytes_concat("%", bytes_concat(dec_u32(idx), bytes_concat(":", callee))), hof_fn_joints(rest)) }
  };

// hof_dyn_joints: the dynamic (kept-closure) fn-argument segments `~{idx}:{arrow}` (the `~` joint).
fn hof_dyn_joints(df: Vec[Pair[Binary{32}, Bytes]]) => Bytes =
  match df {
    Nil => "",
    Cons(p, rest) => match p { Pr(idx, arrow) =>
      bytes_concat(bytes_concat("~", bytes_concat(dec_u32(idx), bytes_concat(":", arrow))), hof_dyn_joints(rest)) }
  };

fn mangle_hof_decl(name: Bytes, targs: Vec[Ty], wargs: Vec[Width], fa: Vec[Pair[Binary{32}, Bytes]], df: Vec[Pair[Binary{32}, Bytes]]) => Bytes =
  let base = mangle_decl_with_wargs(name, targs, wargs) in
  match and_(pairs_is_empty(fa), pairs_is_empty(df)) {
    True => base,
    False => bytes_concat(base, bytes_concat(hof_fn_joints(fa), hof_dyn_joints(df)))
  };

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// mono.rs FREE-VARIABLE + BINDER ANALYSIS (M-740 Stage 5, increment 5 — M-1010). Pure Expr walks.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Ports mono.rs's free-variable + binder analysis — `free_vars`/`free_vars_at` and
// `pattern_binders`/`pattern_binders_at` (mono.rs) — the closure-conversion prerequisite (the
// capture set of a lambda/defunctionalization — RFC-0024 SS4A). Pure `Expr` -> ordered name-set
// walks depending only on the increment-1 `Expr`/`Pattern` vocabulary (INDEPENDENT of
// M-1007/M-1008/M-1009). Live oracle: mono::free_vars (`pub(crate)`), reachable in-crate; the
// worker `free_vars_at` and BOTH `pattern_binders`/`pattern_binders_at` are module-private but are
// exercised TRANSITIVELY through `free_vars` (a `match` scrutinee's binders drive the capture-set
// shadowing), so the differential (compiler_stage5_freevars.rs) still asserts every arm live.
//
// FLAG-semcore-18 (`&mut BTreeSet<String>` scope + `&mut Vec<String>` output -> the FLAG-semcore-6
// value-threaded collapse). Rust threads THREE mutable accumulators: `bound` (the in-scope binder
// set, pushed on scope entry and RESTORED on exit), `seen` (which names are already emitted), and
// `out` (the ordered first-occurrence capture list). Here:
//   * `bound` is a READ-ONLY scope parameter EXTENDED for a sub-scope (`ensure_bound`/`union_names`)
//     and never returned — because Rust always restores it to its entry value by the end of each
//     call (every `insert` is paired with its `remove`), so it is semantically an immutable
//     environment, not accumulated state. Shadowing is preserved: an already-bound name's re-bind is
//     a set no-op (`ensure_bound` keeps the set unchanged), exactly Rust's `insert`-returns-false arm.
//   * `seen`/`out` DO accumulate and are threaded upward as a `Pair[Vec[Bytes], Vec[Bytes]]` return
//     — a name emitted in one sub-walk stays emitted in the next (cross-branch de-dup), and `out`
//     grows by append-to-END (`names_snoc`) to keep Rust's first-occurrence order.
// `pattern_binders` becomes `pattern_binder_names` (the SET of a pattern's binder idents, the
// FLAG-semcore-6 collapse of the `&mut bound`+`&mut added` push/pop pair — the caller unions it into
// the arm scope). A `Pattern::Or` reaching it is a never-silent `Err` (Rust PANICS on the same
// desugaring-invariant break; a clean refusal is the faithful, G2-preferred shape — documented).
// The M-866 `MAX_WALK_DEPTH` (4096) budget is the SAME ceiling as `enter_depth`/max_semcore_depth
// (FLAG-semcore-3), reused verbatim; the pattern walk charges a fresh budget from 0 as Rust's
// `pattern_binders_at` does.

// ── small name-set helpers over the FLAG-semcore-4 Vec[Bytes] ────────────────────────────────────
// names_snoc: append a name to the END (preserves free_vars' first-occurrence order — `out.push`).
fn names_snoc(xs: Vec[Bytes], n: Bytes) => Vec[Bytes] =
  match xs { Nil => Cons(n, Nil), Cons(h, t) => Cons(h, names_snoc(t, n)) };

// names_append: concatenate two name lists (a pattern's binder-set union across sub-patterns).
fn names_append(a: Vec[Bytes], b: Vec[Bytes]) => Vec[Bytes] =
  match a { Nil => b, Cons(h, t) => Cons(h, names_append(t, b)) };

// ensure_bound: `bound.insert(n)` as a set op — add iff absent (an already-bound name is unchanged).
fn ensure_bound(bound: Vec[Bytes], n: Bytes) => Vec[Bytes] =
  match names_contains(bound, n) { True => bound, False => Cons(n, bound) };

// union_names: extend `bound` by every name in `names` (the arm/lambda/for scope extension).
fn union_names(bound: Vec[Bytes], names: Vec[Bytes]) => Vec[Bytes] =
  match names { Nil => bound, Cons(h, t) => union_names(ensure_bound(bound, h), t) };

// param_names: the value-parameter names of a lambda (Rust `params.iter().map(|p| p.name)`).
fn param_names(params: Vec[Param]) => Vec[Bytes] =
  match params { Nil => Nil, Cons(p, rest) => Cons(param_name(p), param_names(rest)) };

// ── pattern_binder_names (mono.rs::pattern_binders/pattern_binders_at) — a pattern's binder set ──
fn pattern_binder_names(pat: Pattern, depth: Binary{32}) => Result[Vec[Bytes], Bytes] =
  match enter_depth(depth) {
    Err(m) => Err(m),
    Ok(d) => match pat {
      PWildcard => Ok(Nil),
      PLit(_) => Ok(Nil),
      PIdent(n) => Ok(Cons(n, Nil)),
      PCtor(_, subs) => pattern_binder_names_list(subs, d),
      PTuple(subs) => pattern_binder_names_list(subs, d),
      POr(_) => Err("internal: Pattern::Or reached pattern_binders -- or-patterns must be desugared by the checker before any downstream pass (invariant violation -- report this)")
    }
  };

fn pattern_binder_names_list(subs: Vec[Pattern], depth: Binary{32}) => Result[Vec[Bytes], Bytes] =
  match subs {
    Nil => Ok(Nil),
    Cons(h, t) => match pattern_binder_names(h, depth) {
      Err(e) => Err(e),
      Ok(hn) => match pattern_binder_names_list(t, depth) {
        Err(e) => Err(e),
        Ok(tn) => Ok(names_append(hn, tn))
      }
    }
  };

// ── free_vars / free_vars_at (mono.rs) — the ordered free-variable capture set ──────────────────
// fvw: the depth-tracked worker (free_vars_at), threading (seen, out) up with `bound` read-only.
fn fvw(e: Expr, bound: Vec[Bytes], seen: Vec[Bytes], out: Vec[Bytes], depth: Binary{32}) => Result[Pair[Vec[Bytes], Vec[Bytes]], Bytes] =
  match enter_depth(depth) {
    Err(m) => Err(m),
    Ok(d) => match e {
      Path(p) => match path_segs(p) {
        Cons(n, rest) => match rest {
          Nil => match names_contains(bound, n) {
            True => Ok(Pr(seen, out)),
            False => match names_contains(seen, n) {
              True => Ok(Pr(seen, out)),
              False => Ok(Pr(Cons(n, seen), names_snoc(out, n)))
            }
          },
          Cons(_, _) => Ok(Pr(seen, out))
        },
        Nil => Ok(Pr(seen, out))
      },
      Lit(l) => match l {
        List(elems) => fvw_list(elems, bound, seen, out, d),
        _ => Ok(Pr(seen, out))
      },
      Let(name, _, be, body) => match fvw(be, bound, seen, out, d) {
        Err(e2) => Err(e2),
        Ok(p1) => match p1 { Pr(s1, o1) => fvw(body, ensure_bound(bound, name), s1, o1, d) }
      },
      If(cond, conseq, alt) => match fvw(cond, bound, seen, out, d) {
        Err(e2) => Err(e2),
        Ok(p1) => match p1 { Pr(s1, o1) => match fvw(conseq, bound, s1, o1, d) {
          Err(e2) => Err(e2),
          Ok(p2) => match p2 { Pr(s2, o2) => fvw(alt, bound, s2, o2, d) }
        }}
      },
      Match(scrutinee, arms) => match fvw(scrutinee, bound, seen, out, d) {
        Err(e2) => Err(e2),
        Ok(p1) => match p1 { Pr(s1, o1) => fvw_arms(arms, bound, s1, o1, d) }
      },
      For(x, xs, acc, init, body) => match fvw(xs, bound, seen, out, d) {
        Err(e2) => Err(e2),
        Ok(p1) => match p1 { Pr(s1, o1) => match fvw(init, bound, s1, o1, d) {
          Err(e2) => Err(e2),
          Ok(p2) => match p2 { Pr(s2, o2) => fvw(body, ensure_bound(ensure_bound(bound, x), acc), s2, o2, d) }
        }}
      },
      Swap(value, _, _) => fvw(value, bound, seen, out, d),
      WithParadigm(_, body) => fvw(body, bound, seen, out, d),
      Wild(b) => fvw(b, bound, seen, out, d),
      Spore(b) => fvw(b, bound, seen, out, d),
      Wrapping(b) => fvw(b, bound, seen, out, d),
      Consume(b) => fvw(b, bound, seen, out, d),
      Try(b) => fvw(b, bound, seen, out, d),
      Colony(hyphae) => fvw_hyphae(hyphae, bound, seen, out, d),
      Lambda(params, body) => fvw(body, union_names(bound, param_names(params)), seen, out, d),
      App(head, args) => match fvw(head, bound, seen, out, d) {
        Err(e2) => Err(e2),
        Ok(p1) => match p1 { Pr(s1, o1) => fvw_list(args, bound, s1, o1, d) }
      },
      Fuse(left, right) => match fvw(left, bound, seen, out, d) {
        Err(e2) => Err(e2),
        Ok(p1) => match p1 { Pr(s1, o1) => fvw(right, bound, s1, o1, d) }
      },
      Reclaim(pol, body) => match fvw(pol, bound, seen, out, d) {
        Err(e2) => Err(e2),
        Ok(p1) => match p1 { Pr(s1, o1) => fvw(body, bound, s1, o1, d) }
      },
      Ascribe(inner, _) => fvw(inner, bound, seen, out, d),
      TupleLit(elems) => fvw_list(elems, bound, seen, out, d)
    }
  };

// fvw_list: walk a Vec[Expr] left-to-right, threading (seen, out) (Lit(List)/App args/TupleLit).
fn fvw_list(es: Vec[Expr], bound: Vec[Bytes], seen: Vec[Bytes], out: Vec[Bytes], depth: Binary{32}) => Result[Pair[Vec[Bytes], Vec[Bytes]], Bytes] =
  match es {
    Nil => Ok(Pr(seen, out)),
    Cons(h, t) => match fvw(h, bound, seen, out, depth) {
      Err(e) => Err(e),
      Ok(p) => match p { Pr(s1, o1) => fvw_list(t, bound, s1, o1, depth) }
    }
  };

// fvw_hyphae: walk each hypha's body (Colony) — forage clauses are not free-var positions here.
fn fvw_hyphae(hs: Vec[Hypha], bound: Vec[Bytes], seen: Vec[Bytes], out: Vec[Bytes], depth: Binary{32}) => Result[Pair[Vec[Bytes], Vec[Bytes]], Bytes] =
  match hs {
    Nil => Ok(Pr(seen, out)),
    Cons(h, t) => match fvw(hypha_body(h), bound, seen, out, depth) {
      Err(e) => Err(e),
      Ok(p) => match p { Pr(s1, o1) => fvw_hyphae(t, bound, s1, o1, depth) }
    }
  };

// fvw_arms: per arm, extend `bound` by the arm pattern's binder set, walk the arm body; `bound`
// resets to the match scope between arms (the Rust insert/remove pair, collapsed).
fn fvw_arms(arms: Vec[Arm], bound: Vec[Bytes], seen: Vec[Bytes], out: Vec[Bytes], depth: Binary{32}) => Result[Pair[Vec[Bytes], Vec[Bytes]], Bytes] =
  match arms {
    Nil => Ok(Pr(seen, out)),
    Cons(a, rest) => match pattern_binder_names(arm_pattern(a), zero32()) {
      Err(e) => Err(e),
      Ok(names) => match fvw(arm_body(a), union_names(bound, names), seen, out, depth) {
        Err(e) => Err(e),
        Ok(p) => match p { Pr(s1, o1) => fvw_arms(rest, bound, s1, o1, depth) }
      }
    }
  };

// free_vars: the pub entry — an empty scope/seen/out, returning the ordered capture list.
fn free_vars(e: Expr) => Result[Vec[Bytes], Bytes] =
  match fvw(e, Nil, Nil, Nil, zero32()) {
    Err(msg) => Err(msg),
    Ok(p) => match p { Pr(_, out) => Ok(out) }
  };

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// checkty.rs LITERAL + PATTERN TYPING (M-740 Stage 5, increment 6 — M-1011). The checker's leaves.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Ports checkty.rs's literal + pattern typing leaves: `lit_ty_of` (a literal's `Ty`), `literal_key`
// (the M-320 canonical de-dup key), and `normalize_pattern` (a surface `Pattern` -> the normalized
// matrix `Pat` + its binder set — the bridge to the increment-1 usefulness/decision pipeline).
// Depends on increment 3 (`resolve_ty`'s siblings `param_subst`/`subst_ty` — M-1007/M-1008) and the
// increment-1 `Pat` family + `tuple_ctor_name` (M-1008). Live oracle: checkty::normalize_pattern
// (`pub(crate)`), reachable in-crate; `lit_ty_of` is `pub(crate)` and `literal_key` is module-private
// (exercised TRANSITIVELY through `normalize_pattern`, whose `Pat::Lit` arm keys via it). The
// normalize_pattern differential connects to the already-ported `useful` matrix (a normalized `Pat`
// feeds `useful` — tightening the increment-1 gate transitively).
//
// FLAG-semcore-19 (`literal_key`'s `Int`/`AmbientInt` arms are rendered with the correct distinct
// PREFIX but a SIMPLIFIED body — the integer/paradigm value is NOT decimal-rendered). Both are
// UNREACHABLE through the type-checked `normalize_pattern` path (`lit_ty_of` refuses `Int`/
// `AmbientInt` before any keying — a bare integer has no repr family, an ambient int is resolved
// first), and `literal_key` is module-private (no direct differential), so a full i64-signed-decimal
// + `Paradigm`-Display render would be untested dead code (YAGNI/KISS). The reachable arms
// (`Bin`/`Trit`/`LBytes`/`Str`) are faithful byte-for-byte; `LFloat`/`List` too. A documented
// narrowing, never a silent one (the same "a stable key keeps the fn total" rationale Rust's own
// `Bytes`/`List` arms carry — G2/VR-5).
//
// FLAG-semcore-20 (`infer_type` is DEFERRED — not a leaf). checkty.rs::infer_type constructs a full
// `Cx` and calls `cx.infer` — the ENTIRE ~7k-line inference engine (DN-26 SS7.1 SCC), which this
// increment (and the whole Stage-5 partial port) explicitly does NOT port (the increment-1 header's
// DEFERRED list). It is a thin wrapper over the deferred core, NOT a pure leaf, so it is honestly
// left out rather than faux-ported over an un-ported `infer`. Stated plainly (G2/VR-5).
//
// FLAG-semcore-21 (`normalize_pattern`'s `&mut Vec<(String, Ty, Vec<usize>)>` binder accumulator ->
// a THREADED `Vec[Bind]` returned alongside the `Pat` — the FLAG-semcore-6 collapse). Each binder is
// a `Bnd(name, ty, occ)` triple (`occ` = the field-index path from the scrutinee root — the
// elaborator's occurrence). `binds` is threaded through the ctor-field walk and returned; `site` is
// dropped and the tuple-pattern error-message remap is omitted (cosmetic — the FLAG-semcore-13
// site-drop rationale). An unregistered scrutinee data type is a never-silent `Err` (Rust `.expect()`
// PANICS — a clean refusal is the faithful, G2-preferred shape).

// ── Bind: a pattern binder (name, its concrete type, its occurrence path) ────────────────────────
type Bind = Bnd(Bytes, Ty, Vec[Binary{32}]);

fn snoc_bind(xs: Vec[Bind], b: Bind) => Vec[Bind] =
  match xs { Nil => Cons(b, Nil), Cons(h, t) => Cons(h, snoc_bind(t, b)) };

// ── byte-scanning helpers for lit_ty_of / literal_key ────────────────────────────────────────────
fn is_bindigit(ch: Bytes) => Bool =
  match bytes_eq(ch, "0") { 0b1 => True, _ => match bytes_eq(ch, "1") { 0b1 => True, _ => False } };

// count_bindigits: `s.chars().filter(|c| *c == '0' || *c == '1').count()` (the binary literal width).
fn count_bindigits_at(s: Bytes, i: Binary{32}, n: Binary{32}) => Binary{32} =
  match lt(i, n) {
    0b1 => let ch = bytes_slice(s, i, add_u(i, one32())) in
           add_u(match is_bindigit(ch) { True => one32(), False => zero32() }, count_bindigits_at(s, add_u(i, one32()), n)),
    _ => zero32()
  };

fn count_bindigits(s: Bytes) => Binary{32} = count_bindigits_at(s, zero32(), bytes_len(s));

// filter_bindigits: the 0/1 chars of `s` concatenated (the `literal_key` `b:` body).
fn filter_bindigits_at(s: Bytes, i: Binary{32}, n: Binary{32}) => Bytes =
  match lt(i, n) {
    0b1 => let ch = bytes_slice(s, i, add_u(i, one32())) in
           bytes_concat(match is_bindigit(ch) { True => ch, False => "" }, filter_bindigits_at(s, add_u(i, one32()), n)),
    _ => ""
  };

fn filter_bindigits(s: Bytes) => Bytes = filter_bindigits_at(s, zero32(), bytes_len(s));

// filter_no_underscore: `s.chars().filter(|c| *c != '_')` (the `literal_key` `by:` body).
fn filter_no_us_at(s: Bytes, i: Binary{32}, n: Binary{32}) => Bytes =
  match lt(i, n) {
    0b1 => let ch = bytes_slice(s, i, add_u(i, one32())) in
           bytes_concat(match bytes_eq(ch, "_") { 0b1 => "", _ => ch }, filter_no_us_at(s, add_u(i, one32()), n)),
    _ => ""
  };

fn filter_no_underscore(s: Bytes) => Bytes = filter_no_us_at(s, zero32(), bytes_len(s));

// ── lit_ty_of (checkty.rs::lit_ty_of) — a context-free literal's Ty (never-silent on Int/List) ──
fn lit_ty_of(l: Literal) => Result[Ty, Bytes] =
  match l {
    Bin(s) => let n = count_bindigits(s) in
              match eq(n, zero32()) { 0b1 => Err("empty binary literal"), _ => Ok(TyBinary(WdLit(n))) },
    Trit(s) => match eq(bytes_len(s), zero32()) { 0b1 => Err("empty ternary literal"), _ => Ok(TyTernary(WdLit(bytes_len(s)))) },
    Int(_) => Err("a bare integer literal has no representation family (no cross-family defaulting, Q6) -- write a binary/ternary literal, declare a `default paradigm` (RFC-0012), or ascribe a Dense element"),
    AmbientInt(_, _) => Err("internal: an unresolved ambient bare decimal reached `lit_ty_of` -- the checker resolves its width from context first (RFC-0012 SS4.3)"),
    LBytes(_) => Ok(TyBytes),
    LFloat(_) => Ok(TyFloat),
    Str(_) => Ok(TyBytes),
    List(_) => Err("a list/sequence pattern is not supported in the v0 surface (RFC-0032 D3 -- `[...]` is a constructor literal, not a pattern)")
  };

// ── literal_key (checkty.rs::literal_key) — a canonical de-dup key (M-320) ───────────────────────
fn literal_key(l: Literal) => Bytes =
  match l {
    Bin(s) => bytes_concat("b:", filter_bindigits(s)),
    Trit(s) => bytes_concat("t:", s),
    Int(_) => "i:",
    AmbientInt(_, _) => "amb:",
    List(_) => "list",
    LBytes(s) => bytes_concat("by:", filter_no_underscore(s)),
    Str(s) => bytes_concat("s:", s),
    LFloat(s) => bytes_concat("f:", s)
  };

// ── normalize_pattern (checkty.rs::normalize_pattern) — surface Pattern -> matrix Pat + binders ──
// ctor_lookup: find a constructor by name in a data type's ctor list (Rust `d.ctors.iter().find`).
fn ctor_lookup(ctors: Vec[CtorInfo], name: Bytes) => Option[CtorInfo] =
  match ctors {
    Nil => None,
    Cons(c, rest) => match bytes_eq(ci_name(c), name) { 0b1 => Some(c), _ => ctor_lookup(rest, name) }
  };

// pat_count: the arity of a sub-pattern list (Vec[Pattern] length).
fn pat_count(v: Vec[Pattern]) => Binary{32} =
  match v { Nil => zero32(), Cons(_, t) => add_u(one32(), pat_count(t)) };

fn is_float_lit(l: Literal) => Bool = match l { LFloat(_) => True, _ => False };

fn normalize_lit(lit: Literal, expected: Ty, binds: Vec[Bind]) => Result[Pair[Pat, Vec[Bind]], Bytes] =
  match is_float_lit(lit) {
    True => Err("a float literal is not a legal match pattern (ADR-040 FLAG-4: IEEE equality and content identity diverge on floats; match on the result of an explicit comparison instead -- never a silent equality choice, G2)"),
    False => match lit_ty_of(lit) {
      Err(e) => Err(e),
      Ok(lty) => match ty_eq(lty, expected) {
        False => Err("literal pattern has a type distinct from the scrutinee (W7: a literal arm must match the scrutinee's repr and width)"),
        True => Ok(Pr(MpLit(literal_key(lit)), binds))
      }
    }
  };

fn normalize_ident(types: Vec[DataInfo], n: Bytes, expected: Ty, occ: Vec[Binary{32}], binds: Vec[Bind]) => Result[Pair[Pat, Vec[Bind]], Bytes] =
  match expected {
    TyData(tn, _) => match types_lookup(types, tn) {
      None => Err(bytes_concat("internal: unregistered scrutinee data type `", bytes_concat(tn, "` (never silent -- G2)"))),
      Some(d) => match ctor_lookup(di_ctors(d), n) {
        None => Ok(Pr(MpWild, snoc_bind(binds, Bnd(n, expected, occ)))),
        Some(c) => match ci_fields(c) {
          Nil => Ok(Pr(MpCtor(n, Nil), binds)),
          Cons(_, _) => Err(bytes_concat("constructor pattern `", bytes_concat(n, "` must bind its field(s) (W7)")))
        }
      }
    },
    _ => Ok(Pr(MpWild, snoc_bind(binds, Bnd(n, expected, occ))))
  };

fn normalize_fields(types: Vec[DataInfo], subs: Vec[Pattern], fields: Vec[Ty], s: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Ty]], occ: Vec[Binary{32}], i: Binary{32}, binds: Vec[Bind]) => Result[Pair[Vec[Pat], Vec[Bind]], Bytes] =
  match subs {
    Nil => Ok(Pr(Nil, binds)),
    Cons(sub, srest) => match fields {
      Nil => Ok(Pr(Nil, binds)),
      Cons(fty, frest) =>
        let child = u32_append(occ, Cons(i, Nil)) in
        let fty2 = subst_ty(fty, s) in
        match normalize_pattern(types, sub, fty2, child, binds) {
          Err(e) => Err(e),
          Ok(pr) => match pr { Pr(p, binds2) =>
            match normalize_fields(types, srest, frest, s, occ, add_u(i, one32()), binds2) {
              Err(e) => Err(e),
              Ok(pr2) => match pr2 { Pr(rest_pats, binds3) => Ok(Pr(Cons(p, rest_pats), binds3)) }
            }
          }
        }
    }
  };

fn normalize_ctor(types: Vec[DataInfo], n: Bytes, subs: Vec[Pattern], expected: Ty, occ: Vec[Binary{32}], binds: Vec[Bind]) => Result[Pair[Pat, Vec[Bind]], Bytes] =
  match expected {
    TyData(tn, targs) => match types_lookup(types, tn) {
      None => Err(bytes_concat("internal: unregistered scrutinee data type `", bytes_concat(tn, "` (never silent -- G2)"))),
      Some(d) => match ctor_lookup(di_ctors(d), n) {
        None => Err(bytes_concat("`", bytes_concat(n, bytes_concat("` is not a constructor of ", tn)))),
        Some(c) => match eq_u(pat_count(subs), ty_len(ci_fields(c))) {
          False => Err(bytes_concat("pattern `", bytes_concat(n, "` does not bind exactly the constructor's arity (W7)"))),
          True => let s = param_subst(di_params(d), targs) in
                  match normalize_fields(types, subs, ci_fields(c), s, occ, zero32(), binds) {
                    Err(e) => Err(e),
                    Ok(pr) => match pr { Pr(outpats, binds2) => Ok(Pr(MpCtor(n, outpats), binds2)) }
                  }
        }
      }
    },
    _ => Err(bytes_concat("constructor pattern `", bytes_concat(n, "` on a non-data scrutinee -- match a literal or `_`")))
  };

fn normalize_pattern(types: Vec[DataInfo], pat: Pattern, expected: Ty, occ: Vec[Binary{32}], binds: Vec[Bind]) => Result[Pair[Pat, Vec[Bind]], Bytes] =
  match pat {
    PWildcard => Ok(Pr(MpWild, binds)),
    PIdent(n) => normalize_ident(types, n, expected, occ, binds),
    PCtor(n, subs) => normalize_ctor(types, n, subs, expected, occ, binds),
    PTuple(subs) => normalize_ctor(types, tuple_ctor_name(pat_count(subs)), subs, expected, occ, binds),
    PLit(lit) => normalize_lit(lit, expected, binds),
    POr(_) => Err("internal: Pattern::Or reached normalize_pattern -- or-patterns must be desugared in check_match before any downstream pass (invariant violation -- report this)")
  };

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// elab.rs PURE L0 LOWERING HELPERS (M-740 Stage 5, increment 7 — M-1012; DN-26 SS7.3 row 5 / SS10).
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// The FIRST wave to cross the frontend/kernel L0 seam (DN-26 SS7.2). Every prior increment (1..6)
// ported only frontend-internal `Ty`-algebra / `Bytes` transformers; these helpers construct the
// KERNEL L0 vocabulary (`mycelium_core::{Value, Repr, FieldSpec, FieldTyRef, ScalarKind,
// SparsityClass, Payload}`). Per the maintainer's ratified decision (DN-26 SS10 — Option A, the
// in-language mirror model), that vocabulary is declared as plain Mycelium ADTs here (mirroring the
// Rust kernel field-for-field) and the differential compares the mirror against the live Rust oracle
// (`compiler_stage5_elab.rs`) by structural equality (the FLAG-semcore-12 `ty_eq` posture, one layer
// down). This wave is ENTIRELY `wild`-FREE: pure lowering = mirror construction, no kernel FFI
// (ADR-042 wild-free-core goal; the single "materialize the finished L0" crossing DN-26 SS10 reserves
// `wild` for is NOT in this wave).
//
// FLAG-semcore-22 (the L0 kernel MIRROR ADTs — DN-26 SS10 Option A). `ScalarK`/`SparsityC`/`FloatW`/
// `Repr`/`TritK`/`Payload`/`Meta`/`Value`/`FieldTyRef`/`KFnSig`/`FieldSpec` mirror
// `crates/mycelium-core/src/{repr,value,data,node}.rs` field-for-field. Disjoint prefixes (the
// FLAG-semcore-2 scheme, extended): `Sk` (ScalarKind), `Sc` (SparsityClass — distinct from surface
// `Sparsity`'s `Sp`), `Fw` (FloatWidth), `R` (Repr), `Tk` (Trit), `Pl` (Payload — distinct from the
// surface `Pattern` `P`- and `Paradigm` `P`-families, FLAG-semcore-23), `Mt` (Meta), `Val` (Value),
// `Ft` (FieldTyRef), `KFS` (the KERNEL FnSig — spelled `KFnSig`/`KFS` because the SURFACE `FnSig`/`FS`
// mirror is already present, FLAG-semcore-1), `Fs` (FieldSpec). Every bare tag was diffed against
// every prior family here (verified disjoint). This is exactly the FLAG-semcore-1/-2 move that mirrors
// `checkty.rs`'s `Ty`/`DataInfo`, extended from the frontend `Ty` to the kernel `Value`/`Repr`.
//
// FLAG-semcore-23 (`Payload` mirror declares only the wild-free-CONSTRUCTIBLE variants this wave
// uses — `PlBits`/`PlTrits`/`PlBytes`). `Payload::{Scalars,Hypervector,Float,Seq}` are OMITTED:
// `Scalars`/`Hypervector`/`Float` need the deferred `Float` model (FLAG-semcore-25) and `Seq` needs a
// recursive `Value`; no ported helper constructs them (the FLAG-semcore-1 "declare structural, omit
// unused" precedent). `mycelium_core::Payload::Bytes(Vec<u8>)` is mirrored as `PlBytes(Bytes)` — the
// `.myc` `Bytes` primitive IS the byte-vector (isomorphic); this also SIDESTEPS the absent
// byte-value-synthesis primitive (there is no `ord`/`chr`/`from_u8` in the wild-free surface, so an
// element-wise `Vec[Binary{8}]` cannot be built from arbitrary content — a real surface limit, not a
// modelling choice).
//
// FLAG-semcore-24 (`Meta` mirrored MINIMALLY as the single nullary `MtExactRoot`). `lit_value`
// constructs exactly one Meta, `Meta::exact(Provenance::Root)`; Meta is NOT identity-bearing for
// content-addressing (content.rs hashes neither provenance nor dynamic value metadata), and no ported
// helper varies it. Full Meta (provenance/measured-sparsity/realized-bounds/policy_used) is deferred
// until a helper that constructs a non-trivial Meta lands. `Value` stays field-faithful (the
// `(repr, payload, meta)` triple — `Val(Repr, Payload, Meta)`).
//
// FLAG-semcore-25 (`lit_value`'s `LBytes` and `LFloat` arms DEFERRED — not faked, G2/VR-5). `LBytes`
// (hex -> byte-vector) needs the byte-value-synthesis primitive the wild-free surface lacks (see
// FLAG-semcore-23); `LFloat` needs correctly-rounded decimal->binary64 (`f64::from_str`), infeasible
// to match byte-for-byte in wild-free `.myc` this wave (the same class as the FLAG-semcore-27 hash
// defer). Both arms return an explicit never-silent `Err` naming the deferral (an honest refusal, not
// a wrong value). The `Bin`/`Trit`/`Str` arms + the `Int`/`AmbientInt`/`List` refusals ARE ported
// faithfully, with real payloads. Under ADR-042's wild-free-core goal these two arms are the residual
// `wild`-candidates for this helper — tracked, never silently defaulted.
//
// FLAG-semcore-26 (the fallible helpers narrow `Result<_, ElabError>` to `Result[_, Bytes]` — the
// FLAG-semcore-3/-13 precedent). The structured `ElabError` (Residual/UnknownFn/DepthExceeded, with
// its `site`) becomes a plain `Bytes` reason; the `site` argument is DROPPED. The differential asserts
// Ok/Err (and Some/None) + the success payload, never the message bytes (`res_repr_eq`/`res_value_eq`/
// `opt_*_eq` treat any `Err`==`Err` / `None`==`None`).
//
// FLAG-semcore-27 (`policy_name_ref`'s HASH deferred; only the wild-free PREIMAGE ported — reworded
// 2026-07-07, M-1012 patch: the ORIGINAL text below wrongly named BLAKE3-unavailability as the
// blocker; corrected to the real one). The Rust `policy_name_ref` =
// `operation_hash(&policy_name_preimage(policy))` (elab.rs), and `operation_hash`
// (`mycelium_core::content::Canon`) = BLAKE3 over the FRAMED bytes `[0x07 PRIM-domain tag] ++
// [u64-LE length prefix] ++ [preimage UTF-8 bytes]` (content.rs `Canon::tag`/`Canon::str`/
// `Canon::blob`). The domain-separated PREIMAGE itself (`policy-name.v0:<dotted>`) is the FRONTEND's
// contribution and IS ported wild-free (`policy_name_preimage`), differential-tested LIVE-ORACLE
// against the extracted `elab::policy_name_preimage` (a `pub(crate)` extraction made for exactly this
// oracle-reachability — behaviour-preserving).
//
// The REAL blocker is NOT the hash function — `hash_blake3(b: Bytes) -> Bytes` IS already a
// wild-free, surface-callable `.myc` primitive (M-912, checkty.rs: total and deterministic over
// every `Bytes` input). The blocker is CONSTRUCTING `operation_hash`'s raw-byte PREIMAGE to feed it:
// the `0x07` domain-tag byte and the 8-byte little-endian length prefix are raw byte VALUES, and the
// wild-free `.myc` surface has no byte-value-synthesis primitive (no `\xNN`/`0x..`/`ord`/`chr`/
// `from_u8`) to construct them — the SAME gap FLAG-semcore-25 documents for `lit_value`'s `LBytes`
// arm and FLAG-semcore-23 documents for `Payload`'s omitted variants. So `policy_name_ref` is
// DEFERRED to the single materialization/kernel-hash crossing (a `wild:` framing-construction prim,
// or a wild-free path once a byte-synthesis primitive lands — `hash_blake3` itself needs no `wild:`)
// — not faked (a mismatch would be never-silent: every `PolicyRef` would diverge in the differential,
// G2). No `PolicyRef` mirror is declared this wave (it is a `ContentHash` string; the ported surface
// stops at the preimage `Bytes`).
//
// FLAG-semcore-28 (RETIRED, M-1013 STEP 2 — DN-26 SS10.2). The increment-7 landing carried an
// L0-mirror structural-equality scaffolding (`scalark_eq`/.../`value_eq`/`field_spec_eq`) so the
// differential driver had an in-`.myc` `Bool` witness. That hand-written comparator family restated
// `mycelium_core`'s derived `PartialEq` BY HAND — an untrusted, growing surface. It is REMOVED: the
// differential now compares by HARNESS MARSHALLING (decode the port's mirror output back into the real
// `mycelium_core` type and compare with Rust's own trusted derived `==` — `compiler_stage5_elab.rs`'s
// `decode_*` family). The driver no longer calls any `.myc`-side `_eq`, so none is declared here. This
// removes the hand-mirrored comparators from the trust path (DN-26 SS10.2). Note: `ty_eq` (above,
// FLAG-semcore-12) is DIFFERENT — it is live CHECK logic called by real elaboration paths, not a
// differential comparator, and stays.
//
// FLAG-semcore-29 (`lit_value`'s `Bin`/`Trit` arms omit the `MAX_DIM` UPPER-bound refusal — an
// intentional scope cut this wave, not an oversight; G2). The Rust oracle's `Value::new` runs
// `Repr::check_well_formed` -> `dim_in_range`, which refuses BOTH `width == 0` (the lower bound,
// PORTED below — `eq(w, zero32())`) AND `width > MAX_DIM` (`mycelium_core::repr::MAX_DIM = 2^30`,
// repr.rs) as `WfError::DimensionTooLarge`. This port's `Bin`/`Trit` arms replicate the lower-bound
// refusal only; a `Binary`/`Ternary` literal with more than `2^30` digits would be ACCEPTED here
// where the Rust oracle refuses. Practical risk is negligible — the source text for such a literal
// exceeds 1 GB, past any literal this wave's differential (or any real program) approaches — but the
// divergence is honestly recorded rather than silently dropped (G2/VR-5); closing it is deferred to a
// future increment that adds the `Binary{32}`-safe `> MAX_DIM` comparison.

// ── L0 kernel mirror ADTs (FLAG-semcore-22; DN-26 SS10 Option A) ─────────────────────────────────
// ScalarK: mirrors mycelium_core::ScalarKind (repr.rs).
type ScalarK = SkF16 | SkBf16 | SkF32 | SkF64;

// SparsityC: mirrors mycelium_core::SparsityClass (repr.rs). Sparse carries the max_active passthrough.
type SparsityC = ScDense | ScSparse(Binary{32});

// FloatW: mirrors mycelium_core::FloatWidth (repr.rs) — F64-only at introduction (ADR-040 FLAG-1).
type FloatW = FwF64;

// Repr: mirrors mycelium_core::Repr (repr.rs), the four closed paradigm kinds + Seq/Float/Bytes.
type Repr =
    RBinary(Binary{32})
  | RTernary(Binary{32})
  | RDense(Binary{32}, ScalarK)
  | RVsa(Bytes, Binary{32}, SparsityC)
  | RSeq(Repr, Binary{32})
  | RFloat(FloatW)
  | RBytes;

// TritK: mirrors mycelium_core::Trit (value.rs).
type TritK = TkNeg | TkZero | TkPos;

// Payload: mirrors mycelium_core::Payload (value.rs) — the wild-free-constructible subset only
// (FLAG-semcore-23). `PlBytes(Bytes)` holds the byte-vector directly (the `.myc` Bytes primitive).
type Payload = PlBits(Vec[Binary{1}]) | PlTrits(Vec[TritK]) | PlBytes(Bytes);

// Meta: mirrors mycelium_core::Meta minimally (FLAG-semcore-24) — the single `exact(Root)` form.
type Meta = MtExactRoot;

// Value: mirrors mycelium_core::Value (value.rs) — the (repr, payload, meta) triple.
type Value = Val(Repr, Payload, Meta);

// KFnSig: mirrors mycelium_core::FnSig (data.rs) — (arity, params, ret). Spelled `KFnSig`/`KFS` to
// avoid the SURFACE `FnSig`/`FS` mirror already present (FLAG-semcore-22).
type KFnSig = KFS(Binary{32}, Vec[FieldTyRef], FieldTyRef);

// FieldTyRef: mirrors mycelium_core::FieldTyRef (data.rs).
type FieldTyRef = FtRepr(Repr) | FtData(Bytes) | FtFn(KFnSig);

// FieldSpec: mirrors mycelium_core::FieldSpec (data.rs).
type FieldSpec = FsRepr(Repr) | FsData(Bytes) | FsFn(Binary{32}, KFnSig);

// ── the pure lowering helpers (elab.rs), in dependency order (DN-26 SS10 landing order) ──────────

// scalar_kind (elab.rs:1043) — Scalar -> ScalarKind. Boundary-independent (lands first, DN-26 SS10);
// its tag twin `scalar_tag` (mono.rs) already landed increment 4.
fn scalar_kind(s: Scalar) => ScalarK =
  match s { SF16 => SkF16, SBf16 => SkBf16, SF32 => SkF32, SF64 => SkF64 };

// sparsity_class (elab.rs:1053) — Sparsity -> SparsityClass (the Sparse arm is a bare max_active
// passthrough). Boundary-independent; its tag twin `vsa_sp_tag` already landed increment 4.
fn sparsity_class(sp: Sparsity) => SparsityC =
  match sp { SpDense => ScDense, SpSparse(k) => ScSparse(k) };

// lit_value (elab.rs:102) — a representation literal's L0 Value. Bin/Trit/Str + refusals ported
// faithfully; LBytes/LFloat DEFERRED (FLAG-semcore-25). Never-silent on every fallible arm (G2).
// bin_bits: filter the digit/`_` string to its 0/1 bits, MSB-first (Rust
// `chars().filter(|c| c=='0'||c=='1').map(|c| c=='1')`).
fn bin_bits_at(s: Bytes, i: Binary{32}, n: Binary{32}) => Vec[Binary{1}] =
  match lt(i, n) {
    0b1 => let ch = bytes_slice(s, i, add_u(i, one32())) in
           match bytes_eq(ch, "0") {
             0b1 => Cons(0b0, bin_bits_at(s, add_u(i, one32()), n)),
             _ => match bytes_eq(ch, "1") {
               0b1 => Cons(0b1, bin_bits_at(s, add_u(i, one32()), n)),
               _ => bin_bits_at(s, add_u(i, one32()), n)
             }
           },
    _ => Nil
  };

fn bin_bits(s: Bytes) => Vec[Binary{1}] = bin_bits_at(s, zero32(), bytes_len(s));

fn bits_len(v: Vec[Binary{1}]) => Binary{32} =
  match v { Nil => zero32(), Cons(_, t) => add_u(one32(), bits_len(t)) };

// trit_of: one wire glyph -> a trit; every non-{+,0,-} char is an explicit error (Rust maps EVERY
// char, no filtering — a stray char is a never-silent residual, G2).
fn trit_of(ch: Bytes) => Result[TritK, Bytes] =
  match bytes_eq(ch, "+") { 0b1 => Ok(TkPos), _ =>
  match bytes_eq(ch, "0") { 0b1 => Ok(TkZero), _ =>
  match bytes_eq(ch, "-") { 0b1 => Ok(TkNeg), _ =>
  Err(bytes_concat("lit_value: non-trit char in ternary literal: ", ch)) }}};

fn trit_trits_at(s: Bytes, i: Binary{32}, n: Binary{32}) => Result[Vec[TritK], Bytes] =
  match lt(i, n) {
    0b1 => match trit_of(bytes_slice(s, i, add_u(i, one32()))) {
             Err(e) => Err(e),
             Ok(t) => match trit_trits_at(s, add_u(i, one32()), n) {
               Err(e) => Err(e),
               Ok(rest) => Ok(Cons(t, rest))
             }
           },
    _ => Ok(Nil)
  };

fn trits_len(v: Vec[TritK]) => Binary{32} =
  match v { Nil => zero32(), Cons(_, t) => add_u(one32(), trits_len(t)) };

// lower-bound (`width == 0`) refused below, matching `Value::new`/`check_well_formed`; the
// `MAX_DIM` UPPER bound is NOT ported this wave (FLAG-semcore-29 — an honest, intentional cut).
fn lit_value(l: Literal) => Result[Value, Bytes] =
  match l {
    Bin(s) => let bits = bin_bits(s) in
              let w = bits_len(bits) in
              match eq(w, zero32()) {
                0b1 => Err("lit_value: empty binary literal (Binary{0} is malformed -- Value::new refuses; G2)"),
                _ => Ok(Val(RBinary(w), PlBits(bits), MtExactRoot))
              },
    Trit(s) => match trit_trits_at(s, zero32(), bytes_len(s)) {
                 Err(e) => Err(e),
                 Ok(trits) => let w = trits_len(trits) in
                              match eq(w, zero32()) {
                                0b1 => Err("lit_value: empty ternary literal (Ternary{0} is malformed -- Value::new refuses; G2)"),
                                _ => Ok(Val(RTernary(w), PlTrits(trits), MtExactRoot))
                              }
               },
    Str(s) => Ok(Val(RBytes, PlBytes(s), MtExactRoot)),
    LBytes(_) => Err("lit_value: `0x..` byte-string literal DEFERRED this wave (FLAG-semcore-25 -- hex->byte-vector needs a byte-value-synthesis primitive absent from the wild-free surface; not faked -- G2)"),
    LFloat(_) => Err("lit_value: decimal float literal DEFERRED this wave (FLAG-semcore-25 -- needs correctly-rounded decimal->binary64, infeasible byte-for-byte in wild-free `.myc`; not faked -- G2)"),
    Int(_) => Err("a bare integer literal has no representation family (Q6)"),
    AmbientInt(_, _) => Err("internal: an unresolved ambient bare decimal reached elaboration -- the checker resolves its width before the L0 bridge runs (RFC-0012 SS4.3)"),
    List(_) => Err("internal: a list literal reached `lit_value` -- it lowers through `expr_inner` (the element expressions need elaboration; RFC-0032 D3)")
  };

// type_repr (elab.rs:244) — surface `TypeRef` -> kernel `Repr` (swap targets). Only representation
// types resolve; named/data/Substrate/Fn/Tuple/Ambient/width-var are explicit refusals. Note the Vsa
// arm canonicalizes the surface model id (`vsa_kernel_model_id`) -- matching the Rust oracle, and
// DISTINCT from `field_spec`/`ty_to_repr` below (whose checked `Ty` already carries the canonical id).
fn type_repr(t: TypeRef) => Result[Repr, Bytes] =
  match typeref_base(t) {
    KwBinary(w) => match w {
      WLit(n) => Ok(RBinary(n)),
      WName(v) => Err(bytes_concat("width variable reached elaboration (must be monomorphized first -- DN-42/M-753): ", v))
    },
    KwTernary(w) => match w {
      WLit(m) => Ok(RTernary(m)),
      WName(v) => Err(bytes_concat("width variable reached elaboration (must be monomorphized first -- DN-42/M-753): ", v))
    },
    KwDense(d, s) => Ok(RDense(d, scalar_kind(s))),
    Vsa(model, dim, sp) => Ok(RVsa(vsa_kernel_model_id(model), dim, sparsity_class(sp))),
    KwSeq(elem, len) => match type_repr(elem) {
      Ok(r) => Ok(RSeq(r, len)),
      Err(e) => Err(e)
    },
    KwBytes => Ok(RBytes),
    KwFloat => Ok(RFloat(FwF64)),
    KwSubstrate(tag) => Err(bytes_concat("Substrate is not a representation type: ", tag)),
    Named(name, _) => Err(bytes_concat("`", bytes_concat(name, "` is not a representation type -- no kernel Repr"))),
    Ambient(_) => Err("internal: an unresolved paradigm-less repr `{..}` reached elaboration (the ambient resolution pass fills it first -- RFC-0012 SS4.3)"),
    FnArrow(_, _) => Err("function types (`A -> B`) are not a representation type and cannot be a swap target (RFC-0024 SS3)"),
    Tuple(_) => Err("tuple types are not a representation type and cannot be a swap target (M-826; G2)")
  };

// ty_to_repr (elab.rs:982) — a representation checked `Ty` -> kernel `Repr`; `None` for any
// non-representation type (never a half-elaborated artifact -- G2/VR-5). Vsa uses the model DIRECTLY
// (the checked `Ty` already holds the canonical kernel id -- no re-canonicalization, matching Rust).
fn ty_to_repr(ty: Ty) => Option[Repr] =
  match ty {
    TyBinary(w) => match w { WdLit(n) => Some(RBinary(n)), WdVar(_) => None },
    TyTernary(w) => match w { WdLit(m) => Some(RTernary(m)), WdVar(_) => None },
    TyDense(d, s) => Some(RDense(d, scalar_kind(s))),
    TyVsa(model, dim, sp) => Some(RVsa(model, dim, sparsity_class(sp))),
    TySeq(elem, n) => match ty_to_repr(elem) { Some(r) => Some(RSeq(r, n)), None => None },
    TyBytes => Some(RBytes),
    TyFloat => Some(RFloat(FwF64)),
    TyData(_, _) => None,
    TyVar(_) => None,
    TySubstrate(_) => None,
    TyFn(_, _) => None
  };

// ty_to_field_ty_ref (elab.rs:1023) — a v0 `Ty` -> a `FieldTyRef` signature leaf: a monomorphic
// `Data` reference, a nested `Fn` signature, or (the `_` arm) a `Repr` leaf via `ty_to_repr`. `None`
// for anything with no monomorphic form (mirrors `field_spec`'s staging -- G2/VR-5).
fn ty_to_field_ty_ref(ty: Ty) => Option[FieldTyRef] =
  match ty {
    TyData(n, args) => match args { Nil => Some(FtData(n)), Cons(_, _) => None },
    TyVar(_) => None,
    TySubstrate(_) => None,
    TyFn(param, ret) => match ty_to_field_ty_ref(param) {
      None => None,
      Some(p2) => match ty_to_field_ty_ref(ret) {
        None => None,
        Some(r2) => Some(FtFn(KFS(one32(), Cons(p2, Nil), r2)))
      }
    },
    _ => match ty_to_repr(ty) { Some(r) => Some(FtRepr(r)), None => None }
  };

// field_spec (elab.rs:923) — a checked `Ty` field -> a build-time `FieldSpec`; `None` when the field
// has no monomorphic kernel form (a width-var, a generic `Data`, a `Var`, a `Substrate`, or an
// unresolvable `Fn` signature leaf) -- staged, never half-encoded (G2/VR-5).
fn field_spec(ty: Ty) => Option[FieldSpec] =
  match ty {
    TyBinary(w) => match w { WdLit(n) => Some(FsRepr(RBinary(n))), WdVar(_) => None },
    TyTernary(w) => match w { WdLit(m) => Some(FsRepr(RTernary(m))), WdVar(_) => None },
    TyDense(d, s) => Some(FsRepr(RDense(d, scalar_kind(s)))),
    TyVsa(model, dim, sp) => Some(FsRepr(RVsa(model, dim, sparsity_class(sp)))),
    TySeq(elem, n) => match ty_to_repr(elem) { Some(r) => Some(FsRepr(RSeq(r, n))), None => None },
    TyBytes => Some(FsRepr(RBytes)),
    TyFloat => Some(FsRepr(RFloat(FwF64))),
    TyData(n, args) => match args { Nil => Some(FsData(n)), Cons(_, _) => None },
    TyVar(_) => None,
    TySubstrate(_) => None,
    TyFn(param, ret) => match ty_to_field_ty_ref(param) {
      None => None,
      Some(p2) => match ty_to_field_ty_ref(ret) {
        None => None,
        Some(r2) => Some(FsFn(one32(), KFS(one32(), Cons(p2, Nil), r2)))
      }
    }
  };

// policy_name_preimage (elab.rs:344 preimage) — the domain-separated PREIMAGE of `policy_name_ref`
// (`policy-name.v0:<dotted>`). The hashing step is DEFERRED (FLAG-semcore-27). `join_dot` restates
// `policy.0.join(".")`.
fn join_dot(segs: Vec[Bytes]) => Bytes =
  match segs {
    Nil => "",
    Cons(h, t) => match t {
      Nil => h,
      Cons(_, _) => bytes_concat(h, bytes_concat(".", join_dot(t)))
    }
  };

fn policy_name_preimage(p: Path) => Bytes =
  bytes_concat("policy-name.v0:", join_dot(path_segs(p)));

// (FLAG-semcore-28 RETIRED — M-1013 STEP 2, DN-26 SS10.2.) The L0-mirror structural-equality
// comparator family (`scalark_eq`/`repr_eq`/`payload_eq`/`value_eq`/`field_spec_eq`/`opt_*_eq`/
// `res_*_eq`, ~100 lines) that lived here is REMOVED. The Stage-5 differential no longer needs an
// in-`.myc` `Bool` witness: it now decodes the port's mirror output back into the real
// `mycelium_core` type and compares with Rust's own trusted derived `==` (harness marshalling —
// `crates/mycelium-l1/src/tests/compiler_stage5_elab.rs`'s `decode_*` family). This retires the
// hand-mirrored comparators from the trust path. The live CHECK-logic equalities used by real
// elaboration paths (`ty_eq`/`scalar_eq`/`sparsity_eq`/`width_eq`/`ty_list_eq`, FLAG-semcore-12) are
// a DIFFERENT family, earlier in this nodule, and are unaffected.


// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// checkty.rs IMPORT RESOLUTION (M-740 Stage 5, increment 8 continuation — M-1013 STEP 4).
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Ports checkty.rs::resolve_imports (1423-1533) plus its six small helpers (qualify 1286-1292,
// exports_has_pub/direct_child/split_last_seg/insert_export/remove_import 1535-1584) — the
// "resolution" half of DN-26's M-1013 increment-8 declaration-registration-and-resolution wave
// (register_types/register_traits/register_instances, the "registration" half, landed as M-1013
// STEP 3). `register_nodule_decls` (checkty.rs 1340-1401, the caller that seeds the built-in `Fuse`
// trait and calls register_types/register_traits) was DEFERRED at STEP 4 landing on the read that it
// entangles with fuse.rs — **now CLOSED at M-1013 STEP 5** (further down this file): the entanglement
// turned out to be narrower than the STEP-4 FLAG assumed. `fuse::prelude()`/`TRAIT_NAME` (F-A1) is a
// PURE data-shaping fn with no `eval::Evaluator` dependency; only `check_fuse_laws` (F-A2) touches the
// evaluator, and `register_nodule_decls` never calls it. STEP 5 ports the real conditional
// Fuse-seeding path (no fork, no hand-copied stand-in) using the real `fuse::prelude()` mirror.
//
// `resolve_imports` resolves ONE nodule's `use` imports against the phylum-wide `Exports` table
// (M-662): globs first (lowest precedence), then explicit `use`s (which shadow a glob-bound name),
// enforcing three never-silent refusals — unknown name, private (exists but not `pub`), duplicate
// explicit import — plus the glob-vs-glob ambiguity marking (a *reference* to an ambiguous name is
// refused at use-site elsewhere, not here). Pure; no evaluator dependency; live oracle
// `checkty::resolve_imports` (module-private in the oracle — widened to `pub(crate)`, zero logic
// change, the same widening precedent as M-1013 STEP 3's `resolve_ctors`/`first_duplicate`
// (commit 2bb06f88) and the `CoherenceView` widening (commit 65351071), so the in-crate differential
// module can reach it; `Exports`/`NoduleImports` similarly widened, fields included, for marshalling).
//
// FLAG-semcore-31 (a provable no-op, ported anyway for structural fidelity). The oracle's glob pass
// checks `via_explicit.contains(&simple)` even though `via_explicit` is populated ONLY by the LATER
// explicit pass within the SAME `resolve_imports` call — so that check is always `false` when the
// glob pass runs (the sets start fresh per call, and nothing populates `via_explicit` before the
// glob loop reads it). This port THREADS `via_explicit` through the glob pass anyway (rather than
// silently dropping the always-false branch) — arm-for-arm structural fidelity over a "provably dead
// but let's not gamble on that proof" judgment call; this file's own precedent throughout is "port
// every branch the oracle has."
//
// FLAG-semcore-32 (error TEXT is not differential-compared — the compiler_stage5_register.rs
// precedent: "Err messages differ across the two productions ... only the Ok payload is
// meaningful"). This port's four refusals return short `Bytes` reasons (this file's established
// `bytes_concat`-chain idiom), not the oracle's word-for-word multi-sentence diagnostics; the gate
// compares Ok/Err CLASSIFICATION (and, on Ok, the decoded `NoduleImports` payload structurally),
// never message text.

// Exports: mirrors checkty.rs::Exports (1045-1056) as FOUR FLAG-semcore-4 assoc lists (no map
// primitive, M-982) keyed by the qualified (dot-joined) name STRING — `types`/`fns`/`traits` per
// kind, `declared` the ALL-declared-names-with-pub-ness table `resolve_imports` distinguishes
// "unknown" from "private" against. New ctor `Ex` (FLAG-semcore-2 scheme; checked, no collision).
type Exports = Ex(Vec[Pair[Bytes, DataInfo]], Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], Vec[Pair[Bytes, TraitInfo]], Vec[Pair[Bytes, Bool]]);

fn ex_types(e: Exports) => Vec[Pair[Bytes, DataInfo]] =
  match e { Ex(t, _, _, _) => t };

fn ex_fns(e: Exports) => Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]] =
  match e { Ex(_, f, _, _) => f };

fn ex_traits(e: Exports) => Vec[Pair[Bytes, TraitInfo]] =
  match e { Ex(_, _, tr, _) => tr };

fn ex_declared(e: Exports) => Vec[Pair[Bytes, Bool]] =
  match e { Ex(_, _, _, d) => d };

// exports_types_lookup / exports_fns_lookup / exports_traits_lookup / exports_declared_lookup: the
// FLAG-semcore-4 linear scan over each table, keyed by the flat qualified-name `Bytes` string
// (four duplicated pairs rather than a generic dictionary — FLAG-semcore-5 precedent, KISS/YAGNI).
fn exports_types_lookup(t: Vec[Pair[Bytes, DataInfo]], qual: Bytes) => Option[DataInfo] =
  match t {
    Nil => None,
    Cons(p, rest) => match p { Pr(k, v) => match bytes_eq(k, qual) { 0b1 => Some(v), _ => exports_types_lookup(rest, qual) } }
  };

fn exports_fns_lookup(t: Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], qual: Bytes) => Option[FnDecl] =
  match t {
    Nil => None,
    Cons(p, rest) => match p { Pr(k, v) => match bytes_eq(k, qual) { 0b1 => Some(v), _ => exports_fns_lookup(rest, qual) } }
  };

fn exports_traits_lookup(t: Vec[Pair[Bytes, TraitInfo]], qual: Bytes) => Option[TraitInfo] =
  match t {
    Nil => None,
    Cons(p, rest) => match p { Pr(k, v) => match bytes_eq(k, qual) { 0b1 => Some(v), _ => exports_traits_lookup(rest, qual) } }
  };

fn exports_declared_lookup(t: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Bool]], qual: Bytes) => Option[Bool] =
  match t {
    Nil => None,
    Cons(p, rest) => match p { Pr(k, v) => match bytes_eq(k, qual) { 0b1 => Some(v), _ => exports_declared_lookup(rest, qual) } }
  };

// exports_has_pub (checkty.rs 1535-1537): is `qual` declared AND `pub`?
fn exports_has_pub(exports: Exports, qual: Bytes) => Bool =
  match exports_declared_lookup(ex_declared(exports), qual) {
    Some(True) => True,
    _ => False
  };

// NoduleImports: mirrors checkty.rs::NoduleImports (1064-1075). `ambiguous` is a Vec[Bytes] SET
// (membership via `names_contains`) standing in for `BTreeSet<String>` (the same convention affine.rs
// FLAG-semcore-6/-18 established for accumulator sets).
type NoduleImports = NI(Vec[Pair[Bytes, DataInfo]], Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], Vec[Pair[Bytes, TraitInfo]], Vec[Bytes]);

fn ni_types(n: NoduleImports) => Vec[Pair[Bytes, DataInfo]] =
  match n { NI(t, _, _, _) => t };

fn ni_fns(n: NoduleImports) => Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]] =
  match n { NI(_, f, _, _) => f };

fn ni_traits(n: NoduleImports) => Vec[Pair[Bytes, TraitInfo]] =
  match n { NI(_, _, tr, _) => tr };

fn ni_ambiguous(n: NoduleImports) => Vec[Bytes] =
  match n { NI(_, _, _, a) => a };

// nodule_imports_empty: `NoduleImports::default()` (checkty.rs `#[derive(Default)]`, 1064).
fn nodule_imports_empty() => NoduleImports = NI(Nil, Nil, Nil, Nil);

// assoc_remove_*/assoc_set_*: `BTreeMap::insert` (replace-if-present) over each of the three
// per-kind tables — remove any existing pair for `k`, then cons the new one (order-insensitive, an
// assoc-list map; the FLAG-semcore-4 convention, three duplicated pairs per FLAG-semcore-5).
fn assoc_remove_datainfo(t: Vec[Pair[Bytes, DataInfo]], k: Bytes) => Vec[Pair[Bytes, DataInfo]] =
  match t {
    Nil => Nil,
    Cons(p, rest) => match p { Pr(k2, _) => match bytes_eq(k2, k) {
      0b1 => assoc_remove_datainfo(rest, k),
      _ => Cons(p, assoc_remove_datainfo(rest, k))
    } }
  };

fn assoc_set_datainfo(t: Vec[Pair[Bytes, DataInfo]], k: Bytes, v: DataInfo) => Vec[Pair[Bytes, DataInfo]] =
  Cons(Pr(k, v), assoc_remove_datainfo(t, k));

fn assoc_remove_fndecl(t: Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], k: Bytes) => Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]] =
  match t {
    Nil => Nil,
    Cons(p, rest) => match p { Pr(k2, _) => match bytes_eq(k2, k) {
      0b1 => assoc_remove_fndecl(rest, k),
      _ => Cons(p, assoc_remove_fndecl(rest, k))
    } }
  };

fn assoc_set_fndecl(t: Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], k: Bytes, v: FnDecl) => Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]] =
  Cons(Pr(k, v), assoc_remove_fndecl(t, k));

fn assoc_remove_traitinfo(t: Vec[Pair[Bytes, TraitInfo]], k: Bytes) => Vec[Pair[Bytes, TraitInfo]] =
  match t {
    Nil => Nil,
    Cons(p, rest) => match p { Pr(k2, _) => match bytes_eq(k2, k) {
      0b1 => assoc_remove_traitinfo(rest, k),
      _ => Cons(p, assoc_remove_traitinfo(rest, k))
    } }
  };

fn assoc_set_traitinfo(t: Vec[Pair[Bytes, TraitInfo]], k: Bytes, v: TraitInfo) => Vec[Pair[Bytes, TraitInfo]] =
  Cons(Pr(k, v), assoc_remove_traitinfo(t, k));

// names_remove: drop every occurrence of `n` from a `Vec[Bytes]` SET (the `ambiguous.remove`
// counterpart for a bare-name set, not a keyed table).
fn names_remove(xs: Vec[Bytes], n: Bytes) => Vec[Bytes] =
  match xs {
    Nil => Nil,
    Cons(h, t) => match bytes_eq(h, n) {
      0b1 => names_remove(t, n),
      _ => Cons(h, names_remove(t, n))
    }
  };

// insert_export (checkty.rs 1560-1571): insert the export `qual` into `imp` under `simple`. The
// oracle's OWN invariant comment says exactly one of the three export tables holds `qual` — but this
// port still tries all three (arm-for-arm), since nothing in `Exports`'s SHAPE enforces that
// invariant structurally (a caller-supplied fixture that violates it gets the same multi-table write
// the oracle's own three independent `if let`s would produce).
fn insert_export(imp: NoduleImports, exports: Exports, qual: Bytes, simple: Bytes) => NoduleImports =
  let imp1 = match exports_types_lookup(ex_types(exports), qual) {
    Some(info) => NI(assoc_set_datainfo(ni_types(imp), simple, info), ni_fns(imp), ni_traits(imp), ni_ambiguous(imp)),
    None => imp
  } in
  let imp2 = match exports_fns_lookup(ex_fns(exports), qual) {
    Some(fd) => NI(ni_types(imp1), assoc_set_fndecl(ni_fns(imp1), simple, fd), ni_traits(imp1), ni_ambiguous(imp1)),
    None => imp1
  } in
  match exports_traits_lookup(ex_traits(exports), qual) {
    Some(ti) => NI(ni_types(imp2), ni_fns(imp2), assoc_set_traitinfo(ni_traits(imp2), simple, ti), ni_ambiguous(imp2)),
    None => imp2
  };

// remove_import (checkty.rs 1574-1580): drop any binding for `simple` across all three per-kind
// tables (the glob-vs-glob-ambiguity demotion) — `ambiguous` is untouched (matching the oracle).
fn remove_import(imp: NoduleImports, simple: Bytes) => NoduleImports =
  NI(assoc_remove_datainfo(ni_types(imp), simple), assoc_remove_fndecl(ni_fns(imp), simple), assoc_remove_traitinfo(ni_traits(imp), simple), ni_ambiguous(imp));

// qualify (checkty.rs 1286-1292): `path.0.is_empty() ? name : path.0.join(".") + "." + name`.
fn qualify(path: Path, name: Bytes) => Bytes =
  match path_segs(path) {
    Nil => name,
    Cons(_, _) => bytes_concat(join_dot(path_segs(path)), bytes_concat(".", name))
  };

// bytes_starts_with / bytes_contains_char(_at): small string primitives NOT already in this file —
// needed because `direct_child`/`split_last_seg` operate on the FLAT qualified-name string (the
// `Exports` table's key shape), unlike every prior string helper here (which walks Path SEGMENTS,
// e.g. `join_dot`). Same byte-at-a-time idiom as `count_bindigits_at`/`filter_bindigits_at`
// (`bytes_slice` + `bytes_eq`, source-length-bounded direct-tail recursion).
fn bytes_starts_with(s: Bytes, prefix: Bytes) => Bool =
  match lt(bytes_len(s), bytes_len(prefix)) {
    0b1 => False,
    _ => match bytes_eq(bytes_slice(s, zero32(), bytes_len(prefix)), prefix) { 0b1 => True, _ => False }
  };

fn bytes_contains_char_at(s: Bytes, ch: Bytes, i: Binary{32}, n: Binary{32}) => Bool =
  match lt(i, n) {
    0b1 => match bytes_eq(bytes_slice(s, i, add_u(i, one32())), ch) {
      0b1 => True,
      _ => bytes_contains_char_at(s, ch, add_u(i, one32()), n)
    },
    _ => False
  };

fn bytes_contains_char(s: Bytes, ch: Bytes) => Bool =
  bytes_contains_char_at(s, ch, zero32(), bytes_len(s));

// direct_child (checkty.rs 1542-1550): is `qual` exactly ONE segment under `prefix`? `Some(simple)`
// iff `qual == prefix + "." + simple` with `simple` itself containing no further `.`.
fn direct_child(prefix: Bytes, qual: Bytes) => Option[Bytes] =
  match bytes_starts_with(qual, prefix) {
    False => None,
    True =>
      let rest0 = bytes_slice(qual, bytes_len(prefix), bytes_len(qual)) in
      match lt(zero32(), bytes_len(rest0)) {
        0b1 =>
          match bytes_eq(bytes_slice(rest0, zero32(), one32()), ".") {
            0b1 =>
              let rest = bytes_slice(rest0, one32(), bytes_len(rest0)) in
              match lt(zero32(), bytes_len(rest)) {
                0b1 => match bytes_contains_char(rest, ".") {
                  True => None,
                  False => Some(rest)
                },
                _ => None
              },
            _ => None
          },
        _ => None
      }
  };

// split_last_seg_go / split_last_seg (checkty.rs 1553-1557): `path.0.split_last()` restated as an
// accumulate-then-reverse walk (the FLAG-parse list-building convention) — last segment plus the
// DOT-JOINED prefix of everything before it (`Option[Pair[Bytes, Bytes]]`, matching the oracle's
// `Option<(String, String)>` return shape exactly).
fn rev_bytes_acc(xs: Vec[Bytes], acc: Vec[Bytes]) => Vec[Bytes] =
  match xs {
    Nil => acc,
    Cons(h, t) => rev_bytes_acc(t, Cons(h, acc))
  };

fn split_last_seg_go(segs: Vec[Bytes], acc: Vec[Bytes]) => Option[Pair[Bytes, Vec[Bytes]]] =
  match segs {
    Nil => None,
    Cons(h, t) => match t {
      Nil => Some(Pr(h, rev_bytes_acc(acc, Nil))),
      Cons(_, _) => split_last_seg_go(t, Cons(h, acc))
    }
  };

fn split_last_seg(path: Path) => Option[Pair[Bytes, Bytes]] =
  match split_last_seg_go(path_segs(path), Nil) {
    None => None,
    Some(pr) => match pr { Pr(last, init) => Some(Pr(last, join_dot(init))) }
  };

// ── resolve_imports (checkty.rs 1423-1533) — the two-pass import resolver ───────────────────────

// GlobPassState: the glob loop's threaded (imp, via_explicit, via_glob) triple (FLAG-semcore-6
// value-threading convention — Rust's `&mut` accumulators restated as an explicit fold).
type GlobPassState = GPS(NoduleImports, Vec[Bytes], Vec[Bytes]);

// resolve_imports_glob_quals: the INNER loop over `exports.declared`'s entries for ONE glob item's
// `prefix` (checkty.rs's `for qual in exports.declared.keys()`). FLAG-semcore-31 keeps the
// (provably always-false, see the file-header FLAG) `via_explicit` check for structural fidelity.
fn resolve_imports_glob_quals(exports: Exports, prefix: Bytes, decl: Vec[Pair[Bytes, Bool]], st: GlobPassState) => GlobPassState =
  match decl {
    Nil => st,
    Cons(p, rest) => match p { Pr(qual, _) => match direct_child(prefix, qual) {
      None => resolve_imports_glob_quals(exports, prefix, rest, st),
      Some(simple) => match exports_has_pub(exports, qual) {
        False => resolve_imports_glob_quals(exports, prefix, rest, st),
        True => match st { GPS(imp, via_explicit, via_glob) =>
          match names_contains(via_explicit, simple) {
            True => resolve_imports_glob_quals(exports, prefix, rest, st),
            False => match names_contains(via_glob, simple) {
              True =>
                let imp2 = NI(ni_types(imp), ni_fns(imp), ni_traits(imp), Cons(simple, ni_ambiguous(imp))) in
                resolve_imports_glob_quals(exports, prefix, rest, GPS(remove_import(imp2, simple), via_explicit, via_glob)),
              False =>
                resolve_imports_glob_quals(exports, prefix, rest, GPS(insert_export(imp, exports, qual, simple), via_explicit, Cons(simple, via_glob)))
            }
          }
        }
      }
    } }
  };

// resolve_imports_glob_items: the OUTER glob-pass loop over `nodule.items` (non-glob / non-use items
// are skipped — the `let Item::Use(UsePath{path, glob:true}) = item else { continue }` mirror).
fn resolve_imports_glob_items(exports: Exports, items: Vec[Item], st: GlobPassState) => GlobPassState =
  match items {
    Nil => st,
    Cons(it, rest) => match it {
      ItUse(up) => match usepath_glob(up) {
        True => resolve_imports_glob_items(exports, rest, resolve_imports_glob_quals(exports, join_dot(path_segs(usepath_path(up))), ex_declared(exports), st)),
        False => resolve_imports_glob_items(exports, rest, st)
      },
      _ => resolve_imports_glob_items(exports, rest, st)
    }
  };

// ExplicitPassState: the explicit-pass threaded (imp, via_explicit) pair.
type ExplicitPassState = EPS(NoduleImports, Vec[Bytes]);

// resolve_imports_explicit_items (checkty.rs's explicit-`use` loop, 1478-1531): the never-silent
// refusals in the oracle's EXACT order — unnamed path, un-qualified single-segment path, unknown
// name, private name, duplicate explicit import (FLAG-semcore-32: reason strings, not the oracle's
// full diagnostic text).
fn resolve_imports_explicit_items(exports: Exports, site: Bytes, items: Vec[Item], st: ExplicitPassState) => Result[ExplicitPassState, Bytes] =
  match items {
    Nil => Ok(st),
    Cons(it, rest) => match it {
      ItUse(up) => match usepath_glob(up) {
        True => resolve_imports_explicit_items(exports, site, rest, st),
        False => match split_last_seg(usepath_path(up)) {
          None => Err(bytes_concat("`", bytes_concat(site, "`: a `use` path must name an item (M-662)"))),
          Some(pr) => match pr { Pr(simple, prefix) =>
            match lt(zero32(), bytes_len(prefix)) {
              0b1 =>
                let qual = bytes_concat(prefix, bytes_concat(".", simple)) in
                match exports_declared_lookup(ex_declared(exports), qual) {
                  None => Err(bytes_concat("`use ", bytes_concat(qual, "`: no such name in the phylum (M-662)"))),
                  Some(is_pub) => match is_pub {
                    False => Err(bytes_concat("`use ", bytes_concat(qual, "`: exists but is not `pub` (M-662)"))),
                    True => match st { EPS(imp, via_explicit) =>
                      match names_contains(via_explicit, simple) {
                        True => Err(bytes_concat("duplicate import of `", bytes_concat(simple, "` (M-662)"))),
                        False =>
                          let imp2 = NI(ni_types(imp), ni_fns(imp), ni_traits(imp), names_remove(ni_ambiguous(imp), simple)) in
                          resolve_imports_explicit_items(exports, site, rest, EPS(insert_export(imp2, exports, qual, simple), Cons(simple, via_explicit)))
                      }
                    }
                  }
                },
              _ => Err(bytes_concat("`use ", bytes_concat(simple, "`: a cross-nodule import must be nodule-qualified (M-662)")))
            }
          }
        }
      },
      _ => resolve_imports_explicit_items(exports, site, rest, st)
    }
  };

// resolve_imports (checkty.rs 1423-1533, top level): globs first (lowest precedence), then
// explicit `use`s (which shadow a glob-bound name) — Ok(NoduleImports) or the first refusal.
fn resolve_imports(nod: Nodule, exports: Exports) => Result[NoduleImports, Bytes] =
  match nod { Nod(path, _, items) =>
    let site = qualify(path, "<use>") in
    let glob_st = resolve_imports_glob_items(exports, items, GPS(nodule_imports_empty(), Nil, Nil)) in
    match glob_st { GPS(imp0, via_explicit0, _) =>
      match resolve_imports_explicit_items(exports, site, items, EPS(imp0, via_explicit0)) {
        Err(e) => Err(e),
        Ok(final_st) => match final_st { EPS(imp, _) => Ok(imp) }
      }
    }
  };

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// fuse.rs F-A1 -- the `Fuse` PRELUDE trait vocabulary ONLY (M-1013 STEP 5; DN-58 §A / M-965).
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Ports fuse.rs::{TRAIT_NAME, prelude} (fuse.rs 58-84) -- the PURE, evaluator-free half of fuse.rs.
// `prelude()` hand-builds one `TraitInfo` (`trait Fuse[T] { fn join(a: T, b: T) => T; }`), a plain
// data-shaping function with NO dependency on `eval::Evaluator` -- unlike `check_fuse_laws` (F-A2,
// fuse.rs 116-236), which RUNS a scratch `Evaluator` to exhaustively verify the semilattice laws over
// an enumerable domain and STAYS DEFERRED (the file-header FLAG's entanglement is real for F-A2, not
// F-A1 -- confirmed by reading fuse.rs itself: `prelude()`'s only imports are `ast` types, never
// `eval`). This narrower slice is exactly what UNBLOCKS `register_nodule_decls` below (checkty.rs
// 1340-1401), which only ever calls `fuse::{TRAIT_NAME, prelude}` -- `check_fuse_laws` runs LATER, as
// a separate `check_nodule_with` post-pass this increment does not port (still an honest, flagged
// residual gap, not silently worked around -- G2/VR-5). Live oracle `fuse::prelude`/`TRAIT_NAME` are
// already `pub(crate)` (no widening needed for this slice).

// fuse_trait_name: the fuse.rs::TRAIT_NAME single source of truth (a fn, not a bare literal repeated
// at each use site -- Law of Demeter).
fn fuse_trait_name() => Bytes = "Fuse";

// fuse_join_sig: fuse.rs::prelude's one `FnSig` -- `fn join(a: T, b: T) => T`. No method-level type
// params (the trait's OWN param `T` lives in `TraitInfo.params`, not here -- DN-58 §A.2's explicit-
// type-variable idiom, no implicit `Self`), no effects/budgets.
fn fuse_join_sig() => FnSig =
  FS("join", Nil, Cons(Prm("a", TR(Named("T", Nil), None)), Cons(Prm("b", TR(Named("T", Nil), None)), Nil)), TR(Named("T", Nil), None), Nil, Nil);

// fuse_prelude: fuse.rs::prelude (58-84) verbatim -- `TrInfo(name, params, sigs)`.
fn fuse_prelude() => TraitInfo =
  TrInfo(fuse_trait_name(), Cons("T", Nil), Cons(fuse_join_sig(), Nil));

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// checkty.rs register_nodule_decls (M-1013 STEP 5; checkty.rs 1340-1401) -- the DEFERRED caller
// FLAGged at this file's header and at M-1013 STEP 4's landing, now tractable via the fuse_prelude
// slice above.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Register one (resolved) nodule's declaration-level registries -- data types (register_types, seeded
// with the `Bool` prelude), traits (register_traits), the CONDITIONAL built-in `Fuse` trait seed
// (M-965 F-A1: only when this nodule's own items contain an `impl Fuse[...] for ...`; never based on
// whether `fuse(a, b)` is called), and function signatures (a fresh Pass-2 loop over `Item::Fn`, this
// file's first port of that specific loop). Ok(NoduleRegs) or the FIRST refusal, in the oracle's
// EXACT order. Pure; no evaluator dependency (this is the "registration" work `check_nodule_with`
// runs before any body/instance is checked). Guarantee: `Declared` (a structural registry check, the
// same tag `register_types`/`register_traits` already carry).

// checkty_prelude: checkty.rs::prelude (600-618) -- the builtin `Bool = False | True` registry seed
// `register_nodule_decls` inserts before `register_types` runs, so intra-nodule resolution of `Bool`
// is unchanged.
fn checkty_prelude() => DataInfo =
  DI("Bool", Nil, Cons(CI("False", Nil), Cons(CI("True", Nil), Nil)));

// checkty_unit_prelude: checkty.rs::unit_prelude (DN-137 Alt D / M-1102) -- the second builtin
// prelude entry, `type Unit = Unit;` -- a payload-free, single-constructor data type (the arity-0
// M-826 product-family member). Seeded the SAME way as `checkty_prelude`'s `Bool` (this mirror
// carries no `home` field at all -- see `unqualify_data_info`'s doc comment -- so the seed is just
// `DI(name, params, ctors)`, byte-identical in shape to `Bool`'s).
fn checkty_unit_prelude() => DataInfo =
  DI("Unit", Nil, Cons(CI("Unit", Nil), Nil));

// nodule_uses_fuse: checkty.rs 1367-1370 -- does this nodule's OWN items contain an
// `impl Fuse[...] for ...`? (Never based on whether `fuse(a, b)` is CALLED -- the repr-type fast path
// in `check_fuse` never touches the trait registry at all; restated from the oracle's own comment.)
fn nodule_uses_fuse(items: Vec[Item]) => Bool =
  match items {
    Nil => False,
    Cons(it, rest) => match it {
      ItImpl(id) => match bytes_eq(imd_trait_name(id), fuse_trait_name()) {
        0b1 => True,
        _ => nodule_uses_fuse(rest)
      },
      _ => nodule_uses_fuse(rest)
    }
  };

// fuse_redeclare_err: checkty.rs 1372-1378 / 1381-1387 -- the never-silent refusal for either branch
// that finds `Fuse` already present in `traits` (a user nodule trying to redeclare the built-in). Both
// oracle call sites use the SAME message text (FLAG-semcore-32: error TEXT is not differential-
// compared -- only Ok/Err CLASSIFICATION is; this file's established convention throughout STEP 4/5).
fn fuse_redeclare_err() => Bytes =
  "cannot redeclare the built-in prelude trait `Fuse` (DN-58 §A / M-965 F-A1) -- its lawful-merge `join` contract is already provided by the prelude; remove this declaration and `impl Fuse[T] for T { fn join(a: T, b: T) => T = ... }` directly";

// seed_fuse_trait: checkty.rs 1367-1391 -- conditionally seed the built-in `Fuse` trait (iff this
// nodule declares an `impl Fuse[...] for ...`), refusing any nodule that tries to redeclare it
// (already present, on EITHER branch) -- never a silent shadow of the built-in (G2/VR-5), mirroring
// how redeclaring `Bool` would collide in `types`.
fn seed_fuse_trait(traits: Vec[TraitInfo], items: Vec[Item]) => Result[Vec[TraitInfo], Bytes] =
  match nodule_uses_fuse(items) {
    True => match traits_contains(traits, fuse_trait_name()) {
      True => Err(fuse_redeclare_err()),
      False => Ok(Cons(fuse_prelude(), traits))
    },
    False => match traits_contains(traits, fuse_trait_name()) {
      True => Err(fuse_redeclare_err()),
      False => Ok(traits)
    }
  };

// fns_contains: the `fns.contains_key`-equivalent membership scan over the FLAG-semcore-4 assoc-list
// fn registry `Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]]`.
fn fns_contains(fns: Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], name: Bytes) => Bool =
  match fns {
    Nil => False,
    Cons(p, rest) => match p { Pr(k, _) => match bytes_eq(k, name) { 0b1 => True, _ => fns_contains(rest, name) } }
  };

// register_fns: checkty.rs 1392-1400 -- Pass 2, the fn-signature registration loop. Non-`Item::Fn`
// items are skipped (the `let Item::Fn(fd) = item else { continue }` mirror); each fn's OWN
// type-parameter names (`fnsig_tyvar_names`, the `sig.param_names()` mirror) must have no duplicate,
// then the fn NAME must be free in the registry so far -- the first refusal wins, `Ok` with the built
// registry otherwise.
fn register_fns(items: Vec[Item], acc: Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]]) => Result[Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], Bytes] =
  match items {
    Nil => Ok(acc),
    Cons(it, rest) => match it {
      ItFn(fd) => match first_duplicate(fnsig_tyvar_names(fndecl_sig(fd))) {
        Some(dup) => Err(bytes_concat("duplicate type parameter `", bytes_concat(dup, bytes_concat("` in `", bytes_concat(fnsig_name(fndecl_sig(fd)), "`"))))),
        None => match fns_contains(acc, fnsig_name(fndecl_sig(fd))) {
          True => Err("duplicate function"),
          False => register_fns(rest, Cons(Pr(fnsig_name(fndecl_sig(fd)), fd), acc))
        }
      },
      _ => register_fns(rest, acc)
    }
  };

// NoduleRegs: mirrors checkty.rs::NoduleRegs (1336-1340) field-for-field (types, fns, traits). New
// ctor `NR` (FLAG-semcore-2 scheme; checked against every other family in this file, no collision).
type NoduleRegs = NR(Vec[DataInfo], Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]], Vec[TraitInfo]);

fn nr_types(r: NoduleRegs) => Vec[DataInfo] =
  match r { NR(t, _, _) => t };

fn nr_fns(r: NoduleRegs) => Vec[Pair[Bytes, FnDecl]] =
  match r { NR(_, f, _) => f };

fn nr_traits(r: NoduleRegs) => Vec[TraitInfo] =
  match r { NR(_, _, tr) => tr };

// register_nodule_decls: checkty.rs 1348-1401, top level. Runs the four passes in the oracle's EXACT
// order -- types (seeded with the Bool and Unit (DN-137) preludes), traits, the conditional Fuse
// seed, then fns -- and returns Ok(NoduleRegs) or the FIRST refusal.
fn register_nodule_decls(nod: Nodule) => Result[NoduleRegs, Bytes] =
  match register_types(Cons(checkty_prelude(), Cons(checkty_unit_prelude(), Nil)), nod) {
    Err(e) => Err(e),
    Ok(types) => match register_traits(types, nod) {
      Err(e) => Err(e),
      Ok(traits0) => match seed_fuse_trait(traits0, nodule_items(nod)) {
        Err(e) => Err(e),
        Ok(traits) => match register_fns(nodule_items(nod), Nil) {
          Err(e) => Err(e),
          Ok(fns) => Ok(NR(types, fns, traits))
        }
      }
    }
  };

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// mono.rs TYPE ROUND-TRIP + WORK-ITEM KEY family (M-1013 STEP 6). Closes FLAG-semcore-17.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Ports mono.rs's remaining PURE `Ty`/`TypeRef` round-trip helpers plus the monomorphization
// work-item dedup key — the last of mono.rs's non-`Env`-dependent leaves, sitting directly upstream
// of the (still un-ported, still entangled) `Mono` driver itself: `closure_field_ty`/
// `closure_param_ref` (RFC-0024 §4A.2/§4A.4, M-704 — a closure tag-sum capture's field/param type),
// `mangle_ty_in_ty` (rewrite an applied data type to its mangled-nullary form), `ty_to_source_ref`/
// `ty_to_ref`/`ty_to_ref_tagged` (a checked `Ty` back to a surface `TypeRef`, two variants — source-
// named vs. mangled-nullary — plus the guarantee-tagged form), and `item_key` (the canonical dedup
// key of one `WorkItem`). All are pure `Ty -> {Ty, TypeRef, Bytes}` transformers depending only on
// the increment-1 `Ty`/`TypeRef`/`BaseType` vocabulary and the increment-4 mangling family
// (INDEPENDENT of M-1007/M-1008/M-1010/M-1011/M-1012). Live oracle: `mono::{closure_field_ty,
// closure_param_ref, mangle_ty_in_ty, ty_to_source_ref, ty_to_ref, ty_to_ref_tagged, item_key,
// Item}` — all six fns plus the `Item` enum were Rust MODULE-PRIVATE (FLAG-semcore-17's original
// finding); this leaf widens all seven items to `pub(crate)` (zero logic change, the STEP-3/4/5
// precedent: `resolve_ctors`/`first_duplicate`, commit 2bb06f88; `Exports`/`NoduleImports`,
// `CoherenceView`, commit 65351071) so the in-crate differential module can reach them directly —
// a marshalling differential (`decode_ty`/`decode_typeref` against the real oracle output),
// not a hand-derived one.
//
// FLAG-semcore-33 (`WorkItem` — a FRESH name for mono.rs's `Item`; `Item`/`ItFn` are already taken).
// This nodule already declares a type `Item` (checkty.rs's AST-level nodule-item sum — `ItType`/
// `ItFn`/`ItTrait`/`ItImpl`/`ItUse`, M-1013 STEP 3/4) — a COMPLETELY different `Item` from mono.rs's
// own monomorphization work-item enum, which happens to share the Rust type name only because the
// two live in different Rust modules (`checkty::Item`-shaped construct is actually `ast::Item`; no
// literal Rust name collision there, but re-using the bare name `Item` here WOULD collide with this
// nodule's own flat namespace, FLAG-semcore-2's discipline). So mono.rs's `Item` mirrors here as
// `WorkItem`, with ctors `WiFn`/`WiData`/`WiMethod` (the `Wi` prefix — checked against every other
// family in this file: `Ty`/`Wd`/`CI`/`DI`/`Mp`/`Hd`/`Ct`/`TD`/`Ex`/`NI`/`NR`/`GPS`/`EPS`/`FtRepr`
// and this nodule's copied `Kw*`/`Ct`/`TD` surface families — no collision). `Item::Fn`'s Rust field
// order (`name, targs, wargs, fn_args, dyn_fns`) is preserved verbatim in `WiFn`'s tuple-positional
// fields (this nodule's established field-order-fidelity convention, e.g. `FnSig`/`FnDecl` above).
//
// FLAG-semcore-34 (`ty_to_source_ref`/`ty_to_ref` split into a `_base` (`BaseType`-only) helper plus
// a thin `TR(_, None)` wrapper). Rust's two fns each build a `BaseType` inline then wrap it once in
// `TypeRef::unguaranteed(base)` at the end; this port factors the shared `BaseType`-only recursion
// into `ty_to_source_base`/`ty_to_ref_base` so `ty_to_ref_tagged` (which needs the `BaseType` with a
// CALLER-supplied guarantee, not `None`) reuses `ty_to_ref_base` directly rather than re-deriving it
// or building a `TypeRef` and overwriting its guarantee field (this port has no field-mutation
// primitive — value semantics — so the Rust `let mut r = ty_to_ref(t); r.guarantee = guarantee;`
// pattern is restated as "compute the base once, wrap twice" instead). Behaviourally identical: the
// `BaseType` shape produced for a given `Ty` is exactly Rust's, and the guarantee slot is `None` (in
// `ty_to_ref`/`ty_to_source_ref`) or the caller's value (`ty_to_ref_tagged`) either way.

// ── closure_field_ty / closure_param_ref (mono.rs, RFC-0024 SS4A.2/SS4A.4) ──────────────────────
fn closure_field_ty(t: Ty) => Ty =
  match t {
    TyFn(a, b) => TyData(mangle_arrow(a, b), Nil),
    _ => mangle_ty_in_ty(t)
  };

fn closure_param_ref(t: Ty) => TypeRef =
  match t {
    TyFn(a, b) => ty_to_ref(TyData(mangle_arrow(a, b), Nil)),
    _ => ty_to_ref(t)
  };

// ── mangle_ty_in_ty (mono.rs) — rewrite an applied data type to its mangled-nullary form ────────
fn mangle_ty_in_ty(t: Ty) => Ty =
  match t {
    TyBinary(_) => t,
    TyTernary(_) => t,
    TyDense(_, _) => t,
    TyVsa(_, _, _) => t,
    TySubstrate(_) => t,
    TyBytes => t,
    TyFloat => t,
    TySeq(elem, n) => TySeq(mangle_ty_in_ty(elem), n),
    TyData(n, args) => match args { Nil => t, Cons(_, _) => TyData(mangle_ty(t), Nil) },
    TyVar(v) => TyVar(v),
    TyFn(_, _) => t
  };

// ── ty_to_source_ref / ty_to_ref / ty_to_ref_tagged (mono.rs) — checked Ty -> surface TypeRef ───
// ty_to_source_base: the SOURCE-named round-trip (an applied data type keeps its ORIGINAL name and
// recurses into its arguments) — used to thread an `expected` type into re-inference.
fn ty_to_source_base(t: Ty) => BaseType =
  match t {
    TyBinary(w) => match w { WdLit(n) => KwBinary(WLit(n)), WdVar(v) => KwBinary(WName(v)) },
    TyTernary(w) => match w { WdLit(m) => KwTernary(WLit(m)), WdVar(v) => KwTernary(WName(v)) },
    TyDense(d, sc) => KwDense(d, sc),
    TyVsa(model, dim, sp) => Vsa(model, dim, sp),
    TySubstrate(tag) => KwSubstrate(tag),
    TySeq(elem, n) => KwSeq(ty_to_source_ref(elem), n),
    TyBytes => KwBytes,
    TyFloat => KwFloat,
    TyData(n, args) => Named(n, ty_to_source_ref_list(args)),
    TyVar(v) => Named(v, Nil),
    TyFn(a, r) => FnArrow(ty_to_source_ref(a), ty_to_source_ref(r))
  };

fn ty_to_source_ref(t: Ty) => TypeRef = TR(ty_to_source_base(t), None);

// ty_to_source_ref_list: map a constructor's applied type args through ty_to_source_ref (the direct
// recursive walk this nodule uses throughout — no first-class-fn `map` primitive, FLAG-semcore-5's
// KISS/YAGNI precedent for avoiding a generic higher-order helper in a bounded increment).
fn ty_to_source_ref_list(ts: Vec[Ty]) => Vec[TypeRef] =
  match ts { Nil => Nil, Cons(h, t) => Cons(ty_to_source_ref(h), ty_to_source_ref_list(t)) };

// ty_to_ref_base: the MANGLED-NULLARY round-trip (an applied data type's arguments are baked into
// its mangled name, so it becomes a nullary `Named`) — used for a rewritten `FnDecl`/`Param`/
// `Ascribe`'s emitted surface type.
fn ty_to_ref_base(t: Ty) => BaseType =
  match t {
    TyBinary(w) => match w { WdLit(n) => KwBinary(WLit(n)), WdVar(v) => KwBinary(WName(v)) },
    TyTernary(w) => match w { WdLit(m) => KwTernary(WLit(m)), WdVar(v) => KwTernary(WName(v)) },
    TyDense(d, sc) => KwDense(d, sc),
    TyVsa(model, dim, sp) => Vsa(model, dim, sp),
    TySubstrate(tag) => KwSubstrate(tag),
    TySeq(elem, n) => KwSeq(ty_to_ref(elem), n),
    TyBytes => KwBytes,
    TyFloat => KwFloat,
    TyData(n, args) => match args { Nil => Named(n, Nil), Cons(_, _) => Named(mangle_ty(t), Nil) },
    TyVar(v) => Named(bytes_concat("VAR_", v), Nil),
    TyFn(a, r) => FnArrow(ty_to_ref(a), ty_to_ref(r))
  };

fn ty_to_ref(t: Ty) => TypeRef = TR(ty_to_ref_base(t), None);

// ty_to_ref_tagged: like ty_to_ref, but attaches the CALLER-supplied `guarantee` (the source
// declaration's own `@ g` — never derived from `t`, never merged across instantiations).
fn ty_to_ref_tagged(t: Ty, guarantee: Option[Strength]) => TypeRef = TR(ty_to_ref_base(t), guarantee);

// ── WorkItem (mono.rs::Item, FLAG-semcore-33) + item_key (mono.rs) ──────────────────────────────
// WorkItem: mirrors mono.rs::Item field-for-field (Fn's 5 fields, Data's 2, Method's 3 — Rust's own
// declared field order in each variant, verbatim).
type WorkItem =
    WiFn(Bytes, Vec[Ty], Vec[Width], Vec[Pair[Binary{32}, Bytes]], Vec[Pair[Binary{32}, Bytes]])
  | WiData(Bytes, Vec[Ty])
  | WiMethod(Bytes, Bytes, Ty);

// item_key: the canonical dedup key of a work item — a kind-tagged mangled string.
fn item_key(item: WorkItem) => Bytes =
  match item {
    WiFn(name, targs, wargs, fa, df) => bytes_concat("fn:", mangle_hof_decl(name, targs, wargs, fa, df)),
    WiData(name, targs) => bytes_concat("data:", mangle_decl(name, targs)),
    WiMethod(trait_name, method, for_ty) => bytes_concat("method:", mangle_method(method, trait_name, for_ty))
  };

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// eval.rs DYNAMIC PATTERN MATCH -- FIRST eval.rs FRAGMENT (M-740 Stage 5, increment 12 partial;
// M-1013 eval PR-1). Ports the Data/Ctor/Ident/Tuple/Wildcard fragment of Evaluator::try_match.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// The file header's DEFERRED list (top of this file) names eval.rs wholesale as "the heavy
// entangled core" blocked on `eval::Evaluator`/`eval::L1Value` (Env + PrimRegistry + SwapEngine +
// the CEK work-stack machine + the trusted kernel `Value` type). Triaging eval.rs (M-1013's
// increment 12, "THE hardest wave") for a bounded, witnessable slice per that increment's own
// scope note: `run_machine`/`eval_step`/`apply_frame` (the CEK loop itself, ~750 Rust lines) are
// irreducibly Env/PrimRegistry/SwapEngine/fuel/depth-entangled -- no sub-fragment of the machine
// runs standalone. But `Evaluator::try_match` (eval.rs 2005-2079, the runtime pattern matcher
// `Expr::Match`/`Frame::MatchArms`/`for`-binder dispatch drives) is NOT part of that machine: it
// is a small (~75 Rust line), separately-callable `&self` method whose ONLY `Env` dependency is a
// single `self.env.types.get(ty)` lookup for the `Ident`-as-nullary-ctor check -- exactly the
// `DataInfo`/`CtorInfo`/`types_lookup` registry shape THIS nodule already ported at increment 8
// (M-1013 STEP 3). So `try_match` decomposes cleanly into a PORTABLE fragment (four of its six
// `Pattern` arms: `Wildcard`/`Ident`/`Ctor`/`Tuple` -- pure structural matching over the checked
// type registry) and one OUT-OF-SCOPE arm (`Lit`, FLAG-semcore-35 below); `Or` already refuses in
// the Rust oracle (a checker invariant, ported verbatim as the same refusal).
//
// FLAG-semcore-35 (`Pattern::Lit` -- an honest narrowing, now PARTIALLY lifted by DN-105 / M-1035).
// Rust's `Lit` arm compares a literal pattern against `L1Value::Repr(v)` via `crate::elab::lit_value`
// + the TRUSTED KERNEL `Value`'s `repr()`/`payload()` equality. **DN-105 lifts the `Bytes` case**: a
// `Bytes` scrutinee now rides a dedicated `LReprBytes(Bytes)` carrier (see `LVal` below), so
// `lval_try_match`'s `PLit` arm compares it against a TEXT (`Str`) byte-string literal by byte
// content -- a real eval-match mirror for the string-literal (#72) target. What STAYS deferred: the
// `0x..`-hex byte-string *value synthesis* (`lit_value`'s `LBytes` arm, FLAG-semcore-25 -- no
// wild-free hex->byte primitive), so a `0x..` pattern arm's eval propagates that `Err`; and every
// NON-`Bytes` repr (`Binary`/`Ternary`/`Float`) plus `Substrate`/`Fn`, which still collapse into one
// `LOpaque` (their payload dropped) -- their `PLit` arm stays an explicit `Err`, never a fabricated
// `Ok`/silently-wrong comparison (G2/VR-5). A `Data` value vs a literal is `Ok(false)` (faithful to
// Rust's `Data => Ok(false)`). So the port now claims oracle parity for the `Bytes`-vs-`Str`-literal
// eval-match (witnessed in `compiler_stage5_evalmatch.rs`), keeps the `0x..`/`LOpaque` sub-cases as
// explicit, never-silent deferrals, and the standalone clean-refusal probe still covers the deferred
// path. Every OTHER arm this port implements (`Wildcard`/`Ident`/`Ctor`/`Tuple`) treats the collapsed
// `LOpaque` reprs identically (bind-whole or no-match) in the REAL oracle, which is exactly why the
// `LOpaque` collapse stays lossless for everything OUTSIDE the newly-lifted `Bytes` case.
//
// FLAG-semcore-36 (`LVal` -- the eval.rs::L1Value mirror, TRIMMED to what `try_match`'s ported
// fragment needs). `Data { ty, ctor, fields }` mirrors verbatim (`LData`, FLAG-semcore-2 `L`-prefix
// scheme extended: no collision against any family declared above). `Repr`/`Substrate`/`Fn` collapse
// into ONE nullary `LOpaque` (FLAG-semcore-35 explains why this is lossless for the ported arms).
// `binds` (Rust's `&mut Vec<(String, L1Value)>`, mutated by `push` -- APPEND order) is restated as
// the FLAG-semcore-6 value-threaded collapse: threaded through and RETURNED, and appended (not
// prepended, unlike the FLAG-semcore-13 assoc-list convention) via `bind_append` below, because
// `binds`' ORDER is part of the observable differential (`Vec` equality is order-sensitive) --
// unlike `unify`'s substitution, whose FIRST-MATCH lookup semantics make prepend-order invisible.
// DN-105 / M-1035 (ENB-12): the `Bytes` repr value is LIFTED out of the `LOpaque` collapse into a
// dedicated `LReprBytes(Bytes)` carrier, so `lval_try_match`'s `PLit` arm can compare a `Bytes`
// scrutinee against a TEXT (`Str`) byte-string-literal pattern by byte content -- a REAL eval-match
// mirror of eval.rs's `try_match` `Pattern::Lit` `Repr`-case for the string-literal (#72) target
// (DN-105 §5). Every OTHER repr (`Binary`/`Ternary`/`Float`) plus `Substrate`/`Fn` stays collapsed
// into `LOpaque` (their `PLit` eval-match stays deferred -- FLAG-semcore-35), and the `0x..`-hex
// byte-string *value synthesis* stays deferred too (FLAG-semcore-25 -- `lit_value`'s `LBytes` arm),
// so a `0x..` pattern arm's eval propagates that deferral as an explicit `Err`, never a silent
// mismatch (G2). The Bytes carrier is thus a MINIMAL, targeted lift, not a full `L1Value` port.
type LVal = LData(Bytes, Bytes, Vec[LVal]) | LReprBytes(Bytes) | LOpaque;

// bind_append: append one `(name, val)` binding to the END of `binds` -- mirrors Rust's
// `binds.push((n.clone(), val.clone()))` exactly (order-preserving; bounded by one pattern's own
// binder count, never source-input-driven, so no depth budget is warranted -- the same class of
// bounded structural recursion as `pat_append`/`ty_append` above).
fn bind_append(binds: Vec[Pair[Bytes, LVal]], n: Bytes, v: LVal) => Vec[Pair[Bytes, LVal]] =
  match binds {
    Nil => Cons(Pr(n, v), Nil),
    Cons(h, t) => Cons(h, bind_append(t, n, v))
  };

// (`pattern_len` -- the arity-counting fn over `Vec[Pattern]` -- is ALREADY ported above, increment
// 6/M-1011's `expr_len`/`pattern_len` pair; reused here verbatim, no redeclaration needed.)

// lval_ident_is_ctor_of / ctorinfo_any_named: mirrors try_match's `Ident` guard
// `self.env.types.get(ty).is_some_and(|d| d.ctors.iter().any(|c| c.name == *n))` over the ALREADY
// -ported `types_lookup`/`di_ctors`/`ci_name` registry accessors (increment 8, M-1013 STEP 3) --
// no new registry machinery needed, only the `.any(name == n)` scan.
fn ctorinfo_any_named(ctors: Vec[CtorInfo], n: Bytes) => Bool =
  match ctors {
    Nil => False,
    Cons(c, rest) => match bytes_eq(ci_name(c), n) { 0b1 => True, _ => ctorinfo_any_named(rest, n) }
  };

fn lval_ident_is_ctor_of(types: Vec[DataInfo], ty: Bytes, n: Bytes) => Bool =
  match types_lookup(types, ty) {
    None => False,
    Some(d) => ctorinfo_any_named(di_ctors(d), n)
  };

// lval_try_match: the ported fragment (mirrors eval.rs::Evaluator::try_match's `Wildcard`/`Ident`/
// `Ctor`/`Tuple`/`Or` arms exactly; `Lit` refuses per FLAG-semcore-35). `site` is DROPPED (the
// FLAG-semcore-13 precedent: the differential asserts `Ok`/`Err` + the resulting `(bool, binds)`,
// never the message bytes) -- both the oracle's `L1Error` and this fn's `Bytes` message collapse to
// `Err(())` on the marshalling harness's `decode_result`.
fn lval_try_match(types: Vec[DataInfo], pat: Pattern, val: LVal, binds: Vec[Pair[Bytes, LVal]])
    => Result[Pair[Bool, Vec[Pair[Bytes, LVal]]], Bytes] =
  match pat {
    PWildcard => Ok(Pr(True, binds)),
    PIdent(n) => match val {
      LData(ty, ctor, _) => match lval_ident_is_ctor_of(types, ty, n) {
        True => match bytes_eq(ctor, n) { 0b1 => Ok(Pr(True, binds)), _ => Ok(Pr(False, binds)) },
        False => Ok(Pr(True, bind_append(binds, n, val)))
      },
      // DN-105: a `Bytes` repr value binds to a plain ident exactly like any other non-data value
      // (Rust `try_match`'s `Ident` fall-through `binds.push`) -- never a ctor-name test (a repr
      // value names no constructor).
      LReprBytes(_) => Ok(Pr(True, bind_append(binds, n, val))),
      LOpaque => Ok(Pr(True, bind_append(binds, n, val)))
    },
    PCtor(n, subs) => match val {
      LData(_, ctor, fields) => match bytes_eq(ctor, n) {
        0b1 => lval_match_zip(types, subs, fields, binds),
        _ => Ok(Pr(False, binds))
      },
      // DN-105: a `Bytes` repr value matches NO constructor pattern -- never-silent `Ok(false)`
      // (mirrors Rust's `L1Value::Repr => Ok(false)` in the `Ctor` arm; G2).
      LReprBytes(_) => Ok(Pr(False, binds)),
      LOpaque => Ok(Pr(False, binds))
    },
    // DN-105 / M-1035 (ENB-12): the `Pattern::Lit` eval-match, mirroring eval.rs::try_match's
    // `Pattern::Lit` arm for the `Bytes` (string-literal, #72) target. A `Bytes` scrutinee
    // (`LReprBytes`) is compared by BYTE CONTENT against the literal's own value (`lit_value`):
    //   - a TEXT (`Str`) literal lowers to `Val(RBytes, PlBytes(pb), _)` -> `bytes_eq(pb, b)`;
    //   - a `0x..` hex literal (`lit_value`'s `LBytes` arm) is DEFERRED (FLAG-semcore-25), so its
    //     `Err` propagates -- an explicit, never-silent refusal, not a fabricated match (G2);
    //   - any non-`Bytes` literal value vs a `Bytes` scrutinee is a never-silent `Ok(false)` (the
    //     checker keeps it off this arm anyway -- W7 repr match).
    // A `Data` value vs a literal pattern is `Ok(false)` (faithful to Rust's `Data => Ok(false)`).
    // An `LOpaque` value (a collapsed non-`Bytes` repr / `Substrate` / `Fn`) stays DEFERRED
    // (FLAG-semcore-35): its payload was dropped by the collapse, so there is nothing to compare --
    // an explicit `Err`, never a silently-wrong `Ok`.
    PLit(lit) => match val {
      LReprBytes(b) => match lit_value(lit) {
        Err(e) => Err(e),
        Ok(lv) => match lv {
          Val(RBytes, PlBytes(pb), _) => match bytes_eq(pb, b) { 0b1 => Ok(Pr(True, binds)), _ => Ok(Pr(False, binds)) },
          _ => Ok(Pr(False, binds))
        }
      },
      LData(_, _, _) => Ok(Pr(False, binds)),
      LOpaque => Err("lval_try_match: Pattern::Lit on a collapsed non-Bytes repr / Substrate / Fn value needs trusted-kernel Value equality -- deferred (FLAG-semcore-35); never silently mismatched")
    },
    PTuple(subs) => lval_try_match(types, PCtor(tuple_ctor_name(pattern_len(subs)), subs), val, binds),
    POr(_) => Err("lval_try_match: Pattern::Or must be desugared by the checker before evaluation (invariant violation) -- mirrors eval.rs::try_match's own refusal verbatim")
  };

// lval_match_zip: the `Ctor` arm's `for (sub, fv) in subs.iter().zip(fields.iter())` loop, restated
// as a fold that THREADS `binds` and short-circuits `Ok(false)` on the first sub-pattern mismatch --
// mirrors Rust's `zip` early-stop-at-the-shorter-list semantics exactly (a length mismatch between
// `subs`/`fields` never occurs in a checked program; where it would, `zip` silently stops rather
// than erroring, and so does this fold, for byte-for-byte behavioral parity).
fn lval_match_zip(types: Vec[DataInfo], subs: Vec[Pattern], fields: Vec[LVal],
    binds: Vec[Pair[Bytes, LVal]]) => Result[Pair[Bool, Vec[Pair[Bytes, LVal]]], Bytes] =
  match subs {
    Nil => Ok(Pr(True, binds)),
    Cons(sh, st) => match fields {
      Nil => Ok(Pr(True, binds)),
      Cons(fh, ft) => match lval_try_match(types, sh, fh, binds) {
        Err(e) => Err(e),
        Ok(pr) => match pr {
          Pr(matched, binds2) => match matched {
            False => Ok(Pr(False, binds2)),
            True => lval_match_zip(types, st, ft, binds2)
          }
        }
      }
    }
  };

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// M-1013 checkty PR-2 — two pure checkty.rs classifiers (Stage-5 increment continues; DN-26 §7.3).
// Both are pure structural functions over the ALREADY-ported `Ty`/`DataInfo` vocabulary — no Env,
// no PrimRegistry, no SwapEngine, no fuel/depth, no trusted-kernel `Value`, no Rust trait. Each
// mirrors its Rust oracle arm-for-arm and is differential-witnessed in `compiler_stage5_classify.rs`.
// Neither introduces a NEW surface-inexpressibility: `paradigm_name` is a flat `Ty` match (the
// established `&'static str -> Bytes` idiom, no new FLAG); `cons_list_ctors` reads the type registry
// through the already-established FLAG-semcore-4 `Vec[DataInfo]` + `types_lookup` assoc-list.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

// paradigm_name: mirrors checkty.rs::paradigm_name (checkty.rs 7175-7197) — the swap-paradigm name
// of a representation type, for the never-silent cross-paradigm framing (RFC-0001 §4.1 / M-892).
// The four swap-paradigms (Binary/Ternary/Dense/VSA) name themselves; every other `Ty` is `None` —
// `Seq`/`Bytes`/`Float` are first-class reprs but not v0 swap-paradigms (RFC-0032 D3/D4, ADR-040 §5),
// and `Data`/`Substrate`/`Var`/`Fn` are not representation types at all (RFC-0024 §3). All 11 arms
// are enumerated EXPLICITLY (no `_` wildcard), exactly as the Rust does: a future `Ty` variant must
// force a paradigm decision here, never be absorbed into a silent `None` (G2 — never-silent).
fn paradigm_name(t: Ty) => Option[Bytes] =
  match t {
    TyBinary(_) => Some("Binary"),
    TyTernary(_) => Some("Ternary"),
    TyDense(_, _) => Some("Dense"),
    TyVsa(_, _, _) => Some("VSA"),
    TySeq(_, _) => None,
    TyBytes => None,
    TyFloat => None,
    TyData(_, _) => None,
    TySubstrate(_) => None,
    TyVar(_) => None,
    TyFn(_, _) => None
  };

// cons_list_scan: checkty.rs::cons_list_ctors's `for c in &di.ctors { match c.fields.len() ... }`
// mutable-accumulator loop, restated as a threaded fold over the ctor list carrying the
// `(nil_name?, cons_name?)` pair (the FLAG-semcore-6 value-threaded collapse of the two `mut`
// locals). The field-count dispatch mirrors the Rust exactly: 0 fields -> record `nil`; exactly 2
// fields whose SECOND is the recursive `Data(name, ..)` self-reference at the type's own arity ->
// record `cons`; every other shape leaves the accumulator untouched. The 1-field and 3+-field
// shapes fall to Rust's OUTER `match c.fields.len() { _ => {} }` (the `Nil`/`Cons(_, _)` inner arms
// below); a 2-field ctor whose 2nd field is NOT the `Data(..)` self-reference falls to Rust's inner
// `if let Ty::Data(..) = &c.fields[1] { .. } else {}` (the `_` arm on `f1` below). `&c.fields[1]`
// (Rust indexing) is expressed structurally as the exactly-two-elements shape (`Cons(_, Cons(f1,
// Nil))`), destructured one level at a time per this nodule's single-level-pattern convention.
fn cons_list_scan(ctors: Vec[CtorInfo], name: Bytes, nparams: Binary{32},
    nil: Option[Bytes], cons: Option[Bytes]) => Pair[Option[Bytes], Option[Bytes]] =
  match ctors {
    Nil => Pr(nil, cons),
    Cons(c, rest) => match ci_fields(c) {
      Nil => cons_list_scan(rest, name, nparams, Some(ci_name(c)), cons),
      Cons(_, tl) => match tl {
        Nil => cons_list_scan(rest, name, nparams, nil, cons),
        Cons(f1, rest2) => match rest2 {
          Cons(_, _) => cons_list_scan(rest, name, nparams, nil, cons),
          Nil => match f1 {
            TyData(fname, fargs) => match and_(beq(fname, name), eq_u(ty_len(fargs), nparams)) {
              True => cons_list_scan(rest, name, nparams, nil, Some(ci_name(c))),
              False => cons_list_scan(rest, name, nparams, nil, cons)
            },
            _ => cons_list_scan(rest, name, nparams, nil, cons)
          }
        }
      }
    }
  };

// cons_list_ctors: mirrors checkty.rs::cons_list_ctors (checkty.rs 3592-3624) — recognizes whether
// `expected` is a 2-constructor linked-list type (one nullary "nil" ctor; one binary "cons" ctor
// whose SECOND field is the recursive `Data(name, ..)` self-reference at the type's own arity) and
// returns `(nil_name, cons_name)`; every non-conforming shape yields `None` (never a silent
// reinterpret — the `Seq{T,N}`/no-context paths stay untouched). Pure structural registry
// inspection: no Env, no evaluator, no kernel `Value`. `BTreeMap<String, DataInfo>` is the
// already-established FLAG-semcore-4 `Vec[DataInfo]` + `types_lookup` (no new deviation). The Rust
// `di.ctors.len() != 2` early-return is expressed by matching the ctor list's shape to exactly two
// elements before scanning (one level at a time per the single-level-pattern convention).
fn cons_list_ctors(types: Vec[DataInfo], expected: Ty) => Option[Pair[Bytes, Bytes]] =
  match expected {
    TyData(name, _) => match types_lookup(types, name) {
      None => None,
      Some(d) => match di_ctors(d) {
        Nil => None,
        Cons(_, r1) => match r1 {
          Nil => None,
          Cons(_, r2) => match r2 {
            Cons(_, _) => None,
            Nil => match cons_list_scan(di_ctors(d), name, names_len(di_params(d)), None, None) {
              Pr(nopt, copt) => match nopt {
                Some(n) => match copt {
                  Some(cn) => Some(Pr(n, cn)),
                  None => None
                },
                None => None
              }
            }
          }
        }
      }
    },
    _ => None
  };

// ── subst_type_param_in_typeref (checkty.rs::subst_type_param_in_typeref) ────────────────────────
// DN-54 §10 Model-A rule instantiation (M-973): substitute the rule's type parameter `param` with the
// concrete `TypeRef` throughout a `TypeRef`. A bare nullary `Named(param, [])` occurrence becomes
// `concrete`, keeping the occurrence's own guarantee if written (`T @ Exact` ↦ `C @ Exact`) — the
// `tr.guarantee.or(concrete.guarantee)` first-Some-wins merge, mirrored by `strength_or`; every
// structural form recurses; reprs / `Substrate` / `Bytes` / `Float` / VSA / dense / `Ambient` carry
// no nested type-name and are returned verbatim (the Rust `tr.clone()` — widths are a *separate*
// parameter space, DN-42, so a type parameter never appears in a width slot). Total and
// allocation-bounded by the input's size (like `subst_ty`, this structural substitution takes no
// depth budget — the Rust oracle is likewise unbudgeted). The Rust `if name == param &&
// args.is_empty()` guard is expressed one level at a time (the single-level-pattern convention): a
// `Named` first splits on its argument list, and the nullary case then compares the name. The
// argument-list recursion reuses the direct-recursive-map idiom (FLAG-semcore-5, no generic `map`).
// A complete, wildcard-free `BaseType` match (all 12 arms) — a future `BaseType` variant is a compile
// error here, never a silent pass-through (G2).

// strength_or: `Option[Strength]::or` — keep the left guarantee if present, else take the right. The
// exact semantics of `tr.guarantee.or(concrete.guarantee)`: an occurrence's own `@ g` wins over the
// concrete type's, and a bare occurrence inherits the concrete's guarantee.
fn strength_or(a: Option[Strength], b: Option[Strength]) => Option[Strength] =
  match a { Some(_) => a, None => b };

fn subst_typeref_list(trs: Vec[TypeRef], param: Bytes, concrete: TypeRef) => Vec[TypeRef] =
  match trs {
    Nil => Nil,
    Cons(h, t) => Cons(subst_type_param_in_typeref(h, param, concrete),
                       subst_typeref_list(t, param, concrete))
  };

fn subst_type_param_in_typeref(tr: TypeRef, param: Bytes, concrete: TypeRef) => TypeRef =
  match typeref_base(tr) {
    Named(name, args) => match args {
      Nil => match bytes_eq(name, param) {
        0b1 => TR(typeref_base(concrete), strength_or(typeref_guarantee(tr), typeref_guarantee(concrete))),
        _ => tr
      },
      Cons(_, _) => TR(Named(name, subst_typeref_list(args, param, concrete)), typeref_guarantee(tr))
    },
    KwSeq(elem, len) => TR(KwSeq(subst_type_param_in_typeref(elem, param, concrete), len), typeref_guarantee(tr)),
    FnArrow(a, b) => TR(FnArrow(subst_type_param_in_typeref(a, param, concrete),
                                subst_type_param_in_typeref(b, param, concrete)), typeref_guarantee(tr)),
    Tuple(elems) => TR(Tuple(subst_typeref_list(elems, param, concrete)), typeref_guarantee(tr)),
    KwBinary(_) => tr,
    KwTernary(_) => tr,
    KwDense(_, _) => tr,
    Vsa(_, _, _) => tr,
    KwSubstrate(_) => tr,
    KwBytes => tr,
    KwFloat => tr,
    Ambient(_) => tr
  };
